const NOTES_DATA = {
  "1.1.1": "## Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Know every component of your ILB lifejacket and what it does      |\n| 2.  Understand the difference between auto and manual inflation       |\n| 3.  Pre-use check procedure for the lifejacket                        |\n| 4.  Know every component of your drysuit and how to maintain it       |\n| 5.  Correctly fit your PPE and carry out a buddy check                |\n| 6.  Know the PLB, SART and AIS MOB devices carried aboard             |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### The ILB Lifejacket\n\nThe ILB lifejacket is the single most important piece of safety equipment you carry. It is designed to turn an unconscious person face-up in the water and keep their airway above the surface.\n\n:::fact KEY SPECIFICATION\n**Minimum buoyancy rating**: 150 Newtons\n**Inflation method**: CO2 gas cylinder (auto or manual)\n**Spray hood**: integrated — protects airway from spray and waves\n**Light**: water-activated — automatically illuminates on immersion\n**Whistle**: attached for attracting attention\n:::\n\n#### Inflation Systems\n\n| **System** | **How It Works** | **When It Fires** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Automatic** | Water-soluble bobbin dissolves on immersion, releasing the CO2 cylinder firing pin | On contact with water — no action needed |\n| **Manual** | Pull the red toggle to mechanically fire the CO2 cylinder | When you choose to — e.g. before entering the water deliberately |\n| **Oral top-up** | Blow into the oral inflation tube to add air | After initial inflation, to increase buoyancy or compensate for slow leak |\n\n:::warning\nIf you are **entering the water intentionally** (e.g. abandonment), you should use the **manual toggle** to inflate the lifejacket BEFORE entering. The auto head fires on contact with water and you have no reserve. If the auto system fails after an accidental immersion, pull the manual toggle immediately.\n:::\n\n#### Pre-Use Checks\n\nEvery time you put on your lifejacket, carry out these checks:\n\n:::checklist\n- CO2 cylinder is present, full (check weight), and screwed firmly into the firing mechanism\n- Auto bobbin is intact (not swollen, discoloured, or damp)\n- Oral inflation tube is functional — blow a small amount of air in and check it holds\n- Spray hood is present and correctly stowed\n- Light is present and the battery is in date\n- Whistle is attached\n- All straps, buckles, and the crutch strap are intact\n- No visible damage, tears, or abrasion to the bladder or cover\n- The lifejacket is within its service date\n:::\n\n### The Drysuit\n\nThe drysuit keeps you dry and provides thermal protection. It works by sealing at the neck, wrists, and ankles to prevent water ingress. Thermal undergarments worn beneath provide insulation.\n\n#### Components\n\n- **Latex neck seal** — forms a watertight seal around the neck. Trim carefully if too tight (trim only the outermost ring)\n- **Latex wrist seals** — watertight seal at each wrist\n- **Integrated socks or ankle seals** — keep feet dry inside boots\n- **Front entry zip** — the main waterproof zip (brass or plastic). This is the most expensive component to replace\n- **Relief zip** — for personal comfort during extended operations\n- **Spray cuffs** — additional Velcro cuffs over the wrist seals for extra protection\n- **Reflective tape** — for visibility in search conditions\n\n#### Drysuit Care\n\n:::info\nThe drysuit zip is the most critical component. If it fails, the suit floods and you lose all thermal protection and buoyancy.\n:::\n\n- **After every use**: rinse inside and out with fresh water, hang to dry (not in direct sunlight)\n- **Zip care**: keep clean, wax regularly with beeswax or zip wax, never force it, store partially open\n- **Latex seals**: keep away from UV light, oils, and solvents. Talcum powder helps prevent sticking\n- **Storage**: hang loosely or lay flat, away from heat sources and direct sunlight\n- **Never wear** rings, watches, or sharp jewellery that could puncture the seals\n- **Inspect before every use** for tears, delamination, or seal degradation\n\n### The Helmet\n\nThe crew helmet protects against head impacts during capsize, boarding, and operations in rough seas. It must fit securely and the chin strap must be fastened at all times.\n\n- **Visor**: must be DOWN when operating in surf, using fire extinguishers, handling lines under load, or during any anchoring/veering operation\n- **Intercom cable**: plugs into the console — must be removed immediately during a capsize\n- **Torch mount**: helmet-mounted torch for night operations\n\n### Personal Locator Beacon (PLB)\n\n:::acronym PLB Key Facts\nP — **Personal** — one per crew member, registered to you\nL — **Locator** — transmits your GPS position on 406 MHz to COSPAS-SARSAT satellite system\nB — **Beacon** — also transmits a 121.5 MHz homing signal for close-range direction finding\n:::\n\n:::steps\n1. Extend the aerial fully\n2. Follow the aerial down to the body of the PLB\n3. Press and hold the ON button — you will feel the on/off button first, then the aerial base\n4. A strobe light confirms activation\n5. **To deactivate**: press and hold the on/off button for more than 3 seconds\n:::\n\n:::warning\nThe PLB is **only to be activated when you are in a situation of grave and imminent danger**, you have been separated from the SAR unit, and you need immediate search and rescue assistance to establish your position and location.\n:::\n\n### AIS MOB Device\n\nThe AIS (Automatic Identification System) MOB device transmits your position to all AIS-equipped vessels within approximately 5 nautical miles. It appears on chart plotters and radar displays as a distinctive MOB symbol with your position coordinates.\n\n- Activated manually\n- Works independently of satellite systems — direct vessel-to-vessel\n- Range limited compared to PLB but provides faster local alerting\n\n### Search and Rescue Transponder (SART)\n\nThe SART is carried aboard the lifeboat (not individually). When activated, it responds to X-band (9 GHz) radar pulses from searching vessels or aircraft, creating a distinctive series of 12 dots on the searcher's radar display that form a line pointing towards the SART's position.\n\n### PPE Donning Order and Buddy Checks\n\n:::steps\n1. Thermal undergarments appropriate for conditions\n2. Drysuit — all seals correctly positioned, zip fully closed\n3. Boots\n4. Lifejacket — all straps adjusted, crutch strap fastened\n5. Helmet — chin strap fastened, intercom cable accessible\n6. Gloves\n7. **Buddy check** — visually and physically check your partner's PPE from head to toe\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**Never wear defective PPE.** Report defects or loss immediately to the LOM, DLA, or the person in charge. All PPE is provided free of charge through the RNLI Safety Store. There is no excuse for operating with damaged or incomplete equipment.\n:::\n\n### PPE Requirements by Role\n\n| **Activity** | **Minimum PPE** |\n|---|---|\n| Boat crew (all operations) | Drysuit, lifejacket, helmet, boots, gloves |\n| Shore crew (launch/recovery) | Lifejacket, helmet, boots, high-vis if appropriate |\n| Helm | As boat crew plus kill cord attached |\n| Night operations | As above plus helmet torch |\n| Anchoring/veering | Visor DOWN, approved line-handling gloves |\n",
  "1.2.1": "### 1.2.1 HAZARD AWARENESS\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify the main hazards at a lifeboat station and afloat        |\n| 2.  Understand the hierarchy of controls for managing risk            |\n| 3.  Carry out a dynamic risk assessment using the DR approach         |\n| 4.  Report hazards and near misses correctly                          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Hazard vs Risk\n\n:::fact DEFINITIONS\n**Hazard**: anything with the potential to cause harm (e.g. a wet slipway, a moving winch, a loaded rope)\n**Risk**: the likelihood that the hazard will actually cause harm, combined with the severity of that harm\n**Control measure**: an action taken to reduce the risk to an acceptable level\n:::\n\n### The Hierarchy of Controls\n\nWhen you identify a hazard, work down this hierarchy — the higher up the list, the more effective the control:\n\n:::steps\n1. **Eliminate** — remove the hazard entirely (e.g. use a crane instead of manual lifting)\n2. **Substitute** — replace with something less hazardous (e.g. water-based cleaner instead of solvent)\n3. **Engineering controls** — physically isolate people from the hazard (e.g. guards, barriers, ventilation)\n4. **Administrative controls** — change procedures, training, signage, exclusion zones\n5. **PPE** — the last line of defence — helmets, lifejackets, gloves, ear protection\n:::\n\n:::info\nPPE is always the **last resort**, not the first. If you're relying solely on PPE to manage a hazard, ask whether the hazard could be better controlled higher up the hierarchy.\n:::\n\n### Dynamic Risk Assessment\n\nA dynamic risk assessment is the continuous process of assessing risk in a changing situation. You do it every time you arrive at a scene, and you keep doing it as conditions change.\n\n:::acronym DR (Dynamic Risk)\nD — **Detect** the hazard — what could go wrong? Look, listen, think\nR — **React** to control the risk — take action proportionate to the hazard: avoid it, manage it, mitigate it\n:::\n\n> **Do the hazards and potential risks to you AND to others justify taking action? Is the benefit of action proportionate to the risk? Can you reduce or remove those hazards?**\n\n### Common Hazards at a Lifeboat Station\n\n| **Area** | **Hazards** |\n|---|---|\n| Boathouse | Moving vehicles, overhead equipment, electrical systems, slip/trip hazards, stored chemicals |\n| Slipway/launch area | Wet/uneven surfaces, moving plant, lines under load, tide and wave action |\n| Afloat — transit | Slamming, thrown around, collision, man overboard, hypothermia |\n| Afloat — on scene | Surf zone, rocks/lee shore, other vessels, casualties in the water, poor visibility |\n| Workshop/maintenance | Power tools, chemicals, working at height, manual handling |\n\n### Reporting Hazards and Near Misses\n\n:::warning\n**Even if nothing happened**, a hazard observation may trigger action to change SOPs, improve equipment, or draw attention to a potential hazard. Report everything — near misses today become incidents tomorrow.\n:::\n\nAll hazards and near misses must be reported through:\n- **Compass incident reporting system** — the RNLI's online reporting tool\n- **Verbal report** to the LOM, DLA, or person in charge as soon as practical\n- **Written record** in the station log if the online system is not immediately available\n\nThe RNLI operates a **just culture** — the focus is on learning and improvement, not blame. You will never be penalised for reporting a genuine hazard or near miss.\n",
  "1.2.2": "### 1.2.2 MANUAL HANDLING\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Recognise activities that can cause manual handling injuries      |\n| 2.  Apply the LITE methodology to assess any lifting or moving task   |\n| 3.  Use correct techniques to reduce the risk of injury               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Why This Matters\n\nManual handling injuries are among the most common in any workplace. At a lifeboat station, you'll regularly lift heavy equipment, handle casualties, move awkwardly shaped objects in confined spaces, and work in challenging environments — often under time pressure.\n\n### The LITE Assessment\n\nBefore you lift, move, push, or pull anything, run through LITE in your head. It takes seconds and could save you months of pain:\n\n:::acronym LITE\nL — **Load** — How heavy is it? What shape? Is it hot, cold, sharp, or slippery? Can you grip it safely?\nI — **Individual** — Are you fit for this lift? Any existing injuries? Do you need help or a mechanical aid?\nT — **Task** — What does the job involve? Twisting? Reaching? Repetition? How far do you need to carry it?\nE — **Environment** — Is the floor stable and dry? Is there enough space? Are there obstacles, slopes, or wind?\n:::\n\n:::info\n**Always ask first:** Can I avoid the lift entirely? Can I use a mechanical aid? Do I need another person? These are your first lines of defence.\n:::\n\n### Safe Lifting Technique\n\n:::steps\n1. **Plan the lift** — assess the load, the route, and the destination. Clear obstacles\n2. **Adopt a stable position** — feet shoulder-width apart, one foot slightly forward for balance\n3. **Get a good grip** — use the whole hand, not just fingertips\n4. **Keep the load close** to your body — loads held at arm's length exert far greater force on your spine\n5. **Bend your knees**, not your back — let your leg muscles do the work\n6. **Do NOT twist** — move your feet to change direction\n7. **Look ahead**, not down — keep your chin up\n8. **Put down, then adjust** — don't try to slide the load into position while still holding it\n:::\n\n### High-Risk Activities at a Lifeboat Station\n\n- **Lifting and moving heavy objects** — anchors, fuel cans, pump equipment\n- **Repetitive movements** — hauling in anchor warp, coiling lines\n- **Receiving deliveries** — stores, replacement parts, pyrotechnics\n- **Equipment changes** — swapping engines, moving seats\n- **Casualty handling** — recovering persons from the water, stretcher work\n- **Moving awkwardly shaped objects** — masts, aerials, carriage components\n- **Handling while seated** — requires particular care as the body is less able to absorb loads (relevant when handling equipment aboard the A85)\n\n### The Three-Point Contact Rule\n\n:::fact THREE-POINT CONTACT\nWhen embarking or disembarking any SAR unit, launch vehicle, or carriage, and when using any ladder, you must maintain **three points of contact** at all times — at least two hands and one foot, or two feet and one hand. Never overstretch. Where a ladder is used, it must be stable, secured, and footed by another person while in use.\n:::\n\n### Pushing vs Pulling\n\n:::info\n**Pushing is generally safer than pulling** as you can use your body weight to generate force. When pulling, the load is behind you — harder to control and more strain on the lower back. Where possible, push rather than pull.\n:::\n",
  "1.2.3": "### 1.2.3 HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify the risks of hazardous substances at your station        |\n| 2.  Know where to find safety information (COSHH sheets, SDSs)        |\n| 3.  Understand correct storage, signage, and disposal requirements    |\n| 4.  Know what to do in the event of a spill or exposure               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Hazardous Substances at a Lifeboat Station\n\nLifeboat stations handle a range of hazardous substances as part of routine operations:\n\n| **Substance** | **Hazard** | **Where Found** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Petrol (fuel) | Highly flammable, toxic vapour | Fuel store, SAR unit tanks |\n| Diesel | Flammable, harmful to skin | Fuel store, plant vehicles |\n| Battery acid | Corrosive, causes severe burns | Battery charging area |\n| Engine oils & hydraulic fluids | Harmful to skin, environmental pollutant | Engine maintenance area |\n| Bostik 2402 (tube adhesive) | Flammable, irritant vapour | Repair kit |\n| M-501 solvent | Flammable, harmful vapour | Repair kit |\n| Chemgene disinfectant | Irritant at high concentrations | Decontamination supplies |\n| Antifouling paint | Toxic, harmful to aquatic life | Maintenance store |\n\n### Your Three Go-To Information Sources\n\n| **Document** | **What It Tells You** | **Where to Find It** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **COSHH Assessment** | Risks specific to your station, control measures in place, who is at risk | Station safety file, Compass |\n| **Safety Data Sheet (SDS)** | Detailed chemical properties, first aid measures, firefighting advice, disposal | With the substance, station file |\n| **Packaging Labels** | Hazard warnings, PPE requirements, immediate safety info | On the container itself |\n\n:::memory\n**COSHH** = **C**ontrol **O**f **S**ubstances **H**azardous to **H**ealth. The COSHH assessment is the document that translates the general SDS information into what it means *at your specific station*.\n:::\n\n### GHS Hazard Symbols\n\nYou will see these internationally standardised diamond-shaped symbols on containers:\n\n| **Symbol** | **Meaning** | **Examples** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Flame | Flammable | Petrol, solvents, adhesives |\n| Skull & crossbones | Acute toxicity (fatal/toxic) | Concentrated chemicals |\n| Exclamation mark | Irritant/harmful | Chemgene, dilute solvents |\n| Corrosion | Corrosive — destroys skin/metals | Battery acid |\n| Health hazard | Serious long-term health effects | Some paints and solvents |\n| Environment | Hazardous to aquatic environment | Antifouling, fuel, oils |\n\n### The Spill Response Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Assess** — What has spilled? How much? Is anyone at risk? Is it spreading?\n2. **Inform** — Notify the LOM. If serious: COIR. If pollution: environmental agency\n3. **Contain & clean** — Use the station spill kit. Prevent substance reaching drains or watercourses\n4. **Dispose** — Clinical waste or hazardous waste disposal as required. **Never pour down drains**\n5. **Evaluate** — Why did it happen? How can we prevent it happening again?\n6. **Report & replenish** — Log the incident. Reorder spill kit materials through Safety Store\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**Be aware of the hazards of mixing chemicals.** Never assume two substances are safe to combine. Mixing bleach with ammonia-based cleaners produces toxic chloramine gas. Always check the COSHH assessment and safety data sheets first.\n:::\n\n### Storage Requirements\n\n- Hazardous substances must be stored in a **locked, ventilated area** with appropriate signage\n- **Flammables** must be in a fire-resistant cabinet away from ignition sources\n- **Corrosives** must be stored separately from flammables\n- All containers must be **clearly labelled** — never decant into unmarked containers\n- **Spill kit** must be readily accessible near storage areas\n- **Quantities** stored should be the minimum required\n",
  "1.2.4": "### 1.2.4 NOISE AND VIBRATION\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Recognise sources of noise and vibration at a lifeboat station    |\n| 2.  Understand the health effects of prolonged exposure               |\n| 3.  Know the legal exposure limits and action levels                  |\n| 4.  Reduce your exposure using practical control measures             |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Noise Exposure\n\n:::fact NOISE EXPOSURE LIMITS\n**Lower exposure action level**: 80 dB(A) — employer must provide hearing protection on request\n**Upper exposure action level**: 85 dB(A) — hearing protection is **mandatory**, exposure must be reduced\n**Exposure limit**: 87 dB(A) — must never be exceeded (measured at the ear, accounting for protection)\n:::\n\n| **Source** | **Approximate Level** | **Action Required** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Normal conversation | 60–65 dB | None |\n| A85 engines at cruising speed | 85–95 dB | Hearing protection mandatory |\n| A85 engines at full speed | 95–105+ dB | Hearing protection mandatory, limit exposure time |\n| Winch operations | 80–90 dB | Hearing protection available |\n| Workshop power tools | 85–100 dB | Hearing protection mandatory |\n\n:::memory\n**Quick test**: if you have to **shout to be heard** by someone 2 metres away, the noise level is likely above 85 dB and hearing protection is needed.\n:::\n\n### Whole Body Vibration (WBV)\n\n:::info\nThe Atlantic 85 uses **air-filled seats at 2.5 psi** to reduce slam impact on the crew. These seats significantly reduce but do not eliminate vibration exposure. **Check seat pressure regularly** — underinflated seats transmit more shock.\n:::\n\n**Reducing vibration exposure:**\n- Use the **correct riding posture** — feet braced, knees slightly bent, absorb impacts through your legs\n- **Avoid sitting rigidly** — a relaxed but braced posture absorbs shock better than a stiff one\n- **Speed management** — the Helm should reduce speed in rough conditions where possible\n- **Seat maintenance** — check air pressure before every exercise and shout\n- **Limit exposure time** — rotate crew positions if conducting extended transits in heavy weather\n\n:::warning\nLong-term exposure to WBV can cause **lower back pain, spinal compression, and damage to the kidneys and digestive system**. Report any persistent pain or discomfort — do not assume it is normal.\n:::\n",
  "1.2.5": "### 1.2.5 FIRE SAFETY\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Explain the fire triangle and how removing any element extinguishes a fire |\n| 2.  Identify fire classes and match the correct extinguisher to each  |\n| 3.  Know the considerations before tackling a fire                    |\n| 4.  Locate escape routes and muster points at your station            |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### The Fire Triangle\n\nEvery fire needs three things to burn. **Remove any one of them and the fire goes out.**\n\n:::diagram The Fire Triangle\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 300 240\" style=\"max-width:280px\">\n<polygon points=\"150,20 30,220 270,220\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#E86826\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"150\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"800\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">HEAT</text>\n<text x=\"70\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"800\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">FUEL</text>\n<text x=\"230\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"800\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">OXYGEN</text>\n<text x=\"150\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">FIRE</text>\n<text x=\"150\" y=\"158\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Remove any one element</text>\n<text x=\"150\" y=\"172\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">to extinguish the fire</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\nA fourth element is the **chemical chain reaction** between fuel, oxygen, and heat that sustains the fire while all three are present.\n\n### Fire Classes and Extinguisher Types\n\n| **Class** | **Fuel Type** | **Use** | **NEVER Use** |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| A | Wood, paper, material | Water (cools), Foam, Powder | — |\n| B | Flammable liquids (petrol, diesel) | Foam (smothers), CO2, Powder | **NEVER Water** — spreads burning liquid |\n| C | Gases | Powder only | NEVER Water, Foam, or CO2 |\n| D | Metals | Specialist dry powder only | **NEVER Water** — violent reaction |\n| Electrical | Radar, SIMS, electronics | CO2 or Powder (both non-conductive) | **NEVER Water or Foam** — electrocution risk |\n| F | Cooking oils/fats | Specialist wet chemical only | **NEVER Water** — explosive steam reaction |\n\n:::fact MOST LIKELY FIRES ON THE A85\n**Class B** (petrol fuel — highly flammable) and **Electrical** (radar, SIMS, navigation electronics). The A85 carries a **0.5kg CO2 extinguisher** with approximately **2–3 seconds** of effective discharge.\n:::\n\n### Using a Fire Extinguisher — PASS\n\n:::acronym PASS\nP — **Pull** the pin (or remove the safety clip)\nA — **Aim** the nozzle at the BASE of the fire, not the flames\nS — **Squeeze** the handle to discharge\nS — **Sweep** from side to side across the base of the fire\n:::\n\n### Before Tackling a Fire — STOP and THINK\n\n:::checklist\n- Am I safe? Is my escape route clear?\n- Are other people safe? Have they been alerted?\n- Can I realistically fight this fire, or is it already too big?\n- Would it be safer to evacuate and call for help?\n- Do I know the right extinguisher type for this fire?\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**Personal safety comes first.** A fire extinguisher is designed for small, contained fires. If you have any doubt at all, evacuate immediately and call for help. RNLI crew PPE is **NOT fire resistant**.\n:::\n\n### A85 Fire Procedures\n\n#### Engine Fire\n1. Stop the engine by moving the switch to OFF, or pull kill cord\n2. Disconnect the fuel supply under the crew bench seat\n3. Turn the helm to make the fire port easily accessible\n4. Remove the fire port bung from the engine hood by peeling back the ring pull\n5. Discharge a **3-second burst** of the extinguisher into the fire port\n6. A second burst can be used if required (on second burst, empty entire contents)\n7. Do NOT restart the engine — await assistance\n8. Follow appropriate radio procedure by DSC and voice\n\n#### Electrical Fire\n1. Turn off main **isolator switches** if safe to do so\n2. Discharge a **3-second burst** into the electrical box\n3. If required, fully discharge the extinguisher into the electrical box\n4. Follow appropriate radio procedure using handheld VHF\n\n:::warning\n**Highly flammable fuel onboard. Consider early abandonment.** If the extinguisher fails to control the fire, there is no second chance. The decision to abandon is the Helm's and must not be delayed.\n:::\n\n### Key Safety Points\n\n- Know the sound of your station's **fire alarm**\n- Escape routes and fire exits must be **clear and unobstructed at all times**\n- **Hot gas rises** — staying low keeps you in the freshest environment\n- Burning plastics can release **phosgene gas** — causes eye irritation and sore throat at low levels; pulmonary oedema and death at higher levels\n- **One breath** of superheated gas can kill by burning the respiratory tract\n- Never hang clothing over or near heating equipment\n- Helmet **visor DOWN** when using any fire extinguisher\n\n### Raising the Alarm\n\nIf no fire alarm is present on the SAR unit: **shout \"FIRE\" clearly** to all crew. The importance of communicating the existence and location of the fire to others is paramount.\n\n:::memory\n**Water = Cools** (removes heat) · **Foam = Smothers** (removes oxygen) · **CO2 = Displaces** (removes oxygen, leaves no residue) · **Powder = Versatile** (breaks chemical reaction, but reduces visibility)\n:::\n",
  "1.2.6": "### 1.2.6 PERSONAL SAFETY AND WELLBEING\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Understand your personal safety obligations under H&S legislation |\n| 2.  Know how to access mental health and wellbeing support            |\n| 3.  Recognise signs of stress and trauma in yourself and others       |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Your Safety Responsibilities\n\nAs a volunteer, you have the **same health and safety rights** as any employee. The RNLI has a duty to protect you, and you have a duty to protect yourself and others.\n\n**Your obligations:**\n- Take reasonable care for your own safety and that of others\n- Co-operate with safety procedures and instructions\n- Report hazards, defects, near misses, and incidents\n- Use PPE provided and report any defects\n- Do not undertake any task you have not been trained for\n- **Do not operate if unfit** — fatigue, alcohol, medication, illness, or emotional distress\n\n:::info\n**You do not need to suffer in silence.** If a service or training exercise causes you distress — whether at the time or weeks later — the RNLI provides confidential support services. Your mental health is just as important as your physical safety.\n:::\n\n### Mental Health and Wellbeing\n\nRNLI volunteers are regularly exposed to traumatic incidents. This is not something you can always prepare for, and reactions are completely normal.\n\n**Signs to watch for in yourself and others:**\n- Difficulty sleeping, nightmares, or intrusive thoughts\n- Irritability, withdrawal, or mood changes\n- Increased alcohol consumption or appetite changes\n- Loss of concentration or motivation\n- Feeling emotionally numb or detached\n- Re-living the event or avoiding reminders of it\n\n### Support Available\n\n| **Service** | **What It Offers** | **How to Access** |\n|---|---|---|\n| CiC (Critical Incident Care) | Peer support from trained RNLI volunteers who understand the context | Through your LOM or Regional team |\n| RNLI Wellbeing Hub | Self-help resources, information, and signposting | Compass (RNLI intranet) |\n| Confidential counselling | Professional therapy sessions — free and confidential | Through the RNLI wellbeing team |\n| Your LOM/DLA | First point of contact for any welfare concern | Speak directly at any time |\n\n:::warning\nIf you feel you are not physically or mentally fit to respond to a shout, **do not go**. This is not a sign of weakness — it is a sign of good judgment. A crew member who is not fit to operate is a liability to themselves and the rest of the crew.\n:::\n",
  "1.2.7": "### 1.2.7 SAFE TO THE SHOUT\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Respond safely to a pager alert without putting yourself or others at risk |\n| 2.  Carry out a self-assessment before responding                     |\n| 3.  Drive safely and legally to the station                           |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### When the Pager Goes Off\n\n:::warning\n**Get to the station quickly, but get there safely.** There is no point arriving at the station if you create another casualty or cause a traffic accident in the process.\n:::\n\n### Self-Assessment Before Responding\n\nBefore you respond to a shout, ask yourself honestly:\n\n:::checklist\n- Am I fit to operate? (Not fatigued, ill, or emotionally distressed)\n- Am I free from alcohol? (RNLI zero-tolerance policy applies)\n- Am I free from medication that could affect my performance?\n- Am I in a safe position to leave? (Not mid-task with dangerous equipment)\n- Can I get to the station safely? (Road conditions, weather, distance)\n:::\n\n:::fact RNLI ALCOHOL POLICY\n**Zero tolerance.** If you have consumed **any** alcohol, you must not respond. The effects of alcohol are amplified by cold, fatigue, and motion — even small amounts significantly impair judgment, reaction time, and physical performance afloat.\n:::\n\n### Driving to the Station\n\n- Obey **all traffic laws** — you have NO legal exemption to break speed limits, jump red lights, or drive dangerously\n- Use **headlights** even during the day for visibility\n- Be especially cautious at junctions, pedestrian crossings, and near schools\n- If conditions are poor (ice, fog, heavy rain), **slow down** — arriving 2 minutes late is better than not arriving at all\n- Park at the station **without blocking access** for other crew, vehicles, or plant\n\n### Station-Specific: Littlestone\n\n:::info\nLittlestone Lifeboat Station is located on the seafront at Coast Drive. Park in the **station car park** or along the road without blocking access for other crew, the tractor, or emergency services. The road is residential — **drive slowly** especially at night when responding to a shout. Be aware of pedestrians on the promenade.\n:::\n\n### Arriving at the Station\n\n:::steps\n1. Arrive and report to the person in charge (typically the Helm or LOM/DLA)\n2. Check the **weather forecast and shout information** (what we're going to, conditions)\n3. **Don PPE** in the correct order — do not rush this\n4. Conduct a **buddy check** with another crew member\n5. Attend the **SMEAC briefing** by the Helm if time allows\n6. Take your station as directed by the person in charge\n:::\n",
  "1.3.1": "## SAR Unit Layout — Atlantic 85\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Name and locate every fitting, stowage, and equipment item       |\n| 2.  Understand vessel terminology (bow, stern, beam, quarter)         |\n| 3.  Know what each piece of equipment is for and how to access it     |\n| 4.  Carry out a Safe to Go Afloat equipment check                     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::diagram Atlantic 85 — Key Positions (plan view)\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 400 220\" style=\"max-width:400px\">\n<path d=\"M80,110 Q80,30 200,20 Q320,30 320,110 L320,190 Q320,205 300,205 L100,205 Q80,205 80,190 Z\" fill=\"#E8EBED\" stroke=\"#002B5C\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"15\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">BOW</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"218\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">STERN</text>\n<text x=\"55\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">PORT</text>\n<text x=\"345\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">STBD</text>\n<rect x=\"155\" y=\"65\" width=\"90\" height=\"55\" fill=\"#002B5C\" rx=\"6\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">CONSOLE</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#B8D4F0\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Helm, SIMS, VHF</text>\n<rect x=\"140\" y=\"40\" width=\"25\" height=\"18\" fill=\"#F4A261\" rx=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"152\" y=\"52\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S1</text>\n<rect x=\"235\" y=\"40\" width=\"25\" height=\"18\" fill=\"#F4A261\" rx=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"247\" y=\"52\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S2</text>\n<rect x=\"140\" y=\"128\" width=\"25\" height=\"18\" fill=\"#F4A261\" rx=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"152\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S3</text>\n<rect x=\"235\" y=\"128\" width=\"25\" height=\"18\" fill=\"#F4A261\" rx=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"247\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S4</text>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"38\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Anchor locker</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"175\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">A-frame / tow bollard</text>\n<rect x=\"160\" y=\"158\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#374151\" rx=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"171\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">A-FRAME</text>\n<circle cx=\"170\" cy=\"195\" r=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\"/>\n<text x=\"170\" y=\"198\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">P</text>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"195\" r=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\"/>\n<text x=\"230\" y=\"198\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"210\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"6\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Engines</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::fact KEY DIMENSIONS\n**Length overall**: 8.44m (27'8\") · **Beam**: 2.85m (9'4\") · **Draught**: ~0.5m\n**Displacement**: approx 2.4 tonnes · **Crew**: 3 (min 3, max 4)\n**Engines**: Twin Yamaha outboards · **Max speed**: ~35 knots · **Range**: ~2.5 hours at full speed\n:::\n\n---\n\n**Vessel Terminology**\n\nBefore you can learn the layout, you need the language. These terms are\nused constantly:\n\n  **Term**         **Meaning**\n\n  Bow              The front of the vessel\n\n  Stern            The rear of the vessel\n\n  Port             The left side when facing forward (red navigation\n                   light)\n\n  Starboard        The right side when facing forward (green navigation\n                   light)\n\n  Beam             The widest point of the vessel; also the direction at\n                   right angles to the centreline\n\n  Quarter          The area between the beam and the stern on each side\n\n  Gunwale          The upper edge of the vessel's side\n\n  Transom          The flat surface at the stern where the engines are\n                   mounted\n\n  Fore and aft     Towards the bow and towards the stern respectively\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.3.1a, p.63*\n\n**Atlantic 85 Technical Specification**\n\n  **Item**          **Location**     **Purpose / Notes**\n\n  Bow fairlead      Bow              Leads ropes forward of the cleats to\n                                     reduce chafing on sponsons. MUST be\n                                     used when anchoring and towing\n                                     alongside\n\n  Anchor locker     Forward deck     Stows the delta anchor, 9 metres of\n                                     chain, and 82 metres of warp. Has\n                                     drain holes for washout\n\n  Anchor line reel  Adjacent to      Stores the anchor warp on a reel for\n                    locker           controlled deployment\n\n  Bailey hatches    Forward deck (3  Allow inspection of hull under-deck\n                    hatches)         void spaces. The centre/most-forward\n                                     hatch (largest) can be removed ashore\n                                     to fill ballast tank via hose. The\n                                     two smaller side hatches are for\n                                     inspection ONLY — do NOT fill these\n                                     with water\n\n  Sea anchor        Forward, with    Spring latch opens at the stowage.\n  stowage           spring latch     Can be manually deployed from here,\n                                     or deployed via rope down the\n                                     starboard side, or via the handle on\n                                     the transom after capsize\n\n  Foot straps       Forward deck     Crew foot restraints for safe\n                                     positioning\n\n  General-purpose   Forward          Spare line for various operational\n  line stowage                       uses\n\n**Midships (Crew and Helm Area)**\n\n  **Hazard**    **Specific Risk on the      **How to Minimise**\n                A85**                       \n\n  Radar         Radiation from spinning     Never be near the antenna when\n                transceiver; wires and      transmitting. Be aware of\n                lines (especially during    aerial positions\n                helicopter operations)      \n\n  Aerials       Electrocution, eye injury,  Never hold onto any aerial. MF\n                broken fibreglass, RF burns aerials can produce high\n                                            voltages when transmitting\n\n  Fuel          Fire, dermatitis, fume      Know location of extinguisher\n                inhalation, ingestion.      (helm's starboard foot strap).\n                Petrol is highly flammable  No naked flames. Understand\n                                            ventilation\n\n  Slips, trips, Injury to personnel, damage Hold on at all times. Good\n  falls         to equipment                housekeeping. Remain seated\n                                            when boat is in motion. Use\n                                            foot straps\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.3.1a, pp.63 — 64*\n\n**Crew Seating and Safe Positioning**\n\nThe Atlantic 85 has air-filled seats designed to reduce the effects of\nslam impacts on the spine. The correct operating pressure is 2.5 psi — \nseats should be regularly checked.\n\nSafe crew positioning:\n\n-   Feet in foot straps at all times\n\n-   Seats straddled to prevent spinal injury\n\n-   Hold grab rails and steering wheel with thumbs on TOP to prevent\n    thumb breakage\n\n-   Remain seated when the boat is in motion. If you must move, inform\n    the helm first so speed can be reduced\n\n-   If the 4th seat is occupied, the MOB cord MUST be worn (attached to\n    right leg)\n\n-   In heavy weather: all loose items secured, additional thermal layers\n    and helmet on, crew seated and correctly restrained\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, pp.13 — 14*\n\n**Before Any Launch**\n\nBefore any form of launch, the following must be carried out (this is\nwhat you will see happening around you on your first afloat training):\n\n-   Full SMEAC briefing with all crew and shore crew\n\n-   Weather within operating capabilities of the A85 (daylight: Force 7;\n    darkness: Force 6)\n\n-   Launch site appropriate for prevailing conditions\n\n-   Authorisation from a Launch Authority (LOM or DLA)\n\n-   Navigation aids on: radar, SIMS set up correctly, charts available\n\n-   Hatches closed, kit stowed, charger disconnected, battery isolators\n    ON\n\n-   Equipment returned to stowage: handheld radio, salvage pump, etc.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 3, p.32*\n\n\n:::warning\n**Post recovery: engines MUST be flushed with fresh water every time\nafter saltwater use. Salt water corrodes the aluminium cooling\npassages and will cause overheating and destroy the engine from the\ninside out. Use the water tanks on the carriage or a hose. Do NOT\nflush in freezing temperatures if the boat is stored outside, as the\nfresh water may freeze.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 3, p.36*\n",
  "1.4.1": "### 1.4.1 ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES 1\n\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Identify key station personnel and their roles                    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 6.  Understand the chain of command and who you report to             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 7.  Know how to use the SMEAC briefing and SPEP debrief formats       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 8.  Understand your own limitations and attendance requirements       |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Who's Who at the Station**\n\nA lifeboat station is a team operation. Understanding who does what — \nand who you report to — is essential for safe and efficient\noperations.\n\n  **Role**              **Responsibility**\n\n  Lifeboat Operations   Manages all operational activities, authorises\n  Manager (LOM)         launches, day-to-day station management\n\n  Deputy Launching      Deputises for the LOM when unavailable\n  Authority (DLA)       \n\n  Helm                  Takes command of the Atlantic 85 at sea;\n                        safeguards crew and rescues those in danger\n\n  Head Launcher         Directs shore operations during launch/recovery;\n                        ensures safety of all in the vicinity\n\n  Plant Operator / LVD  Safe operation of the launch vehicle under\n                        direction of Head Launcher\n\n  Shore Crew (Working   Directly assist launch/recovery: passing strops,\n  Crew)                 fitting lines, handling equipment\n\n  Shore Crew (Marshals) Ensure no unauthorised persons enter the\n                        exclusion zone; direct traffic and public\n\n  Lifeboat Training     Ensures training requirements are met, arranges\n  Coordinator           assessments, maintains records\n\n  Mechanic              Responsible for engines and equipment; planned\n                        maintenance programme\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, pp.101 — 102*\n\n\n:::info\n**Shore crew volunteers report to the Head Launcher. If there is no\nHead Launcher, report to the LOM. Ultimately, all volunteers report to\nthe LOM.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, p.102*\n\n**The SMEAC Briefing**\n\nBefore every launch — whether on service or exercise — a briefing\nmust take place. The RNLI uses the SMEAC format:\n\n  **Letter**   **Stands For**      **What It Covers**\n\n  S            Situation           What are the facts? Big picture summary\n\n  M            Mission             What is the objective? What are we going\n                                   to do?\n\n  E            Execution           How are we going to do this? Allocate\n                                   roles and responsibilities\n\n  A            Administration      What support do you need? Other assets,\n                                   extra equipment, crew welfare\n\n  C            Command, Comms &    Pause — is there a reason this plan\n               Confirmation        won't work? What have I missed?\n\n*Source: ILB Decision Support Check Cards TP-LB-28, Card 2; TP-LB-01, p.105*\n\n**The SPEP Debrief**\n\nAfter every operation, a debrief is held using the SPEP format:\n\n  **Letter**   **Stands For**  **Questions to Ask**\n\n  S            Safety          What did we do well? What would we change to\n                               be safer next time?\n\n  P            People          Is everyone OK? Physical health, mental\n                               health, crew welfare, public\n\n  E            Equipment       Did everything perform as expected? Any\n                               defects to report?\n\n  P            Performance     Did we achieve what we intended? What could\n                               we do differently? Does anyone else need to\n                               be informed?\n\n*Source: ILB Decision Support Check Cards TP-LB-28, Card 6*\n\n**Attendance and Currency Requirements**\n\nThe RNLI sets specific attendance and currency requirements. These are\nnot vague guidelines — they are monitored and enforced:\n\n  **Requirement**         **Detail**\n\n  Minimum attendance      12 attendances per year, per role held\n\n  Of which exercises      At least 8 of the 12 must be exercises\n                          (services count for the remainder)\n\n  Assessor Trainer        At least one within the preceding 3 years\n  exercise                \n\n  Currency activity cycle Each of the 6 shore crew currency activities\n                          must be completed at least once every 18 months\n\n  Overall assessment      Currency is assessed over a rolling 5-year\n  period                  period by Operational Management, ALM, and LOM\n\n  Training plan           Overall training plan should be completed\n  completion              within 2 years\n\n  Probation period        12 months for your first volunteer role (led by\n                          LOM or nominated mentor)\n\n  Overdue activities      If you exceed the 18-month period, you appear\n                          as 'overdue' on the station dashboard. A\n                          3-month extension may be granted before\n                          remedial action\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 14, p.340; TP-OCF-03, pp.6 — 8 and p.31; TP-OCF-02, p.20*\n\n**The Six Shore Crew Currency Activities**\n\nTo maintain your Shore Crew Pass Out, you must complete all six of these\nactivities within every 18-month cycle:\n\n-   Activity 1 — PPE, Equipment and Pyrotechnics\n\n-   Activity 2 — Launch SAR Unit (High Water)\n\n-   Activity 3 — Launch SAR Unit (Low Water)\n\n-   Activity 4 — Recover SAR Unit (High Water)\n\n-   Activity 5 — Recover SAR Unit (Low Water)\n\n-   Activity 6 — Emergency Procedures\n\nAt co-located stations (stations with more than one SAR unit type), a\nseparate set of activities is required for each SAR unit. Currency can\nalso be maintained through operational services — if you perform your\nrole correctly on a shout, the SAR unit commander may mark it as\ncompleting the relevant activity.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-03, p.31; TP-OCF-01, p.10*\n\n**Limitations**\n\nYou must not exceed the boundaries of your training and role. The\nconsequences of doing so include confusion, conflict, unrealistic\nexpectations, and risk to the safety of yourself and others. If you are\nunable to respond to the pager for any reason, inform the LOM, station\nmanager, launch authority, SAR unit commander, or head launcher as soon\nas possible. Use RCAMS (RNLI Central Alerting and Messaging System) if\napplicable. Maintaining appropriate manning numbers depends on everyone\ncommunicating their availability.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.1b, pp.69 — 70; TP-LB-01, p.100*\n\n#### Launch Authority Perspective\n\nThe key difference at LA level is that you sit above the operational\nroles in terms of launch authority, but you do not command the launch or\nrecovery itself. You support the LOM in keeping the station running\nsafely and efficiently. You must understand every role at the station\n(LOM, DLA, Helm, Head Launcher, Plant Operator, Shore Crew, Mechanic,\nLTC) because you need to assess whether the right people are available\nbefore authorising a launch.\n\n#### Tier 1 Crew Perspective\n\nThis module is taught in full in the Shore Crew Stage 2 guide. At Tier 1\nlevel, you now understand all station roles from direct experience. You\nmust know the SMEAC briefing format, the SPEP debrief format, the\ncommunications chain for normal and emergency situations, your\nattendance and currency requirements (12 attendances per year, minimum 8\nexercises, 18-month currency cycle), and the consequences of exceeding\nyour role's limitations.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.1, pp.68 — 70*\n",
  "1.4.2": "### 1.4.2 ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES (NAVIGATOR)\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Understand the navigator's role and responsibilities under the    |\n|     direction of the Helm                                             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 2.  Know the RNLI navigation safety policy and the Navigation Safety  |\n|     SOP                                                               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 3.  Manage Position and Intended Movement (PIM) reports               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 4.  Ensure all chart and navigation resources are current and in date |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nUnder the direction of the person in command, you must ensure the craft\nis appropriately and safely navigated at all times. You must maintain\nawareness of the vessel's location at all times with position fixing\nwhere and when appropriate. Your responsibilities include:\n\n-   Maintaining the navigation plot on both paper and electronic charts\n\n-   Providing the Helm with course to steer, speed recommendations, and\n    hazard warnings\n\n-   Monitoring depth, cross-track error, and waypoint proximity\n\n-   Making PIM reports to the Coastguard at the required intervals\n    (every 15 minutes for ILB on service/exercise)\n\n-   Ensuring all charts are current and corrected (check bottom-left\n    corner for last update date)\n\n-   Knowing where to find chart updates and who is responsible (COIR,\n    LOM, Helm)\n\n-   Understanding the dangers of using an uncorrected chart: buoy\n    positions may have moved, lights may have changed, new hazards may\n    exist, depths may be wrong\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.2, p.71; Task 7.1.2a, p.230*\n\n**Position and Intended Movement (PIM)**\n\nA PIM report is a transmission from the lifeboat to the Coastguard\nreporting the current position and intended movement of the SAR unit.\nPIM reports are an essential part of monitoring the safety of lifeboat\ncrew and allowing the Coastguard to maintain visibility of assets.\nFrequency is as per operational procedures — for ILBs, every 15\nminutes on service or exercise.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.2, p.71; GU1113*\n",
  "1.4.3": "### 1.4.3 ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES (COMMAND)\n\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Understand the Head Launcher's specific responsibilities and \\|   |\n|     authority                                                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 2.  Know the three levels of situational awareness and how to apply   |\n|     them                                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 3.  Conduct dynamic risk assessments continuously throughout          |\n|     operations                                                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 4.  Brief and debrief effectively using SMEAC and SPEP                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Know the policies, SOPs, LOPs, and EOPs that govern your role     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Your Role as Head Launcher**\n\nThe Head Launcher takes charge of all operations connected with the\nlaunching and recovery of the SAR unit on the shore side. You oversee a\nteam of shore crew, which may include specialist roles such as vehicle\nand plant operators. You are also responsible to the LTC for the shore\ncrew training package. You and the Helm decide jointly (in consultation\nwith the LA) on the place and method of launch and recovery.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, p.101*\n\nThe Head Launcher and Helm operate as co-equal commanders, each\nresponsible for their own domain. You command everything shore-side: the\nshore crew, the marshals, the plant operator (while ashore), and the\nsafety of everyone in the vicinity. The Helm commands everything afloat\nand takes control of the plant operator once the vehicle enters the\nwater. Command passes back and forth between you depending on the phase\nof the operation:\n\n  **Phase**        **Who Commands** **What Happens**\n\n  Boathouse to     HEAD LAUNCHER    You command the LVD, shore crew, and\n  launch site                       marshals. You direct the transit,\n                                    stops, and positioning. Helm gives\n                                    the SMEAC briefing but you control\n                                    the movement of the rig\n\n  At the water's H ANDOVER Y        ou perform a radio check on CH31 with\n  edge                              the tractor, then pass control to the\n                                    Helm for the launch. The Helm now\n                                    directs the LVD into the water\n\n  Launch and       HELM             Helm directs the LVD in the water and\n  afloat                            commands the boat. You manage the\n                                    shore crew to secure equipment and\n                                    escort the rig back\n\n  Recovery         HELM             Helm contacts the boathouse, agrees\n  approach                          site and method with you and the LVD.\n                                    Helm directs the LVD in the water for\n                                    the recovery\n\n  After boat       HEAD LAUNCHER    You assume control from the LVD for\n  recovered                         the transit back to the boathouse.\n                                    You manage washdown, crew\n                                    disembarkation, task assignment, and\n                                    housing the rig\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 3, pp.129 — 130; Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0, pp.2 — 3; A85 Launch & Recovery SOP V7.0, p.3*\n\n**Situational Awareness — The Three Levels**\n\nAs a command role, you must maintain situational awareness at all times.\nThe Training Standards define three levels, each building on the last:\n\n  **Type**          **What It Is**                **Littlestone Examples**\n\n  SOP (Standard     The standard way of operating 85-SOP-Launch and\n  Operating         in normal circumstances.      Recovery V7.0\n  Procedure)        Blue-bordered. Produced       \n                    centrally by RNLI             \n\n  LOP (Local        Station-specific procedures   Littlestone 002 B-Class\n  Operating         where the SOP cannot be       Launch and Recovery LOP\n  Procedure)        followed due to local         V1.0; Littlestone 002\n                    conditions, or where no SOP   Local Knowledge LOP V4.0\n                    exists. Yellow-bordered.      \n                    Compiled locally, verified by \n                    coastal staff                 \n\n  EOP (Emergency    Procedures for emergency      85-EOP-MB4H Bendy + A85\n  Operating         situations. Red-bordered      DoDo Release + Winch\n  Procedure)                                      V3.0; Launch and\n                                                  Recovery Emergency EOP\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, p.103; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.3b, p.73*\n\n**Shore Crew Selection**\n\nWhen selecting shore crew for an operation, you must consider:\n\n-   All required roles filled — do you have enough people for working\n    crew AND marshals?\n\n-   Physical ability — can each person physically perform the tasks\n    required?\n\n-   Experience — are less experienced crew paired with more\n    experienced crew?\n\n-   Crew competence — is each person passed out for their role?\n\n-   Task-specific competence — does the specific task (e.g. net\n    rigging) require particular skill?\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.2.3a, p.116*\n\n\n:::warning\n**It is better to use an alternative launch method than to risk injury\nor damage through insufficient crew numbers. If you do not have enough\npeople to safely conduct normal launch and recovery, use an\nalternative approved method.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 3, p.129*\n\n#### Launch Authority Perspective\n\nThe three levels of situational awareness (Perception, Comprehension,\nProjection) and the principles of dynamic risk assessment are taught in\nfull in the Head Launcher Stage 3 guide. As LA, your application of\nthese is different — you are not watching the rig move down the beach,\nyou are assessing information from the Coastguard, weather data, and\ncrew availability to build a picture of whether a launch is appropriate.\nYour projection is not about where the tide will be in 20 minutes, but\nabout whether conditions will allow a safe recovery after a 2-hour\nservice.\n\n#### Helm Command Perspective\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Lead and command all operational activity afloat                  |\n|                                                                       |\n| 2.  Brief and debrief using SMEAC and SPEP                            |\n|                                                                       |\n| 3.  Conduct dynamic risk assessments continuously                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 4.  Manage crew fatigue, motivation, and individual limitations       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Know and apply all relevant EOPs, SOPs, and LOPs                  |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nThis module is taught in the Head Launcher guide from the ashore\nperspective. As Helm, the same principles apply afloat, but the stakes\nare higher — you are making decisions under way, in conditions, with\nlimited time to think. The three levels of situational awareness\n(Perception, Comprehension, Projection) taught in the Head Launcher\nguide apply directly: you must perceive what is happening around the\nboat (weather, sea state, crew condition, casualty status), comprehend\nwhat it means for the operation (are conditions deteriorating? is the\ncrew fatigued? is the tow holding?), and project what will happen next\n(will we have enough fuel? will conditions allow recovery? will the\ncasualty survive the transit to safe haven?).\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.4.3, pp.72 — 75; TP-OCF-04, pp.10 — 11*\n",
  "1.5.1": "### 1.5.1 SAR UNIT FIREFIGHTING\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 6.  Know the fire types encountered on the Atlantic 85 (Class B fuel  |\n|     and Electrical)                                                   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 7.  Know the location and operation of the A85's fire extinguisher \\| |\n|                                                                       |\n| 8.  Follow the correct sequence of actions on discovering a fire      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 9.  Know when and how to evacuate, muster equipment, and communicate  |\n|                                                                       |\n| 10. Understand RNLI policy on fighting fires on other vessels         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Fire Types on the Atlantic 85**\n\nOn the Atlantic 85, you will encounter two types of fire: Class B\n(flammable liquid — petrol fuel) and Electrical (radar, SIMS,\nelectronic navigation equipment, console wiring). The A85 carries a\nsingle 0.5kg CO2 fire extinguisher, located in front of the helm's\nstarboard foot strap. It has approximately 2 — 3 seconds of effective\ndischarge time. CO2 is used because it is non-conductive (safe on\nelectrical fires), displaces oxygen, and leaves no residue on\nelectronics.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, pp.12 — 13; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.5.1a, p.75*\n\n**Atlantic 85 Fire Procedures**\n\n  **Fire Location** **Action**\n\n  Engine fire       1\\. Alert the helm. 2. Ensure vessel is in a safe\n                    area. 3. Do NOT stop engine. 4. Helm turns engine\n                    towards the sponson. 5. Discharge extinguisher\n                    completely into the cowl opening of the running\n                    engine. 6. Engine will stall — do not remove engine\n                    hood. Do not restart. 7. Assess if fire is\n                    extinguished\n\n  Electrical fire   1\\. Assess if safe to tackle. 2. Turn off power and\n  in console        isolate by turning the two yellow handles. 3. Fire\n                    the extinguisher into the internal space. 4. Close\n                    the door\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, pp.12 — 13*\n\n\n:::info\n**The Atlantic 85 carries highly flammable petrol fuel onboard.\nConsider early abandonment in the event of any fire that cannot be\nimmediately controlled. Abandonment is a last resort at sea, but the\nfirst resort ashore.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.12; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.5.2a, p.79*\n\n**Initial Actions on Discovering Any Fire**\n\n-   Shout 'FIRE, FIRE, FIRE' — raise the alarm\n\n-   Communicate the existence and location of the fire: verbally, by\n    alarms, by radio to Coastguard (Mayday and DSC if necessary), by\n    telephone to Fire and Rescue Service\n\n-   Isolate fuel and air: locate and close fire flaps/covers, close fuel\n    stops/taps\n\n-   The person in command decides whether to shut down engines\n    (consider: shallows, lee shore, casualty transfer, alongside other\n    vessels, location of fire)\n\n-   If safe to tackle, use the correct extinguisher. If not safe,\n    evacuate — close hatches and doors behind you\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 1.5.1a — b, pp.75 — 77; TP-LB-01, p.107*\n\n**Evacuation and Muster**\n\nIf the fire cannot be controlled, evacuate to a muster point. If afloat,\nthis means the upwind side of the vessel. Assemble and await\ninstructions. Equipment to muster (if safe to collect):\n\n-   Flares, VHF radio, GPS, torch\n\n-   Water, warm clothing, casualty care kit\n\n-   Consider ditching O2, Entonox, and unused extinguishers if safe to\n    do so\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.5.1b, p.77*\n\n**RNLI Firefighting Policy**\n\n\n:::warning\n**RNLI lifeboats and boathouses are not equipped and crew are not\ntrained to fight fires on any vessels or premises other than their\nown. Our equipment is only there to aid escape. Our PPE is not fire\nresistant. A person should only attack a fire when trained to do so\nand if it enhances safety without too much personal risk.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 1, p.97*\n",
  "1.5.2": "### 1.5.2 MANAGE SAR UNIT FIREFIGHTING\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 6.  Direct the crew through both fire procedures (engine and          |\n|     electrical)                                                       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 7.  Make the decision to abandon if the fire cannot be controlled     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 8.  Manage firefighting on the A85 while maintaining situational      |\n|     awareness of the vessel's position and crew safety                |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nThe fire procedures (engine and electrical) are taught in full in the\nSafe to Go on a Service guide (Stage 3) and the ILB Decision Support\nCheck Cards (EOP 2). As Helm, your role is to manage the situation, not\njust execute the procedure. This means:\n\n-   Positioning the vessel safely before crew tackle the fire — assess\n    wind direction (fire should be downwind of crew), sea room,\n    proximity to hazards\n\n-   Directing specific crew members to specific tasks: one to the\n    extinguisher, one to monitor, one to prepare for abandonment\n\n-   Making the abandonment decision if the fire is not controlled after\n    the extinguisher is discharged — the A85 carries petrol, and you\n    have 2 — 3 seconds of CO2. If it fails, there is no second chance\n    with the same type of extinguisher\n\n-   Communicating with the Coastguard throughout: DSC distress alert,\n    voice Mayday if abandoning, position report, number of persons on\n    board\n\n-   Managing post-fire: if the fire is extinguished, monitoring for\n    re-ignition, assessing damage, deciding whether to continue the\n    tasking or return to station\n\n\n:::warning\n**RNLI policy: firefighting equipment carried on RNLI SAR units is\nused solely for fighting fires aboard the SAR unit. The fire\nextinguisher must not be used to tackle fires on casualty vessels.\nCrew PPE is NOT fire resistant. Your equipment is there to aid escape,\nnot to fight a sustained fire.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.5.2, pp.79 — 80; TP-LB-28, EOP 2*\n",
  "1.6.2": "### 1.6.2 MANAGE EMERGENCY PROCEDURES\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 9.  Command the crew through stranding, collision, flooding, capsize, |\n|     and abandonment                                                   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 10. Use the ILB Decision Support Check Cards (EOPs 1 — 9) to structure |\n|     your response                                                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 11. Make the decision to abandon the vessel and manage the            |\n|     abandonment procedure                                             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 12. Decide whether to continue or stand down after an emergency       |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nAll emergency procedures are taught in full in the Safe to Go on a\nService guide (Stage 3) from the crew perspective, and the complete ILB\nDecision Support EOPs are reproduced in the Tier 1 guide. As Helm, you\nmust manage these emergencies while commanding the vessel. The key\ncommand decisions for each:\n\n  **Emergency**    **Your Key Command Decisions**\n\n  Stranding /      Stop the vessel. Account for crew and injuries. Fix\n  Grounding        position. Assess damage. Determine which way deep\n                   water lies. Decide: attempt to refloat, deploy\n                   anchor/sea anchor, or abandon? Contact Coastguard with\n                   appropriate transmission (distress or urgency\n                   depending on severity)\n\n  Collision        Prevent loss of life first. Manoeuvre to minimise\n                   effects. Check for fire, damage, flooding. Offer\n                   assistance to other vessel. Contact Coastguard.\n                   Decide: can we continue, or must we return/abandon?\n\n  Flooding         Prevent further flooding and loss of buoyancy. Direct\n                   crew to identify source and stem the flow. Deploy\n                   pumps. Monitor stability. Decide: is the flooding\n                   controllable, or must we abandon?\n\n  Capsize (A85)    Post-capsize: headcount, assist trapped crew, deploy\n                   sea anchor and swim line, activate righting system,\n                   reboard, restart engines (EOP 5), rig emergency\n                   antenna, send DSC distress and Mayday. Decide: crew\n                   welfare (delayed effects), condition of the vessel,\n                   distance/location, other asset availability — \n                   continue or stand down?\n\n  Abandonment      The decision to abandon is yours and yours alone.\n                   Brief the procedure, collect grab bag, send DSC\n                   distress and Mayday, don all PPE with buddy check,\n                   muster and headcount, enter the water one at a time,\n                   group together, activate PLBs. Abandonment is your\n                   last resort at sea\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.2a, pp.87 — 89; TP-LB-28, EOPs 1 — 9*\n\n\n:::info\n**During a pass out, you may or may not refer to the check cards but\nyou must know that there are cards and where they are stowed without\nbeing prompted. The assessor expects you to know the procedures from\nmemory and to use the cards as a confirmation tool, not as a first\nreference.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.2a, p.87*\n",
  "1.7.1": "### 1.7.1 PYROTECHNICS\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify all types of pyrotechnic held at the station and on the A85 |\n| 2.  Know the purpose, location, and correct PPE for each type         |\n| 3.  Fire each type correctly and handle a misfire safely               |\n| 4.  Understand expiry, disposal, and SOLAS regulations                |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Pyrotechnic Types\n\n| **Type** | **Colour** | **Purpose** | **Duration** | **Visibility** |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Parachute rocket flare | **Red** | Distress signal — maximum range alerting | ~40 sec at 300m height | Up to 28 NM |\n| Parachute rocket flare | **White** | Illumination — lights up a search area at night | ~40 sec at 300m height | Illuminates wide area |\n| Handheld flare | **Red** | Distress — pinpoints your position at close range | ~60 sec | 3–5 NM |\n| Handheld flare | **White** | Collision warning / illumination (NOT a distress signal) | ~60 sec | 3–5 NM |\n| Orange smoke signal | **Orange** | Daytime distress signal and wind direction indicator | ~3 min | 3 NM (day only) |\n| Buoyant smoke signal | **Orange** | Daytime distress — thrown into the water, marks position | ~3 min | 3 NM (day only) |\n\n:::warning\nPyrotechnics are **explosive devices**. They burn at extreme temperatures and can cause severe burns, start fires, and permanently damage eyes. **Full PPE including gloves and visor DOWN** for all firings. Always fire downwind and away from the vessel and all personnel.\n:::\n\n### Firing Procedures\n\n#### Red Parachute Rocket Flare (Distress)\n\n:::steps\n1. Remove the end cap to reveal the lanyard\n2. Hold the flare at **arm's length** at approximately **15° downwind** of vertical\n3. In strong wind or **low cloud**, reduce the angle to **45° downwind** to keep the flare below the cloud base — otherwise it disappears into cloud and wastes the signal\n4. Pull the lanyard **sharply downwards** with a firm, fast action\n5. The rocket fires upward — a parachute deploys at height and the flare drifts slowly down\n6. **Do not point at any aircraft, helicopter, or vessel**\n:::\n\n#### White Parachute Rocket Flare (Illumination)\n\n:::steps\n1. Firing procedure is identical to the red parachute rocket\n2. Fire **upwind** of the area you want to illuminate — the parachute will drift the flare downwind over the search area\n3. Coordinate with the Helm so the crew are looking in the right direction when it fires\n4. Multiple flares may be needed for an extended search — space them to maintain continuous illumination\n:::\n\n:::info\nThe white parachute flare is an **illumination tool**, not a distress signal. It is carried on the A85 specifically for lighting up a search area at night to locate casualties. It produces a very bright white light that casts shadows and can reveal a person in the water from a considerable distance.\n:::\n\n#### Red or White Handheld Flare\n\n:::steps\n1. Remove the end cap\n2. Hold firmly at **arm's length**, angled **downwind** and **away from the vessel** and crew\n3. Strike the igniter (twist or pull depending on model)\n4. The flare will burn with intense flame and drip hot slag — **keep clear of the drips**\n5. **Do not look directly at it** — it will dazzle your night vision for several minutes\n6. When spent, drop into the sea — **never place on deck** as residual heat can cause fire\n:::\n\n#### Orange Smoke Signal (Handheld or Buoyant)\n\n:::steps\n1. **Handheld**: Remove cap, hold over the side of the vessel, pull the igniter. Hold downwind so smoke drifts away from you\n2. **Buoyant**: Remove cap, activate, and throw into the water upwind of your position\n3. Smoke indicates **wind direction** to approaching helicopters as well as marking your position\n:::\n\n:::fact WHEN TO USE WHICH\n**Distress at long range (day or night)**: Red parachute rocket flare\n**Distress at close range (night)**: Red handheld flare\n**Distress at close range (day)**: Orange smoke signal\n**Illuminating a search area (night)**: White parachute rocket flare\n**Collision warning / attracting attention**: White handheld flare (NOT distress)\n**Wind direction for helicopter**: Orange smoke signal\n:::\n\n### Misfire Procedure\n\n:::warning\nIf a pyrotechnic fails to fire:\n**Continue to hold it pointed safely away** from yourself and all persons for **at least 30 seconds**. Do NOT look at the end or attempt to refire. Drop the misfired pyrotechnic **into the sea** well clear of the vessel. If ashore, place in a bucket of water. **Report** the misfire to the LOM.\n:::\n\n### Storage and Expiry\n\n- All pyrotechnics have an **expiry date** — typically **3 years** from manufacture (printed on the casing)\n- Expired pyrotechnics must be returned to the RNLI for **proper disposal** — they cannot be disposed of locally and must never be put in general waste\n- Store in a **cool, dry, secure location** in their original packaging — away from heat sources and direct sunlight\n- **SOLAS-approved** pyrotechnics meet international maritime safety standards\n- The A85 carries pyrotechnics in the **grab bag** stowed in the console — know exactly where they are BEFORE you need them\n\n### A85 Pyrotechnic Inventory\n\n:::checklist\n- Red parachute rocket flares × 4\n- White parachute rocket flares (illumination) × 4\n- Red handheld flares × 4\n- White handheld flares × 2\n- Orange smoke signals × 2\n- Buoyant orange smoke signals × 2\n:::\n\n### PPE for Pyrotechnic Use\n\n- **Helmet with visor DOWN** at all times\n- **Gloves** — protect hands from heat and slag\n- **Face away from wind** — fire downwind so sparks and slag blow away from you\n- **Warn all crew** before firing — shout a clear warning\n- At night, **close one eye** before firing to preserve some night vision\n",
  "1.8.1": "## Risk Assessment\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Understand the difference between formal and dynamic risk assessment |\n| 2.  Apply the Risk = Possibility × Severity matrix                    |\n| 3.  Follow the five-step risk assessment process                      |\n| 4.  Conduct dynamic risk assessments in real time during operations   |\n| 5.  Apply risk assessment to launch authority decisions               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Two Types of Risk Assessment\n\n| **Aspect** | **Formal Risk Assessment** | **Dynamic Risk Assessment** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **When** | Before an activity (planned in advance) | During an activity (continuous, in real time) |\n| **How** | Written document identifying hazards, who is at risk, controls, and remaining risk | Mental process: identify new hazard, assess risk, take immediate action |\n| **By whom** | LOM, Head Launcher, Helm, or appointed person | Everyone — especially those in command roles |\n| **Recorded** | Yes — filed and reviewed regularly | Not formally recorded (but outcomes may be noted) |\n| **Example** | Station launch and recovery risk assessment | Noticing ground softening mid-recovery and changing the recovery point |\n\n### The Risk Matrix\n\nRisk is calculated as **Possibility × Severity**. The matrix produces a score from 1 (very low) to 9 (very high):\n\n| | **1 — Minor** | **2 — Major** | **3 — Fatal** |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **3 — High possibility** | 3 MEDIUM | 6 HIGH | 9 VERY HIGH |\n| **2 — Medium possibility** | 2 LOW | 4 MEDIUM | 6 HIGH |\n| **1 — Low possibility** | 1 VERY LOW | 2 LOW | 3 MEDIUM |\n\n:::memory\nThe matrix is simple: **multiply the row by the column**. A \"medium possibility\" (2) of a \"major\" injury (2) = risk score **4 (MEDIUM)**. A \"high possibility\" (3) of a \"fatal\" outcome (3) = risk score **9 (VERY HIGH)** — do not proceed without additional controls.\n:::\n\n### The Five-Step Risk Assessment Process\n\n:::steps\n1. **Identify the hazards** — what could cause harm? Walk the area, talk to experienced people, review previous incidents\n2. **Identify who is at risk** — shore crew, boat crew, plant operator, the public, casualties?\n3. **Evaluate the risk (before controls)** — use the Possibility × Severity matrix. What is the risk score without any control measures?\n4. **Apply control measures** — eliminate the hazard if possible, or reduce the risk to acceptable levels using the hierarchy of controls (eliminate → substitute → engineering → administrative → PPE)\n5. **Assess remaining risk (after controls)** — is the remaining risk acceptable? If not, add more controls or do not proceed with the activity\n:::\n\n:::fact KEY PRINCIPLE\nRisk assessment is about making risk **visible and manageable**, not about eliminating all risk. Some risk is inherent in SAR operations. The question is always: **is the remaining risk acceptable given the benefit of the action?**\n:::\n\n### Dynamic Risk Assessment in Practice\n\nDynamic risk assessment is not a separate skill — it is the continuous mental process of:\n\n- **Detecting** new or changing hazards as a situation develops\n- **Assessing** how serious they are and how likely they are to cause harm\n- **Reacting** with proportionate action — avoid, manage, mitigate, or withdraw\n\n:::info\nRisk assessment does not stop when you authorise the launch. As a service develops, conditions change. You must continue to dynamically assess risk — monitoring weather, tide, crew fatigue — and be prepared to request the SAR unit return if the risk becomes unacceptable.\n:::\n\n### Launch Authority — Factors to Weigh\n\nAs Launch Authority, every factor you consider when applying the **Compliant–Achievable–Appropriate** framework is a risk assessment:\n\n| **Factor** | **Risk to Consider** | **Information Source** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Weather** | High winds, lightning, ice/snow, wave damage | Shipping forecast, Coastguard, own observation |\n| **Sea state** | Surf height affecting launch/recovery safety | Coastguard, Helm assessment, own observation |\n| **Tide** | Spring low tide (long beach transit, soft ground), tidal surge, restrictions at casualty location | Tide tables, local knowledge, LOP |\n| **Crew** | Physical exposure, mental exposure to trauma, competence of trainees, fatigue | Currency records, LSAR, direct knowledge |\n| **Asset** | SAR unit on restricted service, equipment defects, fuel state | Defect log, mechanic, COIR |\n| **Casualty type** | Person in water vs vessel aground vs medical evacuation — different demands and urgency | Coastguard tasking information |\n| **Time of day** | Darkness increases all risks; visibility reduced; public less visible | Own observation |\n| **Other assets** | Is a flank station, helicopter, or Coastguard team better placed? | Coastguard, local knowledge |\n\n:::warning\nThe question is always: **does the benefit of launching outweigh the risk to the crew?** If the answer is not clearly yes, do not launch — or request additional assets.\n:::\n\n### COMMAND SKILLS — Decision Making Under Pressure\n\nEffective risk assessment under pressure relies on:\n- **Situational awareness** — knowing what is happening around you\n- **Anticipation** — thinking ahead: what could change? What is the worst case?\n- **Communication** — sharing your assessment with the team and inviting challenge\n- **Assertiveness** — any crew member can and should speak up if they identify a hazard\n- **Decision review** — after the event, review decisions made. What worked? What would you change?\n",
  "1.10.1": "### 1.10.1 WORKING AT HEIGHT\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify the specific working at height hazards at Littlestone lifeboat station                |\n| 2.  Know the legal definition and when regulations apply              |\n| 3.  Use the correct precautions and equipment                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### What Counts as Working at Height?\n\n:::fact LEGAL DEFINITION\nWorking at height means working in **any place where a person could fall a distance liable to cause personal injury**. This includes working on ladders, platforms, roofs, the deck of a vessel on a cradle, or near open edges.\n:::\n\n### Common Working at Height Activities at a Station\n\n- **Raising/lowering the mast** on the A85 during launch preparation\n- **Working on the DoDo carriage** — accessing the boat while elevated\n- **Roof access** for building maintenance\n- **Ladder use** for stores, equipment checks, aerial maintenance\n- **Working on the slipway** when the boat is elevated on the cradle\n\n### Precautions\n\n:::steps\n1. **Avoid** working at height wherever possible — can the task be done from ground level?\n2. If not avoidable, use **collective protection** first — platforms with guardrails, scaffolding, edge protection\n3. If collective protection is not practical, use **personal protection** — harnesses, lanyards, safety lines\n4. As a last resort, use **ladders** — but only for short-duration, low-risk tasks\n:::\n\n### Ladder Safety\n\n- The ladder must be **stable, secured, and footed** by another person while in use\n- Maintain **three points of contact** at all times\n- Do not overreach — **your belt buckle should remain within the stiles**\n- Do not carry heavy or bulky items up a ladder — use a line to haul them up\n- Ensure the ladder extends at least **1 metre above the landing point**\n- The angle should be **1 unit out for every 4 units up** (75° angle)\n\n:::warning\n**Falls from height are one of the leading causes of workplace fatalities in the UK.** Even a fall from a relatively low height can cause life-changing injuries. Never rush a task involving height — take the time to set up properly.\n:::\n",
  "3.1.3": "### 3.1.3 MANAGE LAUNCH AND RECOVERY (AFLOAT)\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 13. Command the launch from aboard the SAR unit                       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 14. Select the crew and verify competence before launch               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 15. Manage the recovery approach and communicate with the Head        |\n|     Launcher                                                          |\n|                                                                       |\n| 16. Manage post-recovery procedures and report ready for service      |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nLaunch and recovery from the Helm's perspective at Littlestone: you are\naboard the A85 on the DoDo carriage. Your responsibilities during launch\ninclude: confirming with the Launch Authority that you are ready,\nbriefing the boat crew on the tasking (SMEAC), ensuring the Navigator\nhas the CSP or destination entered, managing the transition from\ncarriage to water (at Littlestone: the CH31 radio check with the tractor\nconfirms you are ready, then command passes from the Head Launcher to\nyou at the water's edge), and establishing communications with the\nCoastguard on Ch16 immediately after launch.\n\nDuring recovery, you command the approach. Liaise with the Head Launcher\non VHF Ch31 to confirm the recovery method (stern, net, or beach at\nLittlestone), the state of the beach and surf, and any hazards. You must\njudge the approach speed, timing relative to waves, and the engine trim\nfor the specific recovery method. After recovery: SPEP debrief, ensure\nthe boat is washed down, engines flushed, refuelled, equipment restowed,\ndefects reported, and the station reports ready for service to the LA\nand Coastguard.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 3.1.3, pp.107 — 111; TP-LB-23, Activity 3, pp.32 — 36; Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0*\n",
  "3.2.1": "## Launch Procedures (Shore Crew)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Carry out pre-launch checks correctly                             |\n| 2.  Follow instruction from the Head Launcher during launch           |\n| 3.  Understand the hazards of launch operations                       |\n| 4.  Know what to do if equipment fails                                |\n| 5.  Secure equipment after launch                                     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Station-Specific: Littlestone\n\n:::info\nLittlestone launches from a **shingle beach** using a DoDo carriage towed by a **Same Dorado tractor**. The beach gradient and shingle surface mean ground conditions vary significantly with tide and weather. Soft ground and deep shingle are common hazards — the Head Launcher must assess ground conditions before every launch and recovery.\n:::\n\n### Littlestone DoDo Carriage Launch — St:::steps\n1. LA appoints approved **Head Launcher** and **LVD** (Licensed Vehicle Driver)\n2. **Prepare boat and launch vehicle** — disconnect electric chargers, close all hatches and pouches, hand red tags to Head Launcher\n3. LVD carries out **vehicle checks**\n4. Open boathouse door and place **barriers either side** outside\n5. **Clear boathouse of ALL personnel** before the vehicle moves\n6. Head Launcher uses **hand signals** to signal tractor driver it is clear to move out\n7. Helm gives the **SMEAC briefing** to boat crew\n8. Head Launcher instructs shore crew to **position marshals** in designated areas\n9. **Stop rig** outside boathouse to allow crew to put A-frame and aerials in position\n10. Head Launcher asks for **DoDo trailer to be made ready** — water pipes checked/removed from engine fishtails, tanks opened as required\n11. **Radio check** — Head Launcher to tractor on VHF Ch31, then control passed to Helm for launch\n12. Helm **directs LVD** to ramp and down to launch site as per SOP\n13. All crew aware of **public, dogs, and waterborne craft** — at low water, a marshal is placed on the beach\n14. After launch, shore crew **escort rig back to boathouse** in same positions\n:::irection\n:::\n\n:::warning\nAll SAR units, launch vehicles, and plant must be **STATIONARY** and all operating activities **HALTED** before any personnel may embark or disembark. Crew must not attempt to disembark during coupling/uncoupling unless a halt has been called and the Head Launcher has deemed it safe.\n:::\n\n### Your Role During Launch\n\nAs shore crew, you work under the direction of the Head Launcher. Your tasks may include passing up straps, fitting bow strops, handling lines, or marshalling a safe area. You must understand the full procedure even though you may only perform part of it on any given launch.\n\n:::info\nThe Atlantic 85 has a normal crew of **3** (minimum 3, maximum 4). When extra crew are on board for exercises, the maximum remains 4. The person in command, in consultation with the launch authority, has the final say on how many persons are aboard.\n:::\n\n### Communications During Launch\n\nThree methods are used. Before any operation, **all personnel must know which method(s) will be used**:\n\n| **Method** | **How It Works** | **Key Points** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Hand signals** | Standardised arm/hand movements | Must be precise, simple, distinctive. Both arms used symmetrically |\n| **VHF radio** | Ch31 (RNLI private channel) | Comms established between HL, SAR unit and vehicle BEFORE moving |\n| **Audible signals** | Horns, whistles, voice commands | Wind and machinery may reduce effectiveness — whistle may be better |\n\n### Key Hand Signals\n\n| **Signal** | **Meaning** |\n|---|---|\n| Both arms extended horizontally, palms forward | **CLEAR TO START** |\n| Both arms clasped at chest height | **END OF OPERATION** |\n| Right arm points up, palm forward | **STOP** |\n| Both arms point up, palms forward | **EMERGENCY STOP** |\n| Both arms bent, palms up, forearms beckon inward | **MOVE FORWARDS** |\n| Both arms bent, palms down, forearms push outward | **MOVE BACKWARDS** |\n| Right arm points down, palm in, makes circle | **WINCH OUT / LOWER** |\n| Right arm points up, palm forward, makes circle | **WINCH IN / RAISE** |\n\n:::warning\nDuring manoeuvring, **ANY crew member** can call an emergency stop by placing both hands in the air or blowing a whistle. Operations do not resume until the Head Launcher has investigated and deemed it safe.\n:::\n\n### Launch Hazards\n\n- **Moving equipment** — vehicles, winches, tilting cradles\n- **Lines under load** — risk of rope parting and whipping\n- **Uneven ground** during transit\n- **Overhead hazards** when working below the SAR unit\n- **Slippery footing** and handholds\n- **Severe weather** conditions\n- **Members of the public** entering the exclusion zone\n\n### Exclusion Zones\n\nExclusion zones reduce risk during launch and recovery. The Head Launcher must rigorously enforce them:\n\n| **Zone** | **Extent** | **Hazard** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Boathouse zone | Little clearance either side of rig | Entrapment/crush hazard when moving |\n| Transit zone | Full length and breadth of the rig while moving | Run-over/crush risk |\n| Coupling/uncoupling zone | Hitch to past end of SAR unit/carriage | Only enter when STATIC and HL deems safe |\n| Winching zone | Two circles, radius 1.5× tow length | Changes as tow is paid out/shortened |\n\n### Equipment Failure During Launch\n\n:::steps\n1. Signal an **emergency stop** where appropriate\n2. Notify the **person in command of the SAR unit or Head Launcher** immediately\n3. If failure cannot be immediately repaired, recover SAR unit to a safe area\n4. If no launch is possible, inform the **coordinating authority** and activate a co-located or flank station asset\n5. All equipment must be **securely stowed** and the SAR unit made safe\n:::\n\n### Dealing with the Public\n\nLaunch and recovery operations will invariably attract onlookers. As shore crew (particularly as marshals), you are the front line for public interaction:\n\n- Be **polite and civil** at all times, but do not allow them to distract you from the operation\n- Be **firm, clear and positive** when directing members of the public — aggressive or unprofessional behaviour damages the RNLI's reputation and charitable donations\n- Be **firm, clear and positive** when directing traffic to stop; be aware of approaching traffic at all times and acknowledge drivers afterwards\n- If you see something that poses a danger to a member of the public, **call an emergency stop** and inform the person in charge\n- Direct any complaints to the Head Launcher, DLA, or LOM **after the operation is complete**\n",
  "3.2.2": "## Recovery Procedures (Shore Crew)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Recover the A85 onto the DoDo carriage safely                     |\n| 2.  Work under the Head Launcher's direction during recovery          |\n| 3.  Secure all equipment after recovery                               |\n| 4.  Understand the hazards specific to recovery operations            |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Station-Specific: Littlestone\n\n:::info\nAt Littlestone, recovery requires particular care due to the **shingle beach gradient**. The DoDo carriage must be positioned precisely — too deep and the tractor may become bogged; too shallow and the boat cannot reach the cradle. The Head Launcher should assess **ground firmness** at the intended recovery point before committing the tractor.\n:::\n\n### Littlestone DoDo Carriage Recovery — Step by Step\n\n:::steps\n1. **Washdown on the ramp** if necessary before proceeding\n2. Stop in designated area to **make ready for recovery**\n3. **Spring ropes replaced** on DoDo carriage; water tanks switched off and refilled; water pipes stored\n4. Carriage prepared as instructed by Helm — **gates open/closed or net rigged**\n5. **Radio check** — Head Launcher to tractor on VHF Ch31\n6. Head Launcher and driver **observe safest route** to shoreline\n7. Tractor driver **contacts Helm** for recovery information, performed as per SOP\n8. After recovery, LVD brings rig back to ramp; **shore crew marshal** under Head Launcher direction\n9. **Washdown** at top of ramp or outside boathouse\n10. Crew assigned tasks — **washdown, refuelling, make ready for service**, post-recovery checks per PM job cards\n11. **Rig put away** in boathouse under Head Launcher instruction\n12. **Full debrief** in boathouse with all crew involved\n:::\n\n:::warning\nRecovery is often **more hazardous than launch** because the crew are fatigued, weather may have deteriorated, and the boat must be manoeuvred precisely onto a moving carriage in surf. Extra vigilance is required from all personnel.\n:::\n\n### Post-Recovery Tasks\n\n:::checklist\n- Engines flushed with fresh water (if sea water used)\n- Fuel tanks topped up\n- All equipment cleaned, checked, and restowed\n- Any defects or damage reported to the LOM\n- Pyrotechnics, first aid kit, and grab bag checked\n- Lifejackets hung to dry (NOT left in the boat)\n- Drysuits rinsed and hung in drying room\n- Station log completed\n:::\n\n- — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — — +\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Prepare recovery equipment correctly                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Assist with all three recovery methods: stern, net, and beach     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Conduct post-recovery checks and make the SAR unit ready for      |\n|     service                                                           |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Factors Affecting Launch and Recovery**\n\nLaunch and recovery may be influenced by many factors that dictate how,\nwhere, and sometimes whether a launch is possible:\n\n-   Tide — high water may obscure submerged hazards and present\n    head-clearance problems; low water may reveal hazards and require\n    alternative launch vehicles or longer beach transits\n\n-   Weather — severe weather can make launch sites untenable; an\n    alternative site should be pre-planned\n\n-   Sea state — certain conditions may make launch/recovery difficult\n    or dangerous; it may be preferable to wait for a change of tide or\n    wind, or choose an alternative site\n\n-   Launch site conditions — beach profile, ground conditions, soft\n    sand, obstacles\n\n-   Time of day — darkness requires scene lighting, additional\n    caution, and (for D Class) the LA should be at the launch site\n    before authorising\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 3, pp.138 — 139*\n\n**Three Recovery Methods**\n\nThe decision on recovery method rests with the Helm, in discussion with\nthe Head Launcher and plant operator. You must be familiar with all\nthree:\n\n  **Method**       **When Used**           **Shore Crew Role**\n\n  Stern recovery   Standard method when    Prepare carriage at water's\n                   conditions allow        edge; boat reverses in and is\n                                           secured with fore and aft\n                                           springs\n\n  Net recovery     When conditions prevent Rig the recovery net to the\n                   safe stern recovery     carriage; shackle top/bottom\n                                           ropes; ensure net forms a good\n                                           cone shape; boat drives in\n                                           under power\n\n  Beach recovery   Emergency procedure     Plant operator manoeuvres rig\n                   when stern/net not      to water's edge carriage-first;\n                   possible                pay out winch rope; boat crew\n                                           attach winch rope; boat is\n                                           winched onto carriage\n*Source: TP-SC-14 DoDo Carriage Manual, pp.30 — 45; A85 Launch & Recovery SOP V7.0, p.3*\n\n**Stern Recovery Limitations**\n\nIf there is any doubt as to the safety of a stern recovery, the Helm\nmust opt for a net recovery or utilise a safe haven. Factors to\nconsider:\n\n-   Height of any surf\n\n-   Duration between sets\n\n-   Beach profile at recovery site\n\n-   Emergency plan in place\n\n*Source: A85 Launch & Recovery SOP V7.0, p.3*\n\n**Post-Recovery**\n\nAfter recovery, you will be assigned tasks: washdown, refuelling,\nmake-ready-for-service, and post-recovery checks as per Planned\nMaintenance job cards. The SAR unit must be made operationally ready\nusing post-recovery checklists. A full debrief (SPEP) is conducted with\nall crew involved.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.53; Littlestone LOP V1.0, p.3*\n",
  "3.2.3": "### 3.2.3 MANAGE LAUNCH AND RECOVERY\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 15. Plan and command a full launch from briefing to post-launch       |\n|     securing                                                          |\n|                                                                       |\n| 16. Plan and command a full recovery including deciding the method    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Manage crew positioning, exclusion zones, and communications      |\n|     throughout                                                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Respond to emergencies: equipment failure, vehicle bog down,      |\n|     fire, MOB                                                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Manage post-recovery procedures and operational readiness         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Planning a Launch**\n\nBefore any launch, you must assess the environmental conditions and plan\naccordingly. Factors include:\n\n  **Factor**       **What to Consider**\n\n  Tide             Current state and rate of change; will the tide cover\n                   the launch point during the operation? High water may\n                   obscure submerged hazards; low water may require\n                   longer beach transits\n\n  Weather          Wind strength and direction; rain reducing visibility;\n                   severe weather may make the site untenable\n\n  Sea state        Surf height and period; may affect recovery method\n                   choice (stern vs net)\n\n  Ground           Soft sand, mud, seaweed; assess in situ before\n  conditions       committing the vehicle\n\n  Time of day      Darkness requires scene lighting; higher public\n                   numbers in summer daylight hours\n\n  Crew             Do you have enough competent crew for all roles\n  availability     including marshals?\n\n  Public presence  Crowded beaches require more marshals and potentially\n                   different routes\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.50; TP-LB-01, Activity 3, pp.138 — 139*\n\n**Conducting the Launch at Littlestone**\n\nYou manage the following sequence (from the Littlestone B-Class Launch\nand Recovery LOP):\n\n-   LA appoints you as Head Launcher and appoints the LVD\n\n-   Ensure boat and vehicle are prepared: chargers disconnected, hatches\n    closed, red tags handed to you\n\n-   LVD carries out vehicle checks; you open boathouse door and place\n    barriers\n\n-   Clear boathouse of ALL personnel before the vehicle moves\n\n-   Use hand signals to signal the tractor driver it is clear to move\n    out\n\n-   Helm gives the SMEAC briefing; you decide if any boat crew are\n    needed on the ground for marshalling\n\n-   Instruct shore crew to position marshals in designated areas\n\n-   Stop rig for A-frame and aerial to be raised; DoDo trailer made\n    ready (water pipes, tank valves)\n\n-   Radio check with tractor on CH31; then pass control to Helm for the\n    launch itself\n\n-   After launch, escort rig back to boathouse in same marshal positions\n\n*Source: Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0, pp.2 — 3*\n\n**Managing Recovery**\n\nThe decision on recovery method rests with the Helm, but you must\ndiscuss it with them and the LVD. At Littlestone, the recovery sequence\nis:\n\n-   Washdown on ramp if necessary; stop in designated area to make ready\n\n-   Spring ropes replaced on DoDo carriage; water tanks off and\n    refilled; pipes stored\n\n-   Carriage prepared as Helm instructs: gates open/closed or net rigged\n\n-   Radio check with tractor on CH31; observe safest route to shoreline\n\n-   LVD contacts Helm for recovery method; recovery performed as per SOP\n\n-   After recovery, manage: washdown, crew disembarkation, task\n    assignment (refuelling, PM job cards), rig stowed in boathouse\n\n-   Full SPEP debrief in boathouse with all crew\n\n*Source: Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0, p.3; A85 Launch & Recovery SOP V7.0, p.3*\n\n**Emergency Procedures You Must Manage**\n\n  **Emergency**    **Your Actions**\n\n  Equipment        Signal emergency stop. Assess: can it be repaired\n  failure          immediately? If yes, repair and continue. If no, use\n                   alternative method or activate flank station. Notify\n                   Coastguard if launch prevented entirely\n\n  Vehicle bog down Inform station, request assistance. Identify approved\n                   bogging-down procedure. Use towing points as per\n                   equipment manual. If recovery not possible, prepare\n                   for abandonment. At Littlestone, the DoDo Release and\n                   Winch EOP applies for steep climbs and soft ground\n\n  Fire (SAR unit,  Raise alarm. If safe, fight the fire. If not,\n  vehicle, or      evacuate. For vehicle fires: make vehicle safe, alert\n  equipment)       boathouse, seek medical help if needed. For SAR unit\n                   fires: follow A85 fire procedures\n\n  Person in water  Throw a throw bag immediately. Do not enter the water\n  (MOB ashore)     unless trained and equipped. Raise the alarm. Discuss\n                   actions for the person in the water and for others\n\n  Halting          Anyone can call an emergency stop (both hands in the\n  operations       air or blow a whistle). Operations do not restart\n                   until you have investigated the reason and deemed it\n                   safe to continue\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.50; TP-LB-01, p.133; 85-EOP-MB4H Bendy + A85 DoDo Release + Winch V3.0; Littlestone LOP V1.0, p.3*\n",
  "3.3.1": "### 3.3.1 PLANT OPERATOR (FAMILIARITY)\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 20. Understand the safe working practices for the launch vehicle and  |\n|     winch                                                             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 21. Know the hazards associated with engine, winch, and electrical    |\n|     systems                                                           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 22. Understand how emotional state and attitude affect operating      |\n|     ability                                                           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 23. Know the factors to consider when the vehicle enters water or     |\n|     when abandoning                                                   |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nAs Head Launcher, you are not required to be passed out as a plant\noperator, but you must understand the vehicle's capabilities,\nlimitations, and hazards in order to direct its use safely.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.50*\n\n**Safe Working Practices by System**\n\n  **System**   **Hazards**                 **Safe Practices**\n\n  Engine       Noise, heat (hot surfaces:  Use correct PPE; ensure\n               radiator, exhaust), fumes   adequate ventilation before\n               (danger from starting in    starting in enclosed spaces\n               boathouse)                  \n\n  Winch        Rope handling (keep hands   Wear gloves; enforce the\n               away from drum), lines      restricted zone (radius 1.5x\n               under load (parting and     tow length); never stand in the\n               whipping), crush injury     bight of a line\n\n  Electrical   Shock hazard from mains and Turn OFF equipment switches\n               low voltage                 before removing plugs; refit\n                                           cable/socket covers\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.3.1a, pp.121 — 122*\n\n**Emotional State and Driving**\n\nThe Training Standards specifically identify that emotional state\naffects operating ability. As Head Launcher, you need to recognise these\neffects in your LVD:\n\n-   Responding to pager: loss of concentration, clouded judgement,\n    temptation to speed\n\n-   Tiredness: inability to spot hazards, slower reaction times\n\n-   Anger: lack of courteous driving, dangerous driving\n\nThe LVD represents the face of the RNLI. They must operate in a calm and\nconsiderate manner, comply with all road traffic regulations, and be\naware of pedestrians and other road users.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.3.1a, p.122*\n\n**Entering Water and Abandonment**\n\nBefore the vehicle enters the water, the following must be considered:\nthe vehicle must be marinised, correct operator PPE worn, ground\nconditions assessed, tidal conditions checked, sea state acceptable,\nvehicle protection hatches closed, and the depth must not exceed the\nvehicle's maximum wading depth.\n\nA vehicle may need to be abandoned after an accident, bog down, drive\ntrain failure, or power unit failure. Before abandonment: inform station\nand Coastguard, remove or secure loose equipment, secure vehicle\ndoors/hatches, note the position, and attach a position marker if\nnecessary.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.3.1b, pp.124 — 125*\n\n\n:::warning\n**At Littlestone, the DoDo Release and Winch EOP (85-EOP V3.0) must be\nfollowed when: 1) facing a steep climb that may end in a bog-down, 2)\non known areas of soft ground, 3) experiencing loss of traction, or 4)\nanticipating a bog-down. Mandatory PPE for this procedure: Head\nLauncher wears safety boots/wellies and orange hi-vis tabard; shore\ncrew/marshals wear safety boots/wellies and yellow hi-vis tabard with\nhelmets and eye protection/visors down if within 10 metres of the\nrig.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: 85-EOP-MB4H Bendy + A85 DoDo Release + Winch V3.0, p.2*\n",
  "3.4.1": "## Passage Planning and Pilotage\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Plan a passage including tidal calculations and hazard identification |\n| 2.  Brief the crew using SMEAC                                        |\n| 3.  Conduct pilotage using transits, leading lines, and clearing bearings |\n| 4.  Monitor position continuously using multiple methods               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Pre-Departure Checklist\n\n:::checklist\n- Weather forecast obtained and assessed (inshore waters, shipping)\n- Tidal information calculated (times, heights, stream direction and rate)\n- Route plotted on chart with courses, distances, and ETAs\n- Hazards identified and marked\n- Waypoints entered into SIMS\n- SMEAC briefing conducted with all crew\n- Fuel state confirmed as sufficient (plus reserve)\n- VHF comms established with Coastguard/station\n- All safety equipment checked and accessible\n:::\n\n:::acronym SMEAC (Pre-Departure Briefing)\nS — **Situation** — Weather, tidal conditions, any navigational warnings\nM — **Mission** — Where we are going and why\nE — **Execution** — Route, speed, crew positions, waypoints\nA — **Administration** — Fuel, equipment, ETA, comms plan\nC — **Command** — Who is in charge, what to do if things change, \"what have I missed?\"\n:::\n\n---\n\n### 3.4.1 AUTHORISING LAUNCHES\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Manage the three states of operational readiness and know who to  |\n|     notify on change                                                  |\n|                                                                       |\n| 2.  Receive a tasking request from the Coastguard and gather the      |\n|     right information                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 3.  Apply the Compliant — Achievable — Appropriate framework to reach a |\n|     launch decision                                                   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 4.  Know when to authorise, when to decline, and when to suggest a    |\n|     flank station                                                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Understand self-launching, Coastguard bypass, and non-operational |\n|     launch authorisation                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 6.  Use the paging system correctly and brief the SAR Unit Commander  |\n|     directly                                                          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Operational Readiness**\n\nBefore you can authorise any launch, you need to know the current state\nof your station. There are three states of operational readiness:\n\n  **State**     **What It Means**        **Implications for You**\n\n  Ready for     SAR unit, equipment, and You can authorise a launch as\n  service       crew are available and   normal\n                fully operational        \n\n  Restricted    Personnel or material    You CAN still authorise a\n  service       defects limit capability launch, but you must consider\n                (e.g. only one qualified the effects of the defect(s) on\n                helm available, or a     the operation. Is the remaining\n                piece of equipment is    capability sufficient for this\n                defective)               specific tasking?\n\n  Off service   SAR unit is not          You cannot authorise a launch.\n                available for launch     The Coastguard and flank\n                                         stations must be informed\n\nWhen the state of readiness changes, you must notify: the Central\nOperations Information Room (COIR), station management, the Coastguard,\nand flank stations. Defects must be reported promptly so that station\nmechanics and coastal/regional support staff can arrange repairs. Follow\nup to ensure speedy repair and regain readiness.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.4.1a, p.126*\n\n**Receiving a Tasking Request**\n\nWhen the pager alert 'Tasking Request' is received, you call the\nCoordinating Authority (CA) on the dedicated station telephone number.\nYou will normally speak to your local Maritime Rescue Co-ordination\nCentre (MRCC), but it could be any MRCC in the country. It is useful to\nask which MRCC you are speaking to, so you can gauge their likely level\nof local knowledge.\n\nGather the essential information using three questions:\n\n  **Question**   **What You're Establishing**\n\n  WHAT?          Nature of the tasking / mission as passed by the CA\n\n  WHERE?         Location of the tasking / casualty\n\n  WHO?           Any other assets involved or already tasked\n\nTry to strike a balance between speed and quality of information. You\nmay need to probe for extra detail to inform your decision. The CA will\ndeliver the request in a standard format aligned with the SMEAC briefing\nstructure. If you do not have enough information, ask for it.\n\n*Source: Pager Response SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n**The Launch Decision**\n\nThis is the most important thing you do. Once you are satisfied with the\ninformation, you must make the launch decision. Every decision must pass\nthree tests:\n\n  **Page**             **When to Use It**\n\n  Crew Assemble        When an immediate launch is NOT required. Helps\n                       de-steam the response and reduce red mist. Gives\n                       time for a full assessment and briefing\n\n  Launch ILB           When an immediate ILB launch is required\n\n  Launch ALB           When an immediate ALB launch is required\n\n  Launch Both Boats    When both assets are needed immediately\n\n  Cancel               When the tasking is cancelled or declined\n\n  Immediate Readiness  At immediate readiness to launch, with crew on\n  ILB / ALB            board or in the immediate vicinity\n\n  Standby ILB / ALB    Crew warned of probable SAR mission, brought to an\n                       agreed notice for launch\n\n*Source: Pager Response SOP V5.0, p.3*\n\n**Briefing the SAR Unit Commander**\n\n\n:::warning\n**You must talk DIRECTLY to the SAR Unit Commander to pass tasking\ndetails. This must not be passed through a third party, as there is\nsignificant scope for the dilution of important information.**\n:::\n\n\nDecide whether the briefing needs to be face-to-face or can be conducted\nby telephone. Factors: urgency (life at immediate risk) and complexity\n(known risks). If a telephone briefing is sufficient, allow a few\nminutes after the second page before calling the station. Cover the\nSituation and Mission first; then determine the Execution,\nAdministration, and Command elements together with the Helm before the\nrest of the crew and shore crew are briefed. Then proceed to the\nstation.\n\n*Source: Pager Response SOP V5.0, p.3; Communicate Launch Decision SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n\n:::info\n**It is not acceptable for any RNLI asset to proceed to sea without\nthe crew having been briefed on the best available information. It is\nrare that spending a few moments briefing a tasking will hinder the\noperation. A well-briefed team will function more efficiently and will\nbe safer.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: Communicate Launch Decision SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n**Coastguard Priority System**\n\n  **Phase**     **Definition**\n\n  Distress      Reasonable certainty that a vessel, aircraft, or person\n                is threatened by grave and imminent danger and requires\n                immediate assistance\n\n  Alert         Apprehension exists as to the safety of a vessel,\n                aircraft, or person\n\n  Uncertainty   Doubt exists as to the safety of a vessel, aircraft, or\n                person\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.4.1b, p.127*\n\n**Self-Launching**\n\nIn certain circumstances, the crew may launch without prior LA\nauthorisation. This is called self-launching. It can occur in three\nways:\n\n-   Coastguard to crew — a direct launch request when delay would\n    result in death\n\n-   Crew to Coastguard — when already launched (e.g. on exercise) or\n    when an incident is observed directly or reported through a third\n    party\n\n-   Launch Authority to crew — when an incident is observed directly\n    or reported through a third party\n\nIn all cases, the LA and SAR coordinating authority must be informed and\napprove at the earliest possible time, and the self-launch guidelines\nmust be followed.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.4.1b, p.128*\n\n**Coastguard Bypass**\n\nIn extreme cases where unnecessary delay may cause loss of life, the CA\nmay bypass the Tasking Request page and proceed directly to a Launch\npage. In this case, the CA will be making best endeavours to contact\nyou, and you should contact them immediately as the crew will already be\nmaking their way to the station.\n\n*Source: Pager Response SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n**Non-Operational Launches**\n\nYou can also authorise launches for non-operational purposes:\n\n-   Training exercises (most common)\n\n-   Passage (moving the boat between locations)\n\n-   Machinery trials\n\n-   Maintenance\n\n-   Fundraising events\n\n-   Public relations events\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.4.1b, p.128*\n\n**Reporting**\n\nAfter every launch, you must ensure accurate records are maintained:\n\n-   Exercise returns — entered into the RNLI database system (LSAR)\n\n-   Return of Service — entered after every operational launch\n\n-   Crew attendance reports — recorded for currency tracking\n\n-   Exercise planning forms — must be signed off to authorise and\n    document exercise launches, ensure safe and appropriate exercises,\n    and ensure the right crew attend regularly\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.4.1d, p.130*\n\n# Domain 4: Seamanship & Boat Handling\n",
  "4.1.2": "## Watchkeeping (IRPCS)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Assess if a risk of collision exists using CBDR                   |\n| 2.  Apply the key IRPCS rules relevant to the A85                     |\n| 3.  Identify vessels by their lights and day shapes                   |\n| 4.  Know the sound signals for manoeuvring and restricted visibility  |\n| 5.  Understand the responsibilities as a lookout                      |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Constant Bearing, Decreasing Range (CBDR)\n\n:::fact COLLISION RISK TEST\nIf a vessel's **compass bearing does not change** but the **range is decreasing**, you are on a collision course. Take early, substantial, and obvious avoiding action.\n:::\n\n\n\n### Key IRPCS Rules for the A85\n\n| **Rule** | **Summary** | **Key Point** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Rule 5 — Lookout** | Every vessel must maintain a proper lookout at all times using sight, hearing, and all available means | Lookout is EVERY crew member's responsibility, not just the Helm's |\n| **Rule 6 — Safe speed** | Travel at a speed that allows you to take effective avoiding action | Consider visibility, traffic density, sea state, draught, and stopping distance |\n| **Rule 7 — Risk of collision** | Use all available means to determine if risk exists. If in doubt, assume it does | CBDR is the primary method — supplement with radar and AIS |\n| **Rule 8 — Avoiding action** | Action must be early, substantial, and obvious to the other vessel | Small course changes are dangerous — the other vessel may not see them |\n| **Rule 12 — Sailing vessels** | Sailing vessels have right of way over power-driven vessels (with exceptions) | A85 must give way to sail UNLESS the sailing vessel is overtaking |\n| **Rule 13 — Overtaking** | The overtaking vessel must keep clear regardless of type | Any vessel approaching from more than 22.5° abaft the beam is overtaking |\n| **Rule 14 — Head-on** | Both vessels alter course to STARBOARD and pass port-to-port | Applies when vessels are nearly end-on |\n| **Rule 15 — Crossing** | The vessel with the other on her STARBOARD side must give way | The give-way vessel should avoid crossing ahead |\n| **Rule 18 — Responsibilities** | The hierarchy of right-of-way from most to least privileged | See below |\n\n### Right of Way Hierarchy\n\n:::info\nVessels higher on this list have priority over those below:\n1. **Not under command** (broken down — two black balls or two red lights vertical)\n2. **Restricted in ability to manoeuvre** (e.g. dredging, cable laying — ball-diamond-ball)\n3. **Constrained by draught** (can only navigate in deep water — black cylinder)\n4. **Fishing** (actively trawling — two cones point-to-point)\n5. **Sailing**\n6. **Power-driven** (this is the A85 in most situations)\n:::\n\n### Navigation Lights\n\n:::diagram Port and starboard lights — the A85 displays these at night\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 350 150\" style=\"max-width:330px\">\n<rect x=\"125\" y=\"30\" width=\"100\" height=\"50\" fill=\"#002B5C\" rx=\"8\"/>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">A85</text>\n<circle cx=\"125\" cy=\"55\" r=\"12\" fill=\"#DC2626\" stroke=\"#991B1B\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"125\" y=\"59\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">P</text>\n<text x=\"95\" y=\"55\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">RED</text>\n<circle cx=\"225\" cy=\"55\" r=\"12\" fill=\"#059669\" stroke=\"#047857\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"225\" y=\"59\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">S</text>\n<text x=\"255\" y=\"55\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">GRN</text>\n<circle cx=\"175\" cy=\"15\" r=\"10\" fill=\"white\" stroke=\"#6B7280\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"19\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#374151\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">W</text>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"3\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Masthead (white)</text>\n<circle cx=\"175\" cy=\"100\" r=\"10\" fill=\"white\" stroke=\"#6B7280\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"104\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#374151\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">W</text>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"125\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Stern (white)</text>\n<polygon points=\"175,30 160,10 190,10\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#6B7280\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>\n<text x=\"175\" y=\"145\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">View from above</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::memory\n**\"Is there any RED PORT LEFT in the bottle?\"**\nRed = Port = Left side (facing forward)\nGreen = Starboard = Right side (facing forward)\n:::\n\n### Sound Signals (Manoeuvring)\n\n| **Signal** | **Meaning** |\n|---|---|\n| One short blast (•) | I am altering my course to **starboard** |\n| Two short blasts (• •) | I am altering my course to **port** |\n| Three short blasts (• • •) | My engines are going **astern** |\n| Five or more short blasts (• • • • •) | **Warning** — I doubt you are taking sufficient avoiding action |\n\n### The Lookout's Role\n\nAs a crew member on the A85, you are always acting as lookout. This means:\n- **Continuous 360° scanning** — not just ahead. Threats can come from any direction\n- Report contacts to the Helm using the **clock face system**: \"Contact, 2 o'clock, 200 metres, crossing left to right\"\n- Use **binoculars** for identification but do not become fixated — regular naked-eye scanning first\n- At night, allow your eyes to **adapt to darkness** (20–30 minutes for full adaptation)\n- **Listen** — engine noise, fog signals, breaking waves all provide critical information\n",
  "4.1.3": "### 4.1.3 IRPCS (COMMAND LEVEL)\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Know the full range of IRPCS rules at command level               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 6.  Apply the steering and sailing rules instinctively                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 7.  Identify all navigation lights, shapes, and sound signals         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 8.  Understand and apply the IALA buoyage system thoroughly           |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nAt Tier 2, you learned six key IRPCS rules. At Navigator level, you must\nknow the full range to command standard. The Pass Out Handbook lists 24\nrules that must be demonstrated, either by passing an approved\nexamination or by direct assessment. You must have a thorough and\ninstinctive understanding — not just recall, but the ability to apply\nthe rules immediately in any situation.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.28*\n\n**Steering and Sailing Rules**\n\n  **Rule**   **Title**          **What It Requires**\n\n  Rule 1     Application        The IRPCS applies to all vessels upon the\n                                high seas and waters connected therewith\n                                navigable by seagoing vessels. Nothing\n                                exempts any vessel from compliance\n\n  Rule 2     Responsibility     Nothing in the rules exonerates any vessel\n                                from the consequences of neglect, or of the\n                                neglect of any precaution required by the\n                                ordinary practice of seamen\n\n  Rule 5     Lookout            Every vessel shall at all times maintain a\n                                proper lookout by sight and hearing as well\n                                as by all available means appropriate in the\n                                prevailing circumstances\n\n  Rule 6     Safe speed         Every vessel shall at all times proceed at a\n                                safe speed so that proper and effective\n                                action can be taken to avoid collision\n\n  Rule 7     Risk of collision  If there is any doubt, risk of collision\n                                shall be deemed to exist. Assumptions shall\n                                not be made on the basis of scanty\n                                information, especially scanty radar\n                                information\n\n  Rule 8     Action to avoid    Action shall be positive, made in ample\n             collision          time, with due regard to good seamanship.\n                                Alteration of course and/or speed shall be\n                                large enough to be readily apparent. A\n                                succession of small alterations shall be\n                                avoided\n\n  Rule 9     Narrow channels    A vessel shall keep as near to the outer\n                                limit of the channel on her starboard side\n                                as is safe and practicable. A vessel less\n                                than 20m shall not impede vessels that can\n                                only navigate within the channel\n\n  Rule 10    Traffic separation Do not enter a TSS unless crossing or in\n             schemes            certain defined circumstances. If crossing,\n                                cross on a heading at right angles to the\n                                direction of traffic flow\n\n  Rule 11    Application        Rules 11 — 18 apply to vessels in sight of\n             (Section II)       one another\n\n  Rule 13    Overtaking         Any vessel overtaking another shall keep out\n                                of the way of the vessel being overtaken. A\n                                vessel is overtaking when coming up from\n                                more than 22.5° abaft the beam\n\n  Rule 14    Head-on situation  When two power-driven vessels are meeting\n                                head-on, each shall alter course to\n                                starboard so that each passes on the port\n                                side of the other\n\n  Rule 15    Crossing situation When two power-driven vessels are crossing,\n                                the vessel which has the other on her\n                                starboard side shall keep out of the way\n                                (give way vessel)\n\n  Rule 16    Action by give-way The give-way vessel shall take early and\n             vessel             substantial action to keep well clear\n\n  Rule 17    Action by stand-on The stand-on vessel shall maintain course\n             vessel             and speed. If the give-way vessel does not\n                                take appropriate action, the stand-on vessel\n                                may take action to avoid collision. In\n                                extremis, the stand-on vessel SHALL take\n                                action\n\n  Rule 18    Responsibilities   Power-driven vessels give way to: sailing\n             between vessels    vessels, vessels engaged in fishing, vessels\n                                not under command, vessels restricted in\n                                ability to manoeuvre. The hierarchy of\n                                priority\n\n  Rule 19    Restricted         When not in sight of another vessel in\n             visibility         restricted visibility, every vessel shall\n                                proceed at safe speed and be ready for\n                                immediate manoeuvre. A vessel detecting\n                                another by radar shall determine if a\n                                close-quarters situation is developing\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.28; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.1.3, p.138*\n\n**Lights, Shapes and Sound Signals**\n\n  **Rule**   **What It Covers**\n\n  Rule 20    Application of lights and shapes rules (sunset to sunrise\n             and restricted visibility)\n\n  Rule 21    Definitions of masthead light, sidelights, sternlight,\n             towing light, all-round light, flashing light\n\n  Rule 23    Power-driven vessels underway: masthead light(s),\n             sidelights, sternlight. Vessels \\<7m \\<7kts: must if\n             practicable show these lights; if not, have a white light\n             ready\n\n  Rule 24    Towing and pushing: additional lights and shapes for vessels\n             engaged in towing\n\n  Rule 25    Sailing vessels underway and vessels under oars\n\n  Rule 26    Fishing vessels: lights and shapes for vessels engaged in\n             fishing (trawling and other methods)\n\n  Rule 27    Vessels not under command (NUC) or restricted in ability to\n             manoeuvre (RAM): red-over-red or red-white-red all-round\n             lights\n\n  Rule 28    Vessels constrained by their draught: three red all-round\n             lights in a vertical line\n\n  Rule 30    Anchored vessels and vessels aground\n\n  Rule 34    Manoeuvring and warning signals: 1 short = altering to\n             starboard, 2 short = altering to port, 3 short = operating\n             astern propulsion, 5+ short = doubt/danger\n\n  Rule 35    Sound signals in restricted visibility: PDV making way = 1\n             prolonged every 2 mins; PDV not making way = 2 prolonged\n             every 2 mins\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, p.28*\n",
  "4.2.1": "## Rope Handling\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify different rope types and their properties                |\n| 2.  Tie the essential knots, bends and hitches                        |\n| 3.  Work safely with ropes under load                                 |\n| 4.  Throw a heaving line/throw bag accurately                         |\n| 5.  Inspect, maintain and stow rope correctly                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Rope Types on the A85\n\n| **Rope** | **Material** | **Properties** | **Used For** |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Anchor warp (82m) | Nylon | High stretch, absorbs shock loads, floats when new | Anchoring, veering |\n| Tow line (66m) | Nylon | High stretch, absorbs shock loads | Towing, anchor extension |\n| GP lines | Polypropylene | Floats, low stretch, lightweight | General purpose, heaving lines |\n| Painter | Polypropylene | Floats, lightweight | Securing alongside |\n\n:::fact KEY ROPE PROPERTIES\n**Nylon**: stretches under load (excellent for anchoring/towing as it absorbs shock). Weakened by UV light over time.\n**Polypropylene**: floats on the surface (easy to recover, won't foul propellers). Lower strength than nylon.\n**Polyester**: low stretch, high strength, good UV resistance. Used in standing rigging.\n:::\n\n### Essential Knots, Bends and Hitches\n\n| **Knot/Bend/Hitch** | **Purpose** | **Key Feature** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bowline** | Creates a non-slip loop for securing to a ring, post, or bollard | Will not jam under load — always easy to untie |\n| **Round turn & two half hitches** | Securing a rope to a rail, ring, or post | Quick to tie, holds well under varying load |\n| **Sheet bend / double sheet bend** | Joining two ropes, especially of unequal size | Double version is more secure — **used to join anchor warp to tow line** |\n| **Clove hitch** | Temporary fastening to a rail, post, or ring | Can slip under heavy or varying load — add half hitches for security |\n| **Rolling hitch** | Takes temporary weight off a loaded line | Holds in one direction, slides in the other |\n| **Figure of eight** | Stopper knot to prevent rope unreeving through a block | Also used to mark the end of a rope |\n\n:::memory\n**\"If you don't know knots, tie lots\"** — but better to learn six knots well than fumble with twenty. The bowline and round turn & two half hitches will cover most situations.\n:::\n\n### Cleat Work\n\nSecuring a line to a cleat is one of the most frequent rope-handling tasks on the A85.\n\n:::steps\n1. Take the line around the **base** of the cleat (the full turn provides the holding power)\n2. Make **figure-of-eight working turns** over the horns of the cleat\n3. **Never use a locking turn** (where the loop is twisted before placing over the horn) — this jams under load and cannot be released quickly\n4. Leave enough tail to prevent the line working free\n:::\n\n:::warning\nDuring anchoring, veering, and towing, you must maintain **at least one full turn on the cleat at all times**. If the line comes off the cleat under tension, it will run free and may cause severe rope burns or loss of the line entirely. Inform the Helm immediately.\n:::\n\n### Working Safely with Ropes Under Load\n\n:::warning\n**Stand clear of ropes under load.** Stand out of the direct line. Never step over or straddle any rope under load. Never take all turns off a cleat or bollard at once. Ease rope out under control.\n:::\n\n- Be aware of **snatch loading** — sudden shock loads when a line comes tight unexpectedly (e.g. towing in waves)\n- Wear **appropriate gloves** when handling lines under load — never bare hands\n- Use a **dagger grip** (small finger towards the cleat) when paying out line under tension — this prevents your hand being pulled into the cleat\n- **Visor down** when handling any line under tension\n- To slip a rope under load: ease out under control until weight is off, then cast off\n\n### Throwing a Heaving Line\n\n:::steps\n1. **Prepare** — uncoil the line, ensure it is free to run\n2. **Split the coil** — hold roughly half in your throwing hand, half in the other\n3. **Aim** — slightly upwind of the target to allow for wind drift\n4. **Throw underarm** with a smooth, sweeping motion — release at approximately 45 degrees\n5. If the throw falls short, **recover quickly** and re-coil for a second attempt\n:::\n\n:::info\nA **throw bag** is easier to throw accurately than a coiled line, especially in wind. The bag should be soaked in water first to add weight.\n:::\n\n### Distance and Accuracy\n\nYou should be able to throw a heaving line or throw bag **at least 15 metres** accurately and consistently. In wind, allow for drift — aim upwind of your target. Practice regularly — this is a perishable skill that degrades quickly without rehearsal.\n\n### Rope Inspection and Maintenance\n\nBefore stowing, inspect for:\n- **Stretching** — permanent elongation indicates the rope has been overloaded\n- **Wear and flattening** — external abrasion from chafing on fairleads and cleats\n- **Crow's footing** — fibres poking out at angles, indicating internal damage\n- **Fraying** — broken strands, particularly at splice points\n- **UV damage** — fading and brittleness (especially nylon)\n- **Chemical contamination** — fuel, oil, or solvents weaken synthetic fibres\n\n**After use**: wash in fresh water, dry thoroughly before stowing. Coil neatly so the rope streams freely when next needed. Never store wet rope in a sealed locker — it will develop mildew.\n",
  "4.3.1": "## Anchoring\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Deploy, monitor, and recover the anchor on the A85                |\n| 2.  Calculate the correct scope for conditions                        |\n| 3.  Recognise when the anchor is holding using transits               |\n| 4.  Recover 50m of anchor warp within approximately 90 seconds        |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Deploying the Anchor — Step by Step\n\n:::steps\n1. **Release the anchor reel** and pull the warp from the channel rope retainer\n2. **Lead the anchor warp through the bow fairlead**, ensuring the **chain is on the seaward side** — this prevents the chain reaching the propellers if it falls overboard\n3. **Make fast** once through the fairlead to prevent the line falling overboard accidentally\n4. **Take up position** on deck aft of the anchor locker lid, back against the sponson, opposite the cleat being used\n5. On the **Helm's command**, secure the locker lid open with the Velcro strap, then **deploy the anchor** over the sponson\n6. **Pay out warp under control**, retaining a minimum of one turn on the cleat at all times. Use a **dagger grip** with the small finger towards the cleat, hands approximately 0.5m from the cleat. **Visor down**\n7. **Pay out warp** equal to at least **6 times the depth**\n8. When the Helm orders, **make fast on the cleat**\n9. The Helm engages **full astern power on both engines** while you **check transits** to confirm holding\n10. Close the anchor locker lid. **Report holding or dragging** to the Helm\n:::\n\n### Recovering the Anchor\n\n:::steps\n1. Helm **motors slowly forward** towards the anchor to relieve tension on the warp\n2. **Recover warp** maintaining turns on the cleat throughout — use the **spring technique** in adverse conditions\n3. In moderate-rough conditions, the **line must be kept on the cleat** throughout recovery. Maintain the boat head to sea using fore and aft power\n4. Once the **chain reaches the fairlead**, make fast the warp on the cleat to prevent chain and engines coming into contact\n5. When the anchor **breaks the surface**, report **\"Anchor aweigh\"** to the Helm\n6. Report **\"Anchor clear\"** or **\"Anchor foul\"** once the anchor is visible\n7. **Stow anchor** and secure all equipment. Close hatches, foredeck clear\n:::\n\n:::fact RECOVERY TIME TARGET\nYou must demonstrate recovering **50m of anchor warp within approximately 90 seconds**.\n:::\n\n#### The Spring Technique\n\nIn adverse conditions when you cannot simply haul the warp in:\n- Use **astern power** to generate tension on the warp\n- **Ease the throttle** — the stretch in the nylon line will pull the boat forward\n- **Recover the slack** created by the spring\n- Repeat until the anchor is recovered\n\n---\n\n### The A85 Anchor System\n\n| **Component** | **Detail** |\n|---|---|\n| Anchor type | **Delta** anchor — excellent holding across various seabed types |\n| Chain | **9 metres** |\n| Warp | **82 metres** of nylon |\n| Total rode | **91 metres** (permanently attached) |\n| Extension | Attach the **66m tow line** using a double sheet bend = **148m total** (reduces tow range) |\n\n### Scope\n\nScope is the ratio of anchor warp deployed relative to the measured water depth.\n\n:::fact MINIMUM SCOPE\n**Warp and chain**: minimum **6× the depth**\n**All-chain**: minimum **4× the depth**\nIn poor weather or for an extended stay, **increase the scope** beyond the minimum.\n:::\n\nYou must also account for the **rise and fall of tide** and the **swinging circle** — the area the boat will swing through as wind and tide change direction.\n\n\n\n### Checking the Anchor is Holding\n\n:::info\n**Transits are the only reliable method.** Two fixed points on shore aligned with each other — if Point B moves behind Point A, the anchor is **dragging**. If both points remain stationary relative to each other, the anchor is **holding**. GPS, radar ranges, and depth alarms can supplement but not replace transits.\n:::\n\nThe Helm slowly engages **full power astern on both engines** whilst you take a transit to confirm the anchor is holding.\n\n### If the Anchor is Dragging\n\n1. **Pay out more warp** first — increasing scope improves holding\n2. If that fails, **recover and redeploy** the anchor\n3. Consider relocating to a different anchorage with better holding ground\n\n### Good vs Poor Holding Ground\n\n| **Good Holding** | **Poor Holding** |\n|---|---|\n| Soft chalk | Soft mud (anchor may plough through) |\n| Clay | Shingle and shell (flukes can't grip) |\n| Sand | Hard rock (flukes can't penetrate) |\n| Heavy mud | Thick weed or kelp |\n\n### Fouled Anchors\n\nAn anchor becomes fouled when it catches on something other than the seabed — foul ground, fishing gear, submarine cables, or another vessel's mooring.\n\n**Recovery methods:**\n- **Reverse or change the angle of pull** — motor past the anchor position and pull from the opposite direction\n- **Shorten or lengthen the scope** as appropriate\n- If recovery is not possible: **buoy it** for later recovery, record the position, and inform the Coastguard and LOM\n\n:::warning\nIf the anchor has fouled a **submarine cable**, do NOT attempt to break it free by force. Report the position to the Coastguard immediately. **Submarine cables carry high voltages and can be lethal if damaged.**\n:::\n\n### Safety\n\n- **Never straddle the anchor warp** or stand in a bight\n- All crew not directly involved must **stand well clear** of all working lines\n- The chain must always be on the **seaward side** of the fairlead to prevent it reaching the propellers\n- **Best time to engage the rope retainer**: while the rope is wet — engage at the seaward end of the slot\n- A vessel at anchor must display a **black ball** in the rigging as far forward as possible (IRPCS)\n\n### Extending the Anchor Line\n\nIf you need greater scope (deep water or heavy weather), attach the **66-metre tow line** from the stern to the anchor warp using a **double sheet bend**. This gives a total of **148 metres**. Be aware that your **tow range is now reduced** — the tow line should be replaced before any towing operation.\n",
  "4.3.2": "### 4.3.2 MANAGE ANCHORING\n\n:::info\nThis module extends the basic anchoring skills from module 4.3.1. You must be competent in the standard anchor deployment and recovery procedures before progressing.\n:::\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Select a safe anchorage using the chart                           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Brief the anchor party and manage deployment                      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Monitor holding using transits, radar, GPS, and depth alarms      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 20. Manage anchor recovery including fouled anchor procedures         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nAnchoring procedures are taught at crew level in the Tier 1 guide. As\nHelm, you must manage the entire operation. This includes selecting the\nanchorage (weather now and forecast, shelter, seabed type, foul ground,\ntidal information, charted depth, other vessels, swinging circle),\ncalculating the required scope (minimum 6× depth for warp and chain,\nadjusted for weather and duration), briefing the anchor party (initial\nbrief, two-way communication, when to let go, expected warp length,\ndirection of lead), monitoring holding (transits are the primary method;\nsupplement with radar ranges, GPS, bearings, depth alarms), and managing\nrecovery (brief crew, safe use of capstan if fitted, correct warp lead,\nanchor stowed and deck clear after recovery, report defects).\n\nIf the anchor drags: pay out more warp first. If that fails, recover and\nredeploy. If the anchor is fouled: attempt to break it out by reversing\nor changing the angle of pull, shorten or lengthen scope. If recovery is\nimpossible: buoy it, record the position, inform the Coastguard and LOM.\nIf a submarine cable is fouled: do NOT attempt to break free by force\n — report immediately.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 4.3.2a — d, pp.146 — 149*\n",
  "4.4.1": "## Veering Down\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Understand when veering is used and why it is dangerous           |\n| 2.  Pay out and manage the anchor warp under tension while veering astern |\n| 3.  Communicate continuously with the Helm throughout the procedure   |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::warning\nVeering is **one of the most dangerous operations the A85 performs**. You are motoring backwards into the surf zone, held by an anchor line, with crew operating warps under tension in confused seas. **Good communication between all crew is the single most important factor in doing this safely.**\n:::\n\n### The Veering Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Preparations**: In open water, clear of the danger area — remove bungees securing anchor/warp/chain. Clip line through the fairlead with chain outermost. Make fast to prevent line falling overboard\n2. **Deploy anchor** as per the standard anchoring procedure. Pay out scope, make fast, check holding with transits\n3. **Helm engages 2/3 to 3/4 astern power**. The speed of approach is determined by the rate of warp deployment by the bow crew\n4. **Bow crew pays out warp** as ordered by the Helm, maintaining turns on the cleat at ALL times. Use a **dagger grip** with the small finger towards the cleat, hands approximately 0.5m away. **Visor down**\n5. **Report continuously** to the Helm: amount paid out, confirmation of holding, incoming waves\n6. **Stern crew dips** to check depth and obstructions, reporting to the Helm continuously using the terms: \"Clear\", \"Contact\", \"Full pole\", \"Half pole\"\n7. Both Helm and bow crew **regularly check transits** — if Point B moves behind Point A, the anchor is dragging\n8. On reaching the casualty position, the Helm orders **\"Hold\"** and the rescue operation begins\n:::\n\n### Recovery After Veering\n\n:::steps\n1. **Keep the boat head to sea at all times** — capsizing risk is highest when beam-on to breaking waves\n2. As soon as safe, **trim down and restart the second engine**\n3. Hold with approximately **2/3 astern power**. Choose a suitable wave — as it reaches the boat, it will stretch the warp\n4. **Reduce astern power as the wave passes** — the boat springs forward from the stored energy in the warp\n5. **Recover the slack** created by the spring\n6. **Repeat** until clear of the surf zone, then recover the anchor normally\n:::\n\n:::warning\nIf anchor recovery would compromise the safety of the boat, the Helm must order the **warp to be cut** and drive out in a safe direction away from the cut line.\n:::\n\n---\n\n### What Is Veering Down?\n\nVeering down is the process of manoeuvring the SAR unit **astern under anchor** to reach a casualty near shore, cliffs, or a harbour wall — situations where the surf or sea conditions prevent a bow-first approach. The anchor line holds the boat's head to sea while the crew pay out warp to move backwards towards the casualty.\n\n### When to Consider Veering\n\nBefore committing, the Helm must consider:\n- **Could another agency** (e.g. cliff rescue) carry out the rescue more effectively and safely?\n- **Availability of other assets** to provide safety cover\n- **Urgency of the situation** — is life at immediate risk?\n- **Sea state and direction** of wind and tide\n- The effect of any **cross current** which may push the boat offline\n\n### Crew Roles During Veering\n\n| **Position** | **Role** |\n|---|---|\n| **Helm** | Maintains 360° lookout, passes commands, drives the boat using 2/3 to 3/4 astern power |\n| **Bow crew** | Pays out the anchor warp under tension. Reports amount paid out, confirms holding, watches for large waves |\n| **Stern crew** | Dips to check depth and obstructions (over the sponson or between sponson and raised engine). Reports continuously to the Helm |\n\n:::info\nTo prevent the boat heeling over, the **dipping crew and warp crew may need to be on alternate sides** — distributing weight counteracts imbalance.\n:::\n\n### Communication During Veering\n\n:::fact STERN CREW TERMINOLOGY\nThe stern crew uses specific terms to avoid confusion with the bow crew's length reports:\n**\"Clear\"** — no obstructions detected\n**\"Contact\"** — seabed or obstruction detected\n**\"Full pole\"** — full pole length of water\n**\"Half pole\"** — half pole length of water\n:::\n\nThe briefing must specifically cover the **terminology to be used** around approaching waves, holding, and paying out — terminology varies between stations.\n\n### Critical Safety Points\n\n- **The warp must remain on the cleat at ALL times.** If it comes off, inform the Helm immediately\n- If big waves are coming through, **lock off the anchor warp** on the cleat\n- If the crew member cannot hold the warp as power increases, inform the Helm — on their command, **add an extra turn under the aft horn of the cleat**\n- **All preparations must be made in open water**, clear of the danger area\n- The anchor must be deployed **directly up-sea of the casualty**, allowing the boat to veer down-sea towards it — not across\n- At **no point** should the lifeboat be in the surf zone without an anchor that has been tested and is confirmed to be holding\n\n### Single-Engine Veering\n\n- The engine closest to the danger is **shut down and fully trimmed up**\n- Where both engines could be used, prefer the **starboard engine** — this protects the steering ram on the port engine\n- The kill cord does not need to be replaced for the tilted engine until in safer water\n- **Crew weight distribution** helps manoeuvre when running on a single engine\n\n### Extending the Warp\n\nIf the anchor warp (82m) is insufficient, the **66m towline** can be used:\n1. Lead the towline along the starboard deck\n2. Secure to the port foredeck cleat\n3. Attach to the anchor warp using a **double sheet bend**\n4. When ready, take the anchor warp off the starboard cleat and continue paying out from the port cleat\n",
  "4.4.2": "### 4.4.2 MANAGE VEERING DOWN\n\n:::warning\nVeering into a surf zone is one of the **highest-risk operations** the A85 performs. The advanced module builds on 4.4.1 — ensure that module is thoroughly understood before progressing.\n:::\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 21. Decide when veering is the safest method to reach a casualty      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 22. Command the veering procedure including crew positioning and      |\n|     communications                                                    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 23. Manage the recovery from the surf zone                            |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nVeering procedure and crew roles are taught at crew level in the Tier 1\nguide. As Helm, you are driving the boat astern into the surf zone while\nmanaging the anchor warp and monitoring crew safety. The specific A85\nprocedure from the Veering Down SOP:\n\n-   Shut down the engine closest to the danger and fully trim it up.\n    Once stopped, reset the RUN/OFF switch to allow quick restarting if\n    needed. The kill cord does not need to be replaced for the engine\n    that has been tilted up until in safer water\n\n-   Where both engines could be used, prefer the starboard engine — \n    this protects the steering ram on the port engine\n\n-   Crew weight distribution helps manoeuvre when running on single\n    engine\n\n-   Maintain approximately two-thirds astern power on the selected\n    engine to take maximum stretch from the warp while leaving power in\n    reserve\n\n-   The crew member in the bow pays out warp at your command,\n    maintaining turns on the cleat. If the warp comes off the cleat,\n    they must inform you immediately\n\n-   The third crew member removes the dipping pole from stowage,\n    assembles the two parts, positions at the stern with their body\n    fully in the boat, and dips over the side nearest the hazard to\n    check depth and obstructions, reporting continuously\n\n-   To prevent the boat heeling over, it may be necessary for the crew\n    dipping and the crew paying out line to be on alternate sides\n\n-   If the anchor warp is insufficient, the towline can be used: lead it\n    along the starboard deck, secure to the port foredeck cleat, attach\n    to the anchor warp using a double sheet bend. When ready, take the\n    anchor warp off the starboard cleat and continue paying out from the\n    port cleat\n\n*Source: 85-SOP-Veering Down V6.0, p.4; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.4.2, p.151*\n\n**Exiting the Surf Zone and Recovering the Anchor**\n\n-   Keep the boat head to sea at all times during exit — capsizing\n    risk is highest when beam-on to breaking waves\n\n-   As soon as safe, trim down and restart the second engine\n\n-   Hold with approximately two-thirds astern power. Choose a suitable\n    wave — as it reaches the boat, it will help stretch the warp\n\n-   Reduce astern power as the wave passes beneath, allowing the boat to\n    spring forward. The slack created is then recovered by the bow crew\n\n-   Repeat until clear of the surf zone, then recover the anchor in the\n    normal way\n\n*Source: 85-SOP-Veering Down V6.0, p.4*\n",
  "4.5.1": "## Towing\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Rig and pass a tow line on the Atlantic 85                        |\n| 2.  Secure, monitor and manage a tow under way                        |\n| 3.  Transfer from astern tow to alongside tow                         |\n| 4.  Release a tow under normal and emergency conditions               |\n| 5.  Understand the RNLI towing policy and the dangers of lines under load |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Astern Tow — Quick Reference Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Lower the tow bar** — reach underneath the A-frame and unfasten the two bungee cords\n2. **Pass the towline through the A-frame**, above the guide bar and between the two webbing strops. Bring the end around the outside onto the aft deck\n3. **Prepare approximately 5m of line** — enough to reach, not so much it tangles or drops in the water\n4. **Attach to the bollard** in a helter-skelter pattern (spiral wrapping for controlled pay-out)\n5. **Attach a heaving line** or throw bag to the end of the tow line for passing\n6. **Position the A85** — Helm maintains head to sea when passing the tow\n7. **Pass the tow line** to the casualty vessel. Keep hold of the inboard end. Keep the line clear of propellers at all times\n8. **Casualty makes fast** to their strongest point — bow bitts, anchor winch, or deck cleats. Rig a **bridle** if no single strong point\n9. **Pay out towline** under control — appropriate length for conditions and vessel size. Maintain turns on the bollard\n10. **Make fast** with figure-of-eight working turns (NOT locking turns). Helm eases throttle first to take tension off\n11. **Take up the tow gradually** — increase speed slowly until the line comes under tension. Never bar tight — maintain a visible dip\n12. **Monitor continuously** — chafe at both ends, casualty vessel behaviour, line tension. Freshen the nip regularly\n:::\n\n### Alongside Tow — Quick Reference\n\n:::steps\n1. Shorten the astern tow first, taking great care not to foul propellers\n2. Position so the A85 stern is **astern of the casualty** (for steerage)\n3. **Bow line** — casualty bow to A85 bow, through fairlead, secured to the bow cleat on the opposite side\n4. **Bow spring** — A85 bow to casualty stern (same line as bow line, leave slack between cleats)\n5. Use ahead power to tension lines 1 and 2 while attaching the remaining lines\n6. **Stern line** — casualty stern to A85 stern on the bollard (use a GP line)\n7. **Stern spring** — A85 stern to casualty bow\n8. **Rig plenty of fenders** between the vessels\n:::\n\n### Emergency Tow Release\n\n:::steps\n1. Take off the figure-of-eight turns\n2. Allow the line to **surge away under control** until all line has paid out\n3. The **weak link** will part during this procedure\n4. If surging is not possible, **cut the rope** near the bollard as a last resort — crew must NOT be aft of the cut point\n:::\n\n:::warning\nA crew member must be **assigned and ready to release the tow at ANY time** throughout the entire towing operation. This is not something you think about only when things go wrong.\n:::\n\n---\n\n### 4.5.1 TOWING\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Rig and pass a tow line on the Atlantic 85                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 2.  Secure, monitor and manage a tow under way                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 3.  Transfer from astern tow to alongside tow                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 4.  Release a tow under normal and emergency conditions               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 5.  Understand the RNLI towing policy and the dangers of lines under  |\n|     load                                                              |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**When and Why We Tow**\n\nThe RNLI policy on towing is clear: a tow must only be undertaken as\npart of an attempt to save life. Exceptionally, a tow may be undertaken\nif an abandoned vessel would pose a significant risk to navigation. A\ncasualty vessel must be taken to the nearest safe haven (agreed before\ntowing begins), and towing by lifeboat must not be conducted if a tug or\nother suitable vessel can be summoned without undue delay.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.2a, p.156; Policy PO1026*\n\n**Evaluating Whether to Tow**\n\nBefore any tow is attempted, the Helm must evaluate whether towing is\nthe right course of action. This is not automatic — there are\nsituations where towing is more dangerous than the alternatives:\n\n  **Question to Ask**  **What You're Really Deciding**\n\n  Is towing the best   Could the casualties be taken off and the vessel\n  option?              left? Would it be safer to stand by and wait for a\n                       commercial tug?\n\n  Is the casualty      Is it taking on water? Is there structural damage?\n  vessel seaworthy     Could it sink during the tow? Check the condition\n  enough to tow?       and draft of the casualty\n\n  What are the         Weather limits for towing exercises: daylight wind\n  conditions?          F6 max, night/darkness F4 max. Astern tow sea\n                       state limit 2.5m (ILB). Alongside tow sea state\n                       limit 0.5m\n\n  Are there adequate   Can the casualty vessel take the loads? Check\n  strong points?       fairleads, cleats, winches, and bollards on the\n                       casualty before committing\n\n  What is the distance A casualty must be taken to the nearest safe\n  to safe haven?       haven, agreed before towing begins. Can the A85's\n                       fuel endurance cover the distance at towing speed?\n\n  Is the crew          Do you have enough experienced crew to manage\n  competent for this?  lines, monitor the tow, and handle an emergency\n                       release?\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.2a, p.156; A85 Towing SOP V5.0, p.2; TP-OCF-03, Towing Exercise Form, p.88*\n\n> **The Helm's number one priority during any towing operation MUST be\n> crew safety. The final decision to tow rests with the Helm. The safest\n> option may be not to attempt to tow, particularly if the casualty is\n> aground or fouled on structures. The towing checklist must be used.**\n\n*Source: A85 Towing SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n**The ILB Towing Check Card (TP-LB-28, Card 3)**\n\nThe ILB Decision Support Check Cards are carried on the boat and must be\nused during towing operations. Card 3 is a two-part towing decision aid.\nThe first part asks 'CAN we tow?' and the second asks 'SHOULD we tow?'\nYou need to understand both parts because as crew, you will be asked to\nhelp the Helm work through them.\n\n**Part 1: CAN We Tow?**\n\nThis is a sequential decision gate. The Helm (Commander + 1 crew member)\nworks through these questions in order. At any point, a 'No' answer may\nmean you do NOT tow:\n\n-   First: are we in a safe location? Do NOT tow if the casualty is\n    aground or sinking\n\n-   Is there anyone on board the casualty? If yes, assess their\n    condition and prompt them to put on lifejackets. If no one is aboard\n    and no one is in danger — do NOT tow\n\n-   Does the location present a risk to third parties? (busy shipping\n    channel/TSS, busy anchorage?)\n\n-   Is anyone in potential danger? If no — do NOT tow\n\n-   Is towing the safest viable option? Consider alternatives:\n    anchor/secure/escort the vessel, deck transfer or daughter craft,\n    shore assets, helicopter. If towing is not the safest option — do\n    NOT tow\n\n-   Are YOU the most suitable asset to tow? Could a commercial vessel or\n    another lifeboat do it? What is their ETA? Would the delay\n    compromise safety?\n\n-   Is permission required to enter the nearest suitable safe haven? If\n    yes, request the Coastguard to liaise with the harbour authority\n\n-   Has the master/owner agreed to the tow?\n\n*Source: TP-LB-28, Card 3 — Towing: CAN We Tow?*\n\n**Part 2: SHOULD We Tow?**\n\nIf you pass all the gates in Part 1, you then assess the risk level\nacross six factors, rating each as Low, Medium, or High:\n\n  **Risk Factor**      **What to Assess**\n\n  Vessel size and      Hull damage, water ingress, stability, suitability\n  condition            of strong points, draft, weight, rigging or gear\n                       secured?\n\n  Environment          Wind, sea, visibility, night, temperature,\n                       hazards, depths, lee shore, traffic?\n\n  Distance of tow      Fuel reserves, crew fatigue, casualty comfort?\n\n  Establishing the tow Astern and/or alongside? Complexity of the setup?\n\n  Likelihood of        Casualty condition, vessel condition,\n  conditions worsening environmental conditions — will any of these get\n                       worse during the tow?\n\n  Crew                 Does the crew lack relatable experience to any of\n                       the above factors?\n\nAfter scoring each factor, the Helm must answer the fundamental\nquestion: does the benefit outweigh the risk? If the answer is no, do\nnot tow. Record the vessel name, length, draft, time tow established,\nand time vessel secured in safe location on the card.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-28, Card 3 — Towing: SHOULD We Tow?*\n\n**The FOR-DEC Decision Making Model (TP-LB-28, Card 7)**\n\nCard 7 of the ILB Decision Support Check Cards provides a structured\ndecision-making model used throughout RNLI operations, not just towing.\nIt is called FOR-DEC:\n\n  **Step**         **Action**         **Key Questions**\n\n  F — Facts       Gather the facts   Who? What? Where? When?\n                                      Weather/Tides?\n\n  O — Options     Identify all       Alternatives? Other assets? Go or No\n                   options            Go?\n\n  R — Weigh risks        Hazards? Time pressures? Casualty\n  Risks/Benefits   against benefits   care? Priority of rescue?\n\n  D — Decide      Make the decision  SMEAC briefing. Update the\n                                      Coastguard\n\n  E — Execute     Carry out the plan Execute as per SOP. Closed-loop\n                                      communications. Cross-check\n\n  C — Check       Continuously       Why are we doing this? Are we\n                   review             getting what we expected? Do the\n                                      benefits still outweigh the risks?\n                                      Pause — is there anything we've\n                                      missed?\n\n*Source: TP-LB-28, Card 7 — Decision Making Model (FOR-DEC)*\n\n> **The 'Check' step is continuous. It does not happen once — it\n> happens throughout the entire operation. Conditions change, casualties\n> deteriorate, equipment fails. The decision to continue must be\n> actively revalidated, not assumed.**\n\n**General Preparation Before Any Tow**\n\nBefore rigging the tow, the following must be done:\n\n-   Establish VHF communications with the casualty vessel\n\n-   Brief the crew on: type of tow, conditions, strong points on the\n    casualty, and allocate specific tasks to each crew member\n\n-   Remove the towing equipment from stowage and check for damage. If\n    the equipment is not in good condition, it MUST NOT be used\n\n-   Inspect the casualty vessel for hazards, damage, or suspicious\n    activity. Report via VHF to the Coastguard. Use the on-board camera\n    to document the vessel and occupants if required\n\n-   Consider the use of a casualty drogue (if carried)\n\n-   Alert other marine traffic: use VHF communications. In poor\n    visibility or low light, consider using a searchlight to illuminate\n    the tow line\n\n*Source: A85 Towing SOP V5.0, p.2; Working with a Casualty Vessel SOP V5.0, p.2*\n\n**The Astern Tow — Step by Step**\n\n**Rope Terminology You Must Know**\n\nBefore learning to tow, you need the language of ropework. These terms\nare used constantly during towing operations and if you do not\nunderstand them, you cannot follow instructions safely:\n\n  **Danger**        **How to Minimise It**\n\n  Lines under load  Keep all personnel clear of the tow line. Establish a\n  parting           No-Go area around the towing point. Stay inside the\n                    wheelhouse/console area if possible — safest place\n                    if the line parts\n\n  Standing in       Never stand in a bight. Keep deck clear of coiled\n  bights or coils   line. Allocate one crew to line management\n\n  Crush injuries    Use adequate fenders. Keep inboard of sponsons. Never\n  alongside         place hands between vessels\n\n  Fouling           Keep tow line clear of stern gear during setup,\n  propellers        shortening, and release. Helm to use minimum revs\n                    when crew are handling lines\n\n  Chafe causing     Freshen the nip regularly. Use fairleads. Apply\n  failure           chafing covers. Monitor BOTH ends\n\n  Casualty veering  Deploy casualty drogue from the casualty's stern.\n  off course        Assists vessels with no steering, prevents surfing\n                    and broaching\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.1b, p.153; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.219 — 222*\n\n> **NEVER tow from the rope reel itself or from the A-frame cleats. The\n> towing bollard and aft lifting points are the only load-bearing\n> securing points on the A85.**\n",
  "4.5.2": "## Towing Alongside and Escort\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Transfer from an astern tow to an alongside tow                  |\n| 2.  Secure the A85 alongside a casualty vessel                        |\n| 3.  Escort a vessel safely to port                                    |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Alongside Tow Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Shorten the astern tow** first — recover line carefully to prevent propeller fouling\n2. Position the A85 so its stern is **astern of the casualty's stern** (for steerage)\n3. The side of approach depends on wind and tide — approach into the elements\n4. **Bow line**: Casualty bow → through A85 bow fairlead → A85 bow cleat (opposite side)\n5. **Bow spring**: A85 bow → Casualty stern (using the same line, leaving slack between cleats)\n6. Use **ahead power** to tension lines 1 and 2 while attaching remaining lines\n7. **Stern line**: Casualty stern → A85 stern bollard (use a GP line)\n8. **Stern spring**: A85 stern → Casualty bow\n9. **Rig plenty of fenders** between the two vessels\n:::\n\n:::warning\nThe A85 stern must always be **behind the casualty vessel's stern**. If the A85 is pushed forward, the lashed vessels may pivot uncontrollably. This is the most critical positioning point.\n:::\n\n- — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — - — — +\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 24. Evaluate the decision to tow using the ILB Towing Check Card      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 25. Command the rigging, passing, securing, monitoring, and release   |\n|     of a tow                                                          |\n|                                                                       |\n| 26. Decide when and how to transfer crew to the casualty vessel       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 27. Manage the transition from astern to alongside tow                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 28. Manage the delivery of the casualty to a safe haven including     |\n|     harbour authority liaison                                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nThe complete towing procedure (all phases from evaluation through\nrelease) and the ILB Towing Check Card (CAN We Tow / SHOULD We Tow) are\ntaught in extreme detail in the Tier 1 guide. As Helm, every element of\nthat procedure is your responsibility to direct. The specific\ncommand-level additions are:\n\n**Positioning the A85 to Pass the Tow**\n\nHow you position the A85 depends on the casualty's orientation:\n\n  **Casualty           **Your Approach**\n  Orientation**        \n\n  Casualty lying head  Come alongside if conditions permit — this is\n  to sea               the most controlled position for passing the line\n\n  Casualty lying       Cross the T — approach across the bow or stern\n  beam-on to sea       of the casualty at right angles\n\n  Casualty running     Approach from downwind/down-sea\n  with wind/sea        \n\n  Casualty at anchor   Come alongside on the lee side\n  or on sea anchor     \n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.2b, p.158*\n\n**Assessing the Casualty Vessel's Stability**\n\nBefore committing to a tow, assess the casualty for stability and\nbuoyancy problems:\n\n-   Signs: pitching and rolling excessively, heeling to one side,\n    sitting lower than normal waterline, history of grounding\n\n-   If boarding the casualty: do NOT go below decks if stability is in\n    doubt. Risk vs benefit must be assessed\n\n-   Towing a vessel with stability issues: a grounded vessel may be\n    holed — towing it clear could cause it to sink. A wallowing vessel\n    under tow affects the handling and stability of the A85. A vessel\n    that sinks under tow will drag the A85 with it unless the tow is\n    released immediately\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.2a, pp.156 — 157*\n\n**Communications During a Tow**\n\nAs Helm, you must maintain communications with: the casualty vessel\n(discuss nature of problem, injury/POB, destination, ability to rig tow,\nrequirement for crew transfer, brief on conduct of tow), the Coastguard\n(progress, ETA, fuel state, weather changes), the harbour authority at\nthe destination (request entry, report pollution risk, fire, or flooding\non the casualty), and your own crew (continuous updates, changes to\nplan, safety warnings). If declined entry to a harbour, inform the\nCoastguard and agree an alternative safe haven.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 4.5.2a — c, pp.156 — 160*\n",
  "4.6.1": "### 4.6.1 STABILITY INTRODUCTION\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Understand how buoyancy and stability work on a vessel            |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Know the free surface effect and why water sloshing inside a      |\n|     vessel is dangerous                                               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Understand how uneven or shifting loads affect stability          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nStability is the ability of a vessel to return to upright after being\nheeled over by an external force (wave, wind, weight shift). A vessel\nloses stability when its centre of gravity moves too high, or when\nfree-moving liquid inside the vessel shifts the centre of gravity\nunexpectedly.\n\n**Free Surface Effect**\n\nWhen water, fuel, or any liquid moves freely inside a vessel, it shifts\nto the low side as the vessel rolls — this amplifies the roll and\nreduces the vessel's ability to right itself. This is the free surface\neffect, and it is why flooding is so dangerous. Even a small amount of\nwater sloshing freely can have a disproportionate effect on stability.\nThis is also why fuel tanks are divided and why watertight integrity\nmust be maintained.\n\n**Shifting Loads**\n\nAny load that moves — an unsecured casualty, loose equipment, a heavy\npump sliding across the deck — amplifies normal vessel movement and\ncan create instability. Loads must be evenly distributed and secured.\nWhen loading casualties, spread them evenly and secure them to prevent\nmovement.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.6.1a, p.162*\n\n**Flooding**\n\nFlooding is the uncontrolled entry of water into the vessel. It reduces\nbuoyancy (the boat sits lower) and introduces the free surface effect\n(water sloshing reduces stability). If you identify flooding:\n\n-   Sound the alarm and alert all crew\n\n-   Identify the location and source of incoming water\n\n-   Shore up the area to stem the flow — bungs, patches, improvised\n    tools\n\n-   Cut off electrical supply running through the flooded area if\n    possible\n\n-   Check bilge pump for operation; start the salvage pump if available\n\n-   Maintain VHF watch on Ch16 and confirm SAR unit position\n\n-   Contact the Coastguard using the appropriate transmission (distress\n    or urgency)\n\n-   If the flooding cannot be controlled, prepare for abandonment\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.2a, p.88*\n\n**Being Holed (Collision or Grounding)**\n\nIf the vessel is holed through collision or grounding:\n\n-   Sound the alarm and alert all crew\n\n-   Manoeuvre the vessel to minimise the effects of the collision (if\n    still mobile)\n\n-   Switch on deck lighting at night\n\n-   Check for fire and damage\n\n-   Sound bilges and tanks for water ingress\n\n-   Visually inspect compartments where possible\n\n-   If another vessel was hit, offer assistance to that vessel\n\n-   Maintain VHF watch and contact the Coastguard\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.2a, pp.87 — 88*\n",
  "4.6.2": "### 4.6.2 HYDROLOGY AND HULL TYPES\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Understand wave formation and the factors that affect wave size   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 20. Know how headlands, beaches, shoals, and current affect wave      |\n|     shape                                                             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 21. Identify the three types of breaking wave and their dangers       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 22. Understand the characteristics of different hull types and        |\n|     propulsion systems                                                |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nUnderstanding why the sea behaves the way it does is essential for safe\nboat handling. This module gives you the physics behind what you feel\nunder the boat. When you know that waves break when the depth equals 1.3\ntimes the wave height, you can predict where the surf line will be. When\nyou know that a headland compresses tidal flow and creates overfalls,\nyou can avoid them.\n\n**Wave Formation**\n\nWaves are created by three factors: wind strength (stronger wind =\nbigger waves), wind direction (waves travel in the direction the wind\nblows), and wind duration (wind blowing for longer builds bigger waves).\nThe size of waves also depends on the fetch — the distance of open\nwater over which the wind blows.\n\n**How the Seabed Affects Waves**\n\n  **Feature**   **Effect on Waves**         **Danger**\n\n  Headlands     Compression of tidal flow.  Unpredictable, steep seas. Can\n                Shoaling. Increased         capsize. Worse when wind is\n                current. Overfalls. Steep   against the tide\n                breaking waves.             \n                Wind-over-tide conditions   \n\n  Shoals        Overfalls. Breaking waves.  Similar to headlands but can\n                Increased current.          appear in open water with no\n                Wind-over-tide conditions   visual warning. Check the\n                                            chart\n\n  Beaches       Waves interact with the     Surf zone forms. Lateral\n  (shallow      seabed. Wave size           currents and rip currents.\n  gradient)     increases. Waves break when Conditions change with tide\n                depth = 1.3 × wave height.  \n                Gradual shoaling = gradual  \n                breaking                    \n\n  Beaches       Same interaction but sudden Plunging/dumping waves form.\n  (steep        depth change = sudden wave  More violent than spilling\n  gradient)     breaking                    waves. Higher capsize risk\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.6.2a, pp.163 — 164; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.194 — 197*\n\n**Types of Breaking Wave**\n\n  **Type**      **How It Breaks**              **Danger Level**\n\n  Surging wave  Does not break in the          Can knock crew off their\n                conventional sense. The wave   feet on the beach. Powerful\n                front simply surges up the     undertow on the backwash\n                beach. Occurs on very steep    \n                beaches                        \n\n  Plunging /    The wave crest curls over and  Most dangerous. Extremely\n  dumping wave  falls onto the face of the     powerful. Can capsize the\n                wave. Occurs on steep beaches  A85. The weight and impact\n                with sudden depth change       of water is enormous\n\n  Spilling wave The crest spills down the      Less violent than plunging\n                front of the wave. Occurs on   waves but still dangerous.\n                shallow, gently sloping        The surf zone is wider\n                beaches                        \n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.196 — 197*\n\nRip currents form where water that has been pushed onto the beach by\nwaves flows back out to sea through gaps in the surf line. They are\nnarrow, fast-moving channels that can pull a person or small vessel out\nto sea. They are often visible as a darker, flatter channel in the surf\nwith foam moving seaward.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.197*\n\n**Hull Types and Propulsion**\n\n  **Type**            **Characteristics**          **A85 Relevance**\n\n  Planing hull        Higher speed in good         The A85 is a planing\n                      conditions. Shallow V-hull   hull. It rides on top\n                      may slam in heavy waves.     of the water at speed\n                      Twin engines give improved   rather than pushing\n                      turning                      through it\n\n  Displacement hull   Reduced top speed. Good      Typical of larger\n                      sea-keeping. Inclined to     yachts and commercial\n                      roll                         vessels you will\n                                                   encounter as casualties\n\n  Semi-displacement   Good sea-keeping with        Some larger motor\n  hull                moderate speed. Needs a lot  yachts. Be aware of\n                      of power to go fast. Long    their limited\n                      keel / small rudders give    manoeuvrability when\n                      reduced turning              coming alongside\n  **Propulsion**   **Benefits**                **Dangers**\n\n  Outboard motors  Steerable power,            Petrol fire risk. Moving\n  (A85)            self-contained, easily      parts hazardous for persons\n                   changed, exposed            in the water. Easily\n                                               damaged. Can be fouled\n\n  Twin screw       Simple, reliable            Can be fouled. Loss of\n  (inboard)                                    drive in aerated water\n                                               (e.g. in surf)\n\n  Jet drive        Good manoeuvrability,       Moving control parts.\n                   shallow water operation     High-pressure water flow.\n                                               Loss of steerage at low\n                                               speed\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.6.2b, pp.164 — 165*\n\n**Vessel Interaction**\n\nWhen two vessels are in close proximity, positive and negative pressure\nzones interact. Positive zones (bow wave, stern wave) repel each other.\nNegative zones (the trough between them) attract. This means:\n\n-   Passing a large vessel close on the same heading: your bow is pushed\n    away at the stern of the other vessel, then your stern swings out as\n    you pass amidships, turning you INTO the large vessel\n\n-   Passing a large vessel on opposite headings: your bow is pushed\n    away, then your stern is pushed out, turning you ACROSS the bow of\n    the other vessel\n\nAs crew, you must be aware of these forces and alert the Helm if you\nobserve the boat being forced into a dangerous position.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.190*\n",
  "4.7.1": "### 4.7.1 HELMING 1\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Identify and operate all A85 helm controls and instruments        |\n| 2.  Steer and maintain a compass course                               |\n| 3.  Alter speed and course safely with correct communications         |\n| 4.  Execute a man overboard recovery manoeuvre                        |\n| 5.  Transfer helm control between crew members                        |\n| 6.  Rig and use the A85 emergency steering system                     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Man Overboard Recovery — Helm Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Reduce speed immediately** and prepare to manoeuvre\n2. Crew will shout, point, and press the **MOB alarm** (records position on SIMS)\n3. **Turn down-sea** and assess the MOB's position\n4. **Approach at slow speed** from downwind/down-sea\n5. Use the **engine furthest from the casualty** — this keeps the near-side propeller stationary\n6. Make contact on the vessel's **shoulder** (forward quarter)\n7. Guide the casualty **aft to the 4th seat area** where sponsons are lower\n8. When in contact with the casualty, **engines must be in neutral**\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**NEVER reverse directly towards a person in the water** with a propeller-driven vessel. This is the only MOB manoeuvre that must never be attempted.\n:::\n\n### Emergency Steering Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Reduce power** and bring the lifeboat to a stop when safe\n2. **Isolate the steering hydraulics** at the valve under the flap in the centre of the trunking (midway between 4th seat and stern)\n3. **Remove the emergency tiller** — the orange pole with the red band (reinforced section)\n4. **Insert into the starboard engine bracket**, ensuring the retaining button engages\n5. The crew member operating the tiller communicates with the Helm using voice, intercom, or hand signals\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**NEVER** open or operate the bypass valve at high speeds — the engines may go hard over. **Reduce to stop first.**\n:::\n\n---\n\n**Helm Controls and Instruments**\n\nYou must be able to identify and operate every control on the A85 helm\nconsole. These were introduced in Safe to Go Afloat (Stage 2) but now\nyou must be able to use them under operational conditions:\n\n  **Control**        **What It Does**        **Key Points for Helming**\n\n  Steering wheel     Hydraulically operates  Thumbs on top to prevent\n                     a ram attached to the   breakage. The wheel steers\n                     engines, turning them   the engines, not a rudder\n                     for steering            \n\n  Throttle levers    Control each engine     Neutral is the safe default.\n  (port/starboard)   individually: gear      Forward for ahead, back for\n                     selection, power, and   astern. Use small, smooth\n                     idle                    adjustments\n\n  Compass            Magnetic compass for    Your primary heading\n                     headings                reference. Electronic systems\n                                             can fail\n\n  Tachometers        Engine rev display, oil Monitor continuously. Oil\n  (port/starboard)   pressure warning,       pressure warning = shut down\n                     trim/tilt indicator,    engine where safe\n                     fault codes             \n\n  Trim/tilt selector Enables lifting of      Trim up in shallow water.\n  switch             individual or both      Trim affects boat attitude\n                     engines via the up/down and speed\n                     switch on the throttles \n\n  Depth sounder      Displays depth from     Check LOP for local offset\n                     hull-mounted transducer settings. Set the depth alarm\n\n  Nav repeater       Displays information    Secondary information source\n                     from SIMS: course to — compass is primary\n                     steer, waypoint info,   \n                     compass (True)          \n\n  Water ballast      Three positions: Fill,  Fill when transiting up-sea\n  (waterscoop lever) Hold, Drain. Controls   (improves bow weight). Drain\n                     the 270kg bow ballast   when transiting down-sea or\n                     tank                    for net recovery. Optimum\n                                             speed 3000 — 3500 rpm (15 — 18\n                                             knots)\n\n  MOB alarm          Push and hold to        Also records position on\n                     activate. Light on      SIMS. Cancel button silences\n                     console + audible alarm audible BUT warning light\n                                             stays on\n\n  Start/stop buttons Green = start (push and Always check neutral before\n                     hold). Red = stop       starting. Prime fuel bulbs\n                     (press and hold until   first. Check tell-tale for\n                     engine completely       coolant flow\n                     stops)                  \n\n  Couple batteries   Links port and          Use if one bank fails. Single\n  button             starboard battery banks bank alarm sounds if only one\n                     while pressed           isolator is on\n\n  Light switches     Navigation lights, deck Navigation lights ON at night\n                     lights (fore/aft),      or restricted visibility.\n                     forward lights, blue    Blue flash per current policy\n                     flashing light          only\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 4, pp.38 — 40; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.1a, p.165*\n\n**Steering and Maintaining a Course**\n\nMethods for maintaining a course on the A85:\n\n-   Compass — the primary method. Steer to the compass heading given\n    by the navigator or Helm. Account for the difference between compass\n    and true headings (variation and deviation)\n\n-   Transit — two fixed objects on shore aligned with each other. Keep\n    them aligned to stay on track\n\n-   Visual reference — steer towards a visible landmark or feature\n\n-   Auto pilot — not fitted to the A85, but be aware that on vessels\n    with auto pilot, rapid course changes can occur\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.1b, p.166*\n\n**Altering Speed and Course**\n\nBefore any alteration, you must:\n\n-   Look around, especially astern — check for vessels, obstructions,\n    or persons in the water\n\n-   Check along the new heading — is it clear?\n\n-   Consider the effect of your actions on others — crew, casualty\n    vessels, other traffic\n\n-   Warn the crew — sudden turns at speed can throw unsecured crew\n    overboard\n\n-   Only alter course if safe to do so\n\n**Communications when changing course:**\n\nThe exchange must follow closed-loop communication:\n\n-   Navigator/Commander to Helm: 'New course, turn to Port 090°'\n\n-   Helm repeats: 'Port 090°' (confirms correct hearing)\n\n-   When on course: 'Steering Port 090°' (confirms completion)\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.192; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.1b, p.166*\n\n**Man Overboard Recovery — Helming Perspective**\n\nAs Helm during a MOB, your immediate actions are:\n\n-   1\\. Reduce speed immediately\n\n-   2\\. Prepare to manoeuvre\n\n-   3\\. Crew will shout, point, and press the MOB alarm\n\n-   4\\. Turn down-sea and assess the MOB's position\n\n-   5\\. Approach at slow speed\n\n-   6\\. Make contact with the MOB on the vessel's shoulder, using the\n    engine furthest away from the casualty (this keeps the propeller on\n    the casualty's side stationary)\n\n-   7\\. Move the casualty aft for recovery over the lowest point of the\n    deck (4th seat area, port side)\n\n-   8\\. When in contact with the casualty, engines must be in neutral\n\n> **An MOB is a dynamic situation and there is no single correct method.\n> When the MOB is back onboard, it is a success. The ONLY manoeuvre that\n> must NEVER be attempted is reversing directly towards the casualty\n> with a propeller-driven vessel.**\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.192 — 193; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.1d, p.168*\n\n**Transferring Helm Control**\n\nOn the A85, control is only transferred when the boat is stopped and in\nneutral. The handover procedure:\n\n-   1\\. Ensure the new helm is in position at the console\n\n-   2\\. Communications established (intercom)\n\n-   3\\. Pass over: current course, current speed/throttle setting,\n    navigational dangers, minimum expected depth, and any other\n    pertinent information\n\n-   4\\. The new helm confirms they have control: 'I have the helm'\n\n-   5\\. The outgoing helm confirms: 'You have the helm'\n\n-   6\\. Maintain control until successfully transferred — never leave\n    the helm unattended during handover\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.1c, p.167; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.191*\n\n**A85 Emergency Steering**\n\nIf the hydraulic steering fails, the A85 has a manual bypass system. The\nprocedure from the Emergency Procedures EOP:\n\n-   1\\. Immediately reduce power and bring the lifeboat to a stop when\n    safe to do so\n\n-   2\\. Isolate the steering hydraulics at the valve located under the\n    flap in the centre of the trunking, midway between the 4th crew seat\n    and the stern\n\n-   3\\. Remove the emergency steering tiller (marked with a red band)\n    from its stowage. Note: there are two similar sections — the\n    orange pole with the red band is the tiller due to its reinforcement\n\n-   4\\. Insert the tiller handle into the starboard engine bracket,\n    ensuring the retaining button engages properly\n\n-   5\\. The crew member operating the tiller may use a partially\n    inflated casualty lifejacket to support their knee for longer\n    durations\n\n-   6\\. The helm communicates required steering actions using voice,\n    intercom, or agreed hand signals\n\n> **There is a chance that if the steering system fails or is set to\n> bypass, the engines may go hard over when operating at speed. The\n> bypass valve is NEVER to be opened or operated whilst operating at\n> high speeds. Reduce to stop first.**\n\n*Source: 85-EOP-Emergency Procedures V6.0, p.6; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.2d, p.172*\n",
  "4.7.2": "### 4.7.2 HELMING 2\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 29. Manoeuvre the A85 in confined areas using both engines and        |\n|     forward/astern power                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 30. Handle the A85 in heavy weather within operational limits         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 31. Come alongside another vessel at sea (slow speed transfer)        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 32. Rig, use, and de-rig the emergency steering system                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 33. Change a propeller while afloat                                   |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Confined Space Manoeuvring**\n\nYou must demonstrate the ability to control the A85 in confined areas\n(harbours, marinas, narrow channels) using the wheel, both engines\nindependently, and forward and astern propulsion, while accounting for\nwind, tide, and other external forces. Where location allows,\ndemonstrate manoeuvring alongside and departing safely in a variety of\nconditions. The training session plan emphasises: 'Slow is pro' (driving\nslowly is more professional and safer), and 'steer then gear' (make the\nsteering input before the throttle input).\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.2a, p.169; TP-OCF-03, Session Plan: Helming, p.51*\n\n**Heavy Weather Handling**\n\nThe A85 operational limits: daylight — up to rough sea state (Force\n6/7); darkness — up to moderate/rough sea state (Force 5/6). Actions\nto limit damage and prevent injury:\n\n  **Technique**   **When to Use**     **How It Works**\n\n  Reduce speed    Slamming, airborne, Slower speed reduces impact forces.\n                  crew discomfort     Match speed to conditions, not to\n                                      urgency\n\n  Change heading  Beam seas causing   Heading slightly off the sea\n                  excessive rolling,  (10 — 15°) can dramatically reduce\n                  following seas      roll or prevent surf. Head to sea is\n                  causing             not always the only option\n                  surfing/broaching   \n\n  Adjust trim     Bow slamming into   Trim engines slightly up to lift the\n                  head seas           bow. Excessive trim reduces thrust\n                                      and increases fuel consumption\n\n  Fill ballast    Transiting up-sea   270kg of water in the bow improves\n                  in head seas        handling in head seas. Drain when\n                                      transiting down-sea or for net\n                                      recovery\n\n  Crew            Any heavy weather   Ensure all crew are correctly\n  positioning                         seated, restrained by foot straps,\n                                      holding on. Move crew weight if\n                                      needed for single-engine operation\n                                      or to balance the boat\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.2b, pp.170 — 171; TP-LB-23, Activity 4, pp.38 — 40*\n\n**Going Alongside Another Vessel at Sea**\n\nThe Slow Speed Transfers SOP teaches the technique for coming alongside\na moving casualty vessel:\n\n-   Approach the casualty in the negative pressure zone (amidships),\n    paralleling the casualty's course. The mid-wash can be used as a\n    brake\n\n-   Aim for a boarding ladder, gate, or other suitable embarkation point\n\n-   Focus on a fixed point on the vessel and adjust speed with small\n    throttle changes\n\n-   As you close, remain parallel and be prepared for vessel interaction\n    effects\n\n-   ILB specific: once the beam is touching the casualty, apply full\n    helm towards the casualty to lean the shoulder of the ILB onto the\n    hull and apply enough power to remain in position\n\n-   With your permission, crew/equipment transfer may now take place\n\n-   Exiting: ease off the helm to parallel the casualty. Do NOT reduce\n    power — this could draw the ILB into the negative pressure area at\n    the stern and towards the casualty's propulsion. Maintain level with\n    the transfer point, open a sufficient gap before changing course or\n    speed\n\n*Source: LB-SOP-Slow Speed Transfers V3.0, p.3*\n\n**Propeller Change (ILB)**\n\nYou must be able to change a propeller while afloat, in accordance with\nthe Emergency Procedures EOP. This is required when a propeller is\ndamaged by debris, fouling, or grounding. Deploy the sea anchor first to\nstabilise the boat head to sea. Crew safety: engines must be off and\nisolated before anyone enters the water near the propellers.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.7.2e, p.173; 85-EOP-Emergency Procedures V6.0*\n",
  "4.7.3": "### 4.7.3 MOORING AND BERTHING\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 13. Secure the A85 alongside a quay, wall, or pontoon using the       |\n|     correct lines                                                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 14. Know which lines to make fast first depending on wind and tide    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 15. Pick up a mooring buoy safely                                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 16. Spring off from a berth when held on by wind or tide              |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Berthing Lines**\n\nFour types of line are used when berthing alongside:\n\n  **Line**         **From → To**        **What It Does**\n\n  Bow line         Vessel's bow → quay  Stops the bow coming away from the\n                   forward              quay\n\n  Stern line       Vessel's stern →     Stops the stern coming away from\n                   quay aft             the quay\n\n  Bow spring       Vessel's bow → quay  Prevents the vessel moving FORWARD\n                   AFT                  (runs opposite to the direction it\n                                        prevents)\n\n  Stern spring     Vessel's stern →     Prevents the vessel moving\n                   quay FORWARD         BACKWARD\n\nOn the A85, the A-frame cleats can be used for mooring and berthing\nlines but are NOT suitable for towing loads. Do not disembark until the\nHelm gives the command. Keep inboard of the sponsons on approach — \nbeware of entrapment between the vessel and the quay.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 4, pp.41 — 43; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.202 — 204*\n\n**Springing Off**\n\nIf wind or tide is holding the vessel onto the berth and you cannot\nsimply reverse away:\n\n-   1\\. Slip all lines except the bow spring, rigged as a slipping line\n    (both ends aboard so you can release from on deck)\n\n-   2\\. Come ahead gently on the engine\n\n-   3\\. As the strain comes on the bow spring, the stern swings out away\n    from the berth\n\n-   4\\. Slip the bow spring and leave the jetty astern\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 4, p.42; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.203*\n\n**Mooring to a Buoy**\n\nA mooring buoy is a specially constructed buoy attached to the seabed by\nchains, anchors, or weights. A fitting on top allows vessels to be\nsecured. The procedure:\n\n-   1\\. Assess weather conditions, strength and direction of wind and\n    tide before approaching. Look at other vessels on buoys to see which\n    way they lie — this tells you the dominant force\n\n-   2\\. The Helm approaches slowly, into the strongest element (wind or\n    tide, whichever is dominant)\n\n-   3\\. A crew member in the bow uses a boat hook to gather the mooring\n    line from the water. They should have their lifeline secured to\n    reduce the risk of falling overboard\n\n-   4\\. Good communication between the bow crew and the Helm is\n    essential: direction and distance of the buoy from the vessel,\n    whether you have it, whether it's slipping\n\n-   5\\. Methods of securing to the buoy: lasso, loop through the buoy\n    (rigged to slip for quick release), bowline, or round turn and two\n    half hitches\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 4, p.43; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.204; TP-OCF-03, Activity 3, p.15*\n\n**Berthing Terminology You Must Know**\n\n  **Term**          **Meaning**\n\n  Double up         Adding a second rope on the same lead to increase\n                    holding in bad weather\n\n  Marry the lines   Ensuring both ropes on a doubled-up lead are under\n                    equal tension\n\n  Single up         Removing one rope from a doubled-up lead in\n                    preparation for departure\n\n  Slip line         A line looped around a bollard on the quay with both\n                    ends secured aboard — allows all crew to be on\n                    board when releasing\n\n  Dipping the eye   When two mooring lines go to the same bollard, the\n                    second line's eye must be passed through the first\n                    line's eye from underneath before going over the\n                    bollard. This allows either line to be cast off in\n                    any order\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.203*\n",
  "4.10.1": "## Helicopter Operations\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Prepare the A85 for helicopter operations                         |\n| 2.  Understand the three no-go areas around a helicopter              |\n| 3.  Execute underway and static winching                              |\n| 4.  Manage the hi-line correctly                                      |\n| 5.  Know the procedures for being winched into a helicopter           |\n| 6.  Conduct helicopter operations at night                            |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### The Three No-Go Areas\n\n:::diagram Helicopter approach zones — always approach from the STARBOARD side (3–4 o'clock)\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 400 400\" style=\"max-width:380px\">\n<circle cx=\"200\" cy=\"200\" r=\"170\" fill=\"#F1F3F5\" stroke=\"#D1D5DB\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>\n<circle cx=\"200\" cy=\"200\" r=\"40\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#002B5C\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">HELI</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"207\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\" font-family=\"Barlow\">12 o'clock ↑</text>\n<path d=\"M200 160 L200 35\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<path d=\"M130 80 L200 35 L270 80\" fill=\"#DC2626\" fill-opacity=\"0.12\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">AREA 1</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"84\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-family=\"Barlow\">CRASH PATH</text>\n<path d=\"M160 200 L35 200\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<path d=\"M80 130 L35 200 L80 270\" fill=\"#DC2626\" fill-opacity=\"0.12\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"70\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">AREA 2</text>\n<text x=\"70\" y=\"209\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-family=\"Barlow\">DITCH ZONE</text>\n<path d=\"M200 240 L200 365\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<path d=\"M130 320 L200 365 L270 320\" fill=\"#DC2626\" fill-opacity=\"0.12\" stroke=\"#DC2626\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"340\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">AREA 3</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"354\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#DC2626\" font-family=\"Barlow\">DOWNDRAFT</text>\n<path d=\"M270 130 L320 150 L345 200 L320 250 L270 270\" fill=\"#059669\" fill-opacity=\"0.15\" stroke=\"#059669\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<text x=\"310\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">SAFE</text>\n<text x=\"310\" y=\"209\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#059669\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow\">3-4 o'clock</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"22\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">12</text>\n<text x=\"370\" y=\"204\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">3</text>\n<text x=\"200\" y=\"390\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">6</text>\n<text x=\"30\" y=\"204\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">9</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n### Underway Winching — Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Establish VHF comms** with the helicopter at the earliest opportunity. Agree call signs and working channel\n2. **Switch radar to standby** — radar emissions can interfere with helicopter systems\n3. **Brief the crew** thoroughly. PPE: helmet with visor down, approved hi-line gloves (NOT neoprene)\n4. **Approach from the starboard side** at the 3–4 o'clock position. Stay clear of 6, 9, and 12 o'clock\n5. **Stand off** until the winchman is in position and you are directed to approach\n6. **Crew 2 watches the winchman** and gives directions to the Helm. **Crew 3 looks ahead** for obstructions. The Helm looks upward at the helicopter\n7. Remain clear until the winchman is lowered to approximately **2 metres above the sea**, then move into the winching position\n8. **Allow the static discharge line to earth** in the sea or on the boat before touching ANYTHING\n9. Once the winchman is aboard and holds the **hook up in the air** (clear signal), move away to starboard\n:::\n\n### Critical Safety Rules\n\n:::warning\n**DO NOT** touch the hi-line, winch wire, or winchman until the **static discharge line has earthed**. Helicopters generate massive static charge — contact before earthing causes severe injury or death.\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**NEVER** secure the hi-line to any part of the lifeboat. If the helicopter moves unexpectedly, a secured line **will capsize the boat**.\n:::\n\n:::warning\nThe **break-off call** is: **\"BREAK OFF, BREAK OFF, BREAK OFF\"** on the agreed VHF working channel (or display a RED flag above your head). The Helm aborts to starboard.\n:::\n\n---\n\n**Preparation Before the Helicopter Arrives**\n\n-   Make earliest possible VHF communications with the helicopter\n\n-   Establish primary call signs and working channel\n\n-   The Helm and the pilot agree the safest method of transfer, and\n    course and speed\n\n-   Ensure adequate sea room to conduct the transfer\n\n-   Brief the crew and any casualty thoroughly\n\n-   PPE: ILB safety helmet with visor down, drysuit, ILB lifejacket. If\n    handling the hi-line: approved gloves (not neoprene). If being\n    winched: replace ILB lifejacket with a deflated casualty lifejacket\n\n-   Switch radar to standby (if applicable) — radar emissions can\n    interfere with helicopter systems\n\n-   Clear and secure the deck — downdraft will propel any unsecured\n    objects\n\n-   Lower whip aerials if applicable; switch to emergency slot aerial to\n    maintain VHF\n\n-   Have a bucket available to collect the hi-line\n\n*Source: ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.2; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.228; TP-LB-45, Card 17*\n\n**The Three No-Go Areas**\n\nYou must never position the A85 in any of the following areas relative\nto the helicopter:\n\n  **Area**   **Location**         **Why It Is Dangerous**\n\n  Area 1     In FRONT of the      If the helicopter loses power, it will\n             helicopter           dive forward into this area to gain\n                                  speed and generate lift. You will be\n                                  directly in its crash path\n\n  Area 2     To PORT of the       In the event of a major engine failure,\n             helicopter           the pilot will always aim to ditch to\n                                  port. You will be in the ditching zone\n\n  Area 3     To the REAR of the   The downdraft produces a large amount of\n             helicopter           spray behind and below the aircraft,\n                                  reducing visibility to near zero. The\n                                  position of the downdraft moves\n                                  depending on the helicopter's speed\n\nThe safe approach area is to STARBOARD of the helicopter, at the 3 — 4\no'clock position.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.231; TP-LB-23, Activity 5, p.57; ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.3*\n\n**Underway Winching (ILB Formates on Helicopter)**\n\nIn an underway transfer, the ILB approaches the helicopter — the\nhelicopter does not come to the ILB. The procedure:\n\n-   1\\. Approach from the starboard side of the helicopter at the 3 — 4\n    o'clock position\n\n-   2\\. Stay clear of the 6, 9, and 12 o'clock positions (the three\n    no-go areas)\n\n-   3\\. Stand off until the winchman is in position and you have been\n    directed to approach\n\n-   4\\. On approach, one crew member watches the winchman and gives\n    directions to the Helm. A second crew member looks ahead for\n    obstructions in the water. On the A85: Crew 2 watches the winchman,\n    Crew 3 looks ahead, Crew 4 (if aboard) looks all around. The Helm\n    looks upward at the helicopter itself and cannot see ahead\n\n-   5\\. Use small throttle and steering corrections to provide a stable\n    platform\n\n-   6\\. Remain clear of the winching position until the winchman is\n    lowered to approximately 2 metres above the sea, then move into the\n    winching position directly under the helicopter\n\n-   7\\. Once the winchman is onboard and has released the winch wire\n    (indicated by holding the hook up in the air), move away from the\n    helicopter to starboard\n\n-   8\\. Maintain the station until the Helm receives a thumbs-up from\n    the winchman. Then depart to the 3 o'clock position\n\n*Source: ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.3; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.231; TP-LB-23, Activity 5, pp.56 — 58*\n\n**Static Winching**\n\nDuring static winching, the ILB lies stopped with engines running but in\nneutral. The helicopter positions itself over the ILB. This method is\nused when: ILB pitching could worsen casualty injuries, in high sea\nstates, when sea room is insufficient for underway transfers, or at\nnight.\n\n  **Conditions**   **Positioning**            **Notes**\n\n  Slight sea /     Starboard side to weather. Lying beam-on presents a\n  light wind       Consider sea anchor with   larger target for the\n                   gentle astern power to     helicopter. First sponson\n                   prevent the boat spinning  contact gives the winchman\n                   under the helicopter       easier bow access\n\n  Moderate or      Head to sea, deploy sea    If unsafe to lie beam-on,\n  greater sea /    anchor                     maintaining head to sea is\n  stronger wind                               the safer option. Sea anchor\n                                              stabilises the boat\n\n*Source: ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.3; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.232*\n\n**The Hi-Line — B Class Procedure**\n\nThe hi-line is a weighted line lowered from the helicopter before the\nwinchman. It reduces swinging and the time the helicopter spends\ndirectly overhead. The B Class procedure:\n\n-   1\\. The helicopter lowers the hi-line with a weighted bag\n\n> **DO NOT touch the hi-line, winch wire, or winchman until the static\n> discharge line has earthed by making contact with the sea or the\n> lifeboat. A very heavy static charge builds up in all helicopter winch\n> wires. Contact before earthing can cause severe injury or death.**\n\n-   2\\. DO NOT secure the hi-line to any part of the lifeboat — if the\n    helicopter moves, a secured line will capsize the boat\n\n-   3\\. B Class specific: pass the line past the Helm on the port side\n    and flake it into the footwell between seats 2 and 3\n\n-   4\\. One crew member handles the line, taking in ONLY the slack. A\n    second crew member coils the excess into a bucket. Approved hi-line\n    gloves (not neoprene) must be worn\n\n-   5\\. When the winchman is being lowered, maintain tension on the line\n    and pull it in as directed\n\n-   6\\. The crew must manage the excess hi-line to prevent it snagging\n    on the boat or crew\n\n-   7\\. When the winchman is being recovered to the helicopter, pay the\n    line out under tension until the weighted bag is reached. Let go of\n    the bag under control — do not throw it overboard\n\n-   8\\. If the helicopter has to break away during winching, the line\n    should be paid out or, if necessary, let go completely ensuring it\n    passes clear outboard\n\n*Source: ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.3; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.233 — 234*\n\n**Being Winched into a Helicopter**\n\nIf you are being winched into the helicopter:\n\n-   ILB crew MUST remove their ILB lifejacket and wear a non-inflated\n    casualty lifejacket instead. An inflated lifejacket is dangerous\n    inside a helicopter — if the aircraft ditches, it would seriously\n    hinder escape\n\n-   Always take directions from the winchman\n\n-   Put the rescue strop over your head and under your arms. Pull down\n    the beckett (webbing ring) to tighten. Position the strop high up on\n    your back. Keep your arms down at your sides\n\n-   The winch operator will do all the work when you arrive at the winch\n    door\n\n-   For a double strop (used for hypothermic or injured casualties), the\n    winch operator will decide\n\n-   Only the helicopter's basket stretcher is to be used for lifting.\n    The RNLI PS1 stretcher will NOT be lifted by the helicopter\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, pp.235 — 236; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.10.1b, p.187*\n\n**Night Operations**\n\nAt night, the helicopter pilot may not be able to identify the lifeboat\nfrom other vessels. When asked for identification:\n\n-   Shine the searchlight vertically upwards until the helicopter's\n    landing lights flash in acknowledgement\n\n-   Then swing the searchlight down to shine forward, parallel with the\n    sea surface\n\n> **Helicopter crews searching at night are likely to be wearing night\n> vision goggles. Under no circumstances are flares to be released or\n> searchlights and aldis lamps to be shone directly towards the\n> helicopter. This will blind the crew and could cause a crash.**\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.236*\n\n**Emergency Break-Off**\n\nIf the Helm needs to abort the helicopter operation at any time:\n\n-   Broadcast on the agreed working VHF channel: 'BREAK OFF, BREAK OFF,\n    BREAK OFF'\n\n-   Or display the RED flag (held above head)\n\n-   The helicopter will immediately recover the wire, ascend, and move\n    off to a safe distance\n\n-   The Helm should abort to STARBOARD\n\n-   If the helicopter suffers a major mechanical failure forcing the\n    pilot to ditch, the pilot will always attempt to move the aircraft\n    to PORT before ditching\n\n*Source: ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0, p.2; TP-LB-01, Activity 4, p.229; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.10.1b, p.187*\n",
  "4.10.2": "### 4.10.2 MANAGE HELICOPTER OPERATIONS\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 34. Plan and liaise with helicopter organisations before operations   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 35. Command the crew through underway and static winching             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 36. Decide the safest method of transfer in the prevailing conditions |\n|                                                                       |\n| 37. Manage night helicopter operations                                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 38. Manage ashore helicopter operations including landing sites       |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nHelicopter operations at crew level are taught in full in the Tier 2\nguide. As Helm, you are the person who decides the method of transfer\n(underway or static), agrees the parameters with the pilot, positions\nthe boat, and makes the break-off call if anything goes wrong. You also\nplan helicopter exercises in advance, liaising with SAR helicopter\norganisations for knowledge sharing and passing current RNLI personnel\ncompetence records.\n\nAshore helicopter operations (preparing landing sites, managing rotor\nwash and blade sail hazards, hot landing vs shutdown landing techniques,\nbriefing from aircrew, clearing loose objects and managing the public)\nare also within your scope. The pilot is in command of the aircraft at\nall times — but you are responsible for crew safety on the ground or\non the boat.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 4.10.1 — 4.10.2, pp.186 — 190; ILB Helicopter Operations SOP V5.0; Ashore Helicopter Operations SOP*\n\n# Domain 5: Search & Rescue Operations\n",
  "5.1.1": "## Locate and Assist\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Use search equipment and visual scanning to locate casualties     |\n| 2.  Recover casualties from the water using the A85's equipment       |\n| 3.  Evaluate a casualty's condition and provide immediate care        |\n| 4.  Understand the different recovery methods available               |\n| 5.  Manage a search using expanding square and sector patterns        |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Casualty Recovery from the Water — Quick Reference\n\n:::steps\n1. **Approach from downwind/down-sea** at slow speed. Use the engine furthest from the casualty\n2. Make contact at the **vessel's shoulder** (forward quarter)\n3. When alongside, **both engines to NEUTRAL immediately**\n4. Guide the casualty aft to the **4th seat area** where the sponson is lowest\n5. If the casualty can assist: use the **scramble net** or crew assistance over the sponson\n6. If the casualty is unconscious: use the **double strop method** — one strop under the arms, one under the knees — maintaining a **horizontal position**\n7. For larger or heavier casualties: deploy **Jason's Cradle** for a full horizontal recovery\n8. Once aboard, carry out **DR ABC** immediately\n9. **Protect from exposure** — survival bag, shelter from wind and spray\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**Horizontal recovery is essential for hypothermic casualties.** Lifting vertically removes the hydrostatic squeeze and allows blood to pool in the legs, causing post-rescue collapse and cardiac arrest. Use the double strop or Jason's Cradle.\n:::\n\n### Visual Search Techniques\n\n:::fact SCANNING PATTERN\nDivide your search area into **sectors of approximately 10–15 degrees**. Scan each sector from near to far, pause briefly, then move to the next sector. Overlap each sector slightly. This systematic approach is far more effective than random searching.\n:::\n\n- In **daylight**: look for colour contrast, movement, splashing, waving arms, reflective tape, dye marker\n- At **night**: use the **searchlight** in sweeping arcs, look for lifejacket lights, PLB strobe, reflective tape\n- In **poor visibility**: slow down, increase lookout numbers, use radar and AIS, listen for shouts/whistles\n\n### Search Patterns\n\n| **Pattern** | **When Used** | **How It Works** |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Expanding square** | Position known approximately | Start at datum, run legs of increasing length, turning 90° each time |\n| **Sector search** | Position known accurately | Start at datum, run outbound legs at different bearings, always returning to datum |\n| **Parallel track** | Large area, position uncertain | Run parallel legs across the area with spacing based on visibility |\n| **Shoreline search** | Casualty near coast | Follow the coastline at appropriate distance, using crew as lookouts |\n\n\n\n**Recovery Methods on the A85 — In Detail**\n\nPreferred recovery side on the A85 is PORT (because the throttles on the\nstarboard side impede crew movement). Contact the casualty level with\nthe helm's seat, then guide them aft to the 4th seat position where\nthere is more space and the sponsons are lower.\n\n  **Method**        **How It Works**              **When to Use**\n\n  Over the sponson  Crew grab the casualty's      Conscious casualty who\n  (crew-assisted)   lifejacket or harness and     can assist.\n                    pull them over the sponson. A Calm-to-moderate\n                    second crew member supports   conditions. Most common\n                    from inside the boat.         A85 method\n                    Requires significant upper    \n                    body strength                 \n\n  Over the transom  Casualty uses the lowered     Conscious casualty with\n  (engine           engine's cavitation plate as  reasonable strength.\n  cavitation plate) a step to climb over the      Engines must be stopped\n                    transom. Crew assist from     and isolated first\n                    above                         \n\n  Deflate rear      If recovery over the sponson  Unconscious or very\n  sponsons          is proving difficult, the     heavy casualty. Last\n                    rear sponsons can be          resort as it reduces the\n                    partially deflated to reduce  boat's buoyancy and\n                    freeboard                     stability\n\n  Throw bag         Throw to the casualty, who    Conscious casualty at\n                    holds on while being pulled   short range. Quick\n                    to the boat. Can also be used deployment from the 4th\n                    to pass a tow line            seat\n\n  Single strop      A lifting strop is placed     Quick recovery. Avoid\n  (under arms)      under the casualty's arms and for hypothermic\n                    used to haul them aboard      casualties (vertical\n                                                  lift reduces blood\n                                                  pressure)\n\n  Double strop      Two strops: one under the     Preferred for\n  (arms + knees)    arms, one under the knees.    hypothermic casualties\n                    Casualty is recovered in a — reduces the risk of\n                    more horizontal position      post-rescue collapse by\n                                                  maintaining blood\n                                                  distribution\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.17; TP-LB-01, Activity 5, pp.254 — 256; TP-OCF-03, Session Plan: MOB, p.58*\n\n**Boarding a Casualty Vessel**\n\nIf the Helm decides to transfer a crew member to the casualty vessel,\nthat crew member should take:\n\n-   A portable handheld VHF radio (to maintain communications\n    independently)\n\n-   A knife (stowed in the first aid kit — for cutting lines in an\n    emergency)\n\n-   A first aid / casualty care kit\n\n-   A torch\n\n-   A casualty drogue (if carried and needed)\n\nBefore boarding, the crew member must be briefed on: the approach plan,\nconditions, strong points on the casualty vessel for making fast, and\ntheir specific tasks. Marine safety helmets MUST be worn onboard\ncasualty vessels. Crew should only disembark the lifeboat on the Helm's\nsignal.\n\n\n:::warning\n**Crew safety is the priority. If persons on the casualty vessel are\nsuspicious or pose a danger to the crew or lifeboat, NO crew member\nshould be transferred. The Helm should stand off the vessel and\ncommunicate from a distance. Information about the vessel should be\npassed to the Coastguard. If the vessel contains sensitive cargo or\nfurther investigation is needed, the Coastguard will request\nhelicopter attendance.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: Working with a Casualty Vessel SOP V5.0, p.2; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.5.2b, p.158*\n",
  "5.1.2": "### 5.1.2 LOCATE AND ASSIST 2\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 14. Manage multi-vessel search operations as On-Scene Coordinator     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 15. Deploy and manage search assets effectively                       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 16. Handle complex casualty situations including triage               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nLocate and Assist 1 (Tier 1) taught you to find and recover a single\ncasualty. Locate and Assist 2 teaches the management of more complex\nsituations: multiple casualties, multiple search assets, deteriorating\nconditions, and the role of On-Scene Coordinator (OSC).\n\n**The On-Scene Coordinator (OSC) Role**\n\nThe Coastguard (SMC) may appoint the A85 as OSC when it is the first or\nmost capable asset on scene. As OSC, your responsibilities include:\n\n-   Monitoring and coordinating all SAR units on scene\n\n-   Maintaining communications between all assets and the SMC\n\n-   Reporting search effectiveness back to the SMC (SAR Check Card 9)\n\n-   Monitoring your own vessel's safety, fuel, and crew fatigue while\n    coordinating others\n\n-   Maintaining the search plot using Card 16 (OSC/Search Planning) from\n    the SAR Check Cards\n\n\n:::warning\n**Acting as OSC degrades your own search capability because your\nattention is divided between coordination and searching. You must\nmonitor your own vessel safety and crew fatigue. If the OSC burden is\ncompromising crew safety, inform the SMC.**\n:::\n\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 5.3.1c, p.206; TP-LB-45, Card 16*\n",
  "5.2.1": "## Plan SAR\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Gather and evaluate all incident information                      |\n| 2.  Plot positions on paper and electronic charts                     |\n| 3.  Plan a SAR sortie using SMEAC                                     |\n| 4.  Brief the crew effectively before launch                          |\n| 5.  Apply tidal and weather information to planning decisions         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### The SMEAC Briefing\n\nEvery SAR sortie begins with a structured briefing. SMEAC ensures nothing is missed:\n\n:::acronym SMEAC\nS — **Situation** — What has happened? Casualty type, position, number of persons involved, conditions on scene, other units tasked\nM — **Mission** — What are we going to do? Our objective in clear terms\nE — **Execution** — How are we going to do it? Route, speed, approach, crew positions, contingencies\nA — **Administration** — Kit checks, fuel state, ETA, communications plan, any special equipment needed\nC — **Command and Communication** — Who is in charge? Reporting chain, frequencies, call signs. \"What have I missed?\"\n:::\n\n:::info\nThe final question — **\"What have I missed?\"** — is critical. It invites crew input and catches oversights. Even the most experienced Helm can miss something.\n:::\n\n### Gathering Information\n\nBefore launch, gather as much information as possible from:\n\n- **Coastguard** — position, nature of incident, other assets tasked, weather on scene\n- **Station information** — local knowledge, chart, tidal atlas, weather forecast\n- **Previous incidents** — has this happened before in this area? Any known hazards?\n\n### Plotting Positions\n\n:::fact POSITION FORMATS\n**Latitude/Longitude**: 50° 56.8'N 001° 04.3'E — the standard format for chart work\n**Bearing and distance**: 045°T, 2.3 NM from Dungeness lighthouse — useful for quick reference\n**Grid reference**: Used on land maps, not at sea\nAlways confirm which format is being used — errors in position can be fatal.\n:::\n\n### Tidal Planning\n\n- **What is the tide doing?** Rising, falling, slack, spring, neap\n- **How strong is the tidal stream** at the incident position? Direction and rate\n- **Depth at the casualty position** — is there enough water for the A85 (draught ~0.5m)?\n- **Will the tide change during the operation?** This affects approach, anchoring, and duration\n- Use the **tidal atlas** or **tidal diamond** data on the chart\n\n### Weather Considerations\n\nKey factors affecting SAR planning:\n- **Wind speed and direction** — affects sea state, spray, casualty drift, helicopter operations\n- **Visibility** — fog, rain, darkness all significantly increase risk\n- **Sea state** — wave height, period, and direction. Consider swell vs wind waves\n- **Temperature** — air and water temperature affect casualty survival time and crew performance\n- **Forecast trend** — is it improving or deteriorating? Will conditions change during the operation?\n\n### Route Planning\n\n:::steps\n1. **Plot the direct course** from station to incident position\n2. Identify **hazards on route** — shallow water, rocks, buoys, shipping lanes, fishing gear\n3. Calculate **distance and ETA** at planned speed (consider reducing speed in poor conditions)\n4. Identify **waypoints** for course changes\n5. Consider the **tidal stream** effect on your track — apply corrections\n6. Plan a **contingency route** in case conditions require diversion\n:::\n",
  "5.3.1": "### 5.3.1 MANAGE SAR\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 39. Adjust a search plan in response to changing conditions           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 40. Manage the crew during prolonged search operations                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 41. Act as On-Scene Coordinator (OSC) and manage multiple assets      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 42. Manage casualty recovery, evaluation, and evacuation decisions    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 43. State the A85 maximum casualty carrying limit (20 casualties)     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Adjusting the Search Plan**\n\nConditions change during a search. Factors that may require you to\nadjust the plan:\n\n  **Factor**        **How You Might Adjust**\n\n  Weather           Reduce search speed, change pattern type, increase\n  deterioration     track spacing, reduce search area, request additional\n                    assets, or suspend search\n\n  Day to night      Reduce speed, switch to datum search (expanding\n                    square), deploy searchlights, reduce sweep width,\n                    increase track spacing\n\n  Updated           Recalculate datum, shift search area, change pattern\n  information       orientation\n\n  New casualties    Prioritise (W1/W2/W3 from Decision Support Card 4),\n                    reallocate assets, request helicopter\n\n  Other assets      Redistribute sectors, adjust track spacing, update\n  arrive or depart  OSC plan\n\n  Crew fatigue      Rotate lookout positions, rotate roles, request crew\n                    change from shore if available, consider standing\n                    down\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 5.3.1a, p.204*\n\n**Managing the Crew During Search**\n\n-   Position crew at best height of eye suited to conditions, covering\n    allocated sectors as briefed\n\n-   Monitor for fatigue and complacency — poor, ineffective searching\n    results from lack of focus and demotivation\n\n-   Rotate lookout positions and roles regularly (every 30 minutes\n    recommended)\n\n-   Provide information updates to maintain motivation and focus\n\n-   Ensure appropriate PPE and refreshments\n\n-   Consider crew changes if the operation is prolonged\n\n-   Report search effectiveness to the SMC using the terminology: Ideal\n    / Normal / Reduced\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 5.3.1a, pp.204 — 205; TP-LB-45, Card 9*\n\n**Casualty Management at Command Level**\n\nWhen a casualty is located, you must make several command decisions:\n\n  **Decision**         **Factors to Consider**\n\n  Transfer/recover     Damage to the A85, risk vs benefit of transfer,\n  person or vessel to  exacerbating injuries, risk to traffic if vessel\n  the A85?             abandoned, vessels on fire, stability of the\n                       casualty vessel\n\n  Maximum casualties   The A85 can carry 20 casualties. If you have more\n                       than 20, you must request additional assets or\n                       make multiple trips. Overloading compromises\n                       stability\n\n  Plan evacuation from Crew safety, number and nature of injuries, triage\n  the A85              priority, time to evacuate, distance to medical\n                       assistance, weather, other available assets\n\n  Request helicopter   The helicopter's basket stretcher must be used\n  for evacuation?      (not the RNLI PS1). Consider: casualty condition,\n                       sea state, time to helicopter arrival vs time to\n                       shore\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 5.3.1c, pp.206 — 207*\n",
  "5.4.1": "### 5.4.1 MANAGE OPERATIONAL SERVICES\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 7.  Manage the station and remaining crew while the SAR unit is at    |\n|     sea                                                               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 8.  Control access to the station during operations                   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 9.  Coordinate with other SAR agencies                                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 10. Plan for crew rotation on lengthy services                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 11. Manage post-recovery: debrief, welfare, reporting, and            |\n|     ready-for-service                                                 |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Your Role During a Service**\n\nOnce the SAR unit has launched, your role shifts from authorising to\nmanaging. You are responsible for:\n\n  **Parameter**         **Atlantic 85**\n\n  Normal crew           3\n\n  Minimum crew          3\n\n  Maximum crew          4\n\n  Extras on exercise    N/A (maximum remains 4)\n\n  Fire extinguisher     0.5kg CO2 (2 — 3 seconds discharge)\n\n  Fuel type             Petrol (highly flammable)\n\n  Engines               Twin Yamaha 4-stroke outboards\n\n  Recovery methods      Stern (standard), Net (heavy surf), Beach\n                        (emergency)\n\n  VHF Coastguard        Every 15 minutes on service/exercise\n  reporting             \n\n  LA attendance         D Class launches during hours of darkness (not\n  required              A85, but know this for co-located stations)\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 3, p.128; TP-LB-23, Activity 2, pp.12 — 13*\n\n# Domain 6: Communications\n",
  "6.1.1": "## Operate VHF Radio\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Switch on, adjust and operate the main VHF radio functions        |\n| 2.  Know the key channels and their purposes                          |\n| 3.  Use correct voice procedure and the phonetic alphabet             |\n| 4.  Send and receive a DSC distress alert                             |\n| 5.  Make a Mayday, Pan Pan, and Securité call                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### Key VHF Channels\n\n| **Channel** | **Purpose** | **Notes** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ch 16 | International distress, safety, and calling | Monitor at ALL times. Initial contact then move to working channel |\n| Ch 0 (zero) | DSC distress channel (70) | Automatic — do not use for voice |\n| Ch 31 | RNLI private working channel | Used for launch/recovery comms between HL, plant, and SAR unit |\n| Ch 06 | Ship-to-ship safety | Commonly used for SAR coordination once established |\n| Ch 67 | UK Coastguard working channel | Directed by the Coastguard for SAR coordination |\n\n### Voice Procedure\n\n:::fact PRO-WORDS\n**Mayday**: Distress — grave and imminent danger, immediate assistance required\n**Pan Pan**: Urgency — serious situation but no immediate danger to life\n**Securité**: Safety — navigational or meteorological warning\n**Over**: I have finished speaking and expect a reply\n**Out**: I have finished speaking and do NOT expect a reply (never say \"Over and Out\")\n**Roger**: I have received and understood your last message\n**Say again**: Please repeat your last message\n**Correction**: I made an error — the correct version follows\n:::\n\n### The Mayday Call\n\n:::steps\n1. Press and hold the transmit button\n2. Say **\"MAYDAY MAYDAY MAYDAY\"**\n3. **\"THIS IS\"** [vessel name] × 3, [callsign]\n4. **\"MAYDAY\"** [vessel name]\n5. **\"MY POSITION IS\"** [latitude/longitude or bearing and distance from known point]\n6. **\"I REQUIRE IMMEDIATE ASSISTANCE\"**\n7. **\"I HAVE\"** [number of persons on board]\n8. **\"NATURE OF DISTRESS\"** [describe: fire, flooding, capsize, etc.]\n9. **\"OVER\"**\n:::\n\n:::acronym MIRDPANIO (Mayday format memory aid)\nM — **Mayday** × 3\nI — **Identification** — \"This is\" [vessel name × 3, callsign]\nR — **Repeat** — \"Mayday\" [vessel name]\nD — **Distress** position\nP — **Position** — lat/long or bearing/distance\nA — **Assistance** required\nN — **Number** of persons on board\nI — **Information** — nature of distress, type of vessel, any other useful info\nO — **Over**\n:::\n\n### DSC (Digital Selective Calling)\n\nDSC sends a digital distress alert at the push of a button. It transmits your vessel identity (MMSI), position, and nature of distress to all DSC-equipped stations and vessels within range.\n\n:::steps\n1. Lift the protective cover on the **DISTRESS** button\n2. **Press and hold** for 5 seconds (this prevents accidental activation)\n3. The radio will automatically transmit a DSC distress alert on Channel 70\n4. The radio then switches to **Ch 16** for voice follow-up\n5. **Make a voice Mayday** on Ch 16 as above\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**False DSC alerts waste Coastguard resources and can divert SAR assets from real emergencies.** If you accidentally trigger a DSC alert, immediately contact the Coastguard on Ch 16 to cancel it. Do not simply ignore it.\n:::\n\n### Phonetic Alphabet\n\n| A — Alpha | B — Bravo | C — Charlie | D — Delta |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| E — Echo | F — Foxtrot | G — Golf | H — Hotel |\n| I — India | J — Juliet | K — Kilo | L — Lima |\n| M — Mike | N — November | O — Oscar | P — Papa |\n| Q — Quebec | R — Romeo | S — Sierra | T — Tango |\n| U — Uniform | V — Victor | W — Whiskey | X — X-ray |\n| Y — Yankee | Z — Zulu | | |\n\n:::memory\nNumbers are spoken as individual digits: **156.8 MHz** = \"Wun Fife Six Decimal Ait\" — not \"one hundred and fifty-six point eight\".\n:::\n",
  "6.1.2": "### 6.1.2 SAR COMMUNICATION\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 44. Send and respond to Mayday, Pan Pan, and Sécurité transmissions   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 45. Conduct SAR communications with the Coastguard throughout an      |\n|     operation                                                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 46. Manage communications failure including deployment of the         |\n|     emergency aerial                                                  |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nAt command level, you must be able to initiate and respond to all three\npriority transmissions:\n\n  **Transmission**   **When to Use**                **Priority**\n\n  Mayday (Distress)  Grave and imminent danger      Highest. All stations\n                     requiring immediate            must cease transmitting\n                     assistance. You or another     and listen\n                     vessel is in danger of         \n                     sinking, capsizing, or loss of \n                     life                           \n\n  Pan Pan (Urgency)  Urgent safety message that     Second highest. All\n                     does not involve immediate     stations should listen\n                     danger to life. Medical        but may continue normal\n                     emergency requiring advice,    traffic after\n                     vessel disabled but not        \n                     sinking                        \n\n  Sécurité (Safety)  Navigation or weather warning. Lowest priority of the\n                     Debris in the shipping lane,   three. An information\n                     unlit vessel adrift, weather   broadcast\n                     warning                        \n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 6.1.2, pp.216 — 218*\n\nThe complete Mayday voice format (MIRDPANIO) is taught in full in the\nTier 1 guide (TP-LB-28, EOP 9). As Helm, you must be able to send it\nfrom memory under pressure, respond to a received Mayday (Mayday relay\nif required), send a Pan Pan and Sécurité, and maintain operational\ncommunications with the Coastguard throughout a service (PIMs every 15\nminutes, SITREPs as required, search effectiveness reports, and\noperations normal transmissions).\n\nIn the event of VHF failure: connect the emergency aerial (located on\nthe starboard side inside the A-frame). If VHF communication cannot be\nre-established, consider activating PLBs and using pyrotechnics for\nsignalling. Inform the Coastguard by any means available (mobile phone\nif within range, relay through another vessel).\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.30; 85-EOP-Emergency Procedures V6.0*\n\n# Domain 7: Navigation\n",
  "7.1.1": "### 7.1.1 NAVIGATION INTRODUCTION\n\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 29. Understand latitude and longitude and how positions are expressed |\n|                                                                       |\n| 30. Read and interpret a nautical chart including colours, symbols,   |\n|     and depths                                                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 31. Identify all IALA Region A buoyage marks by shape, colour, top    |\n|     mark, and light                                                   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 32. Understand the compass rose, variation, deviation, and how        |\n|     distance and speed are measured at sea                            |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n**Latitude and Longitude**\n\nTo express any position on Earth, navigators use a grid system. Lines\nrunning vertically from pole to pole are called meridians or lines of\nlongitude. They are measured east and west from the Prime Meridian (0\ndegrees) at Greenwich, out to 180 degrees at the International Date\nLine. Lines running horizontally around the world are parallels of\nlatitude, measured north and south from the Equator (0 degrees) to 90\ndegrees at the poles.\n\nA position is always written latitude first, then longitude. For\nexample: 50°43'.35N 015°16'.6W. Latitude has two digits for the degrees\n(maximum 90); longitude has three digits (maximum 180). Each degree is\ndivided into 60 minutes, and minutes are divided into tenths (decimals).\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.288 — 289*\n\n**Measuring Distance at Sea**\n\nDistance at sea is measured in nautical miles. The critical\nrelationships to memorise:\n\n-   1 degree of latitude = 60 nautical miles\n\n-   1 minute of latitude (1') = 1 nautical mile\n\n-   1 cable = one-tenth of a nautical mile (approximately 200 yards /\n    183 metres)\n\n> **Distance must always be measured using the latitude scale on the\n> SIDE of the chart, never the longitude scale at the top or bottom.\n> This is because Mercator projection charts distort the longitude\n> scale, particularly at higher latitudes.**\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.289 and 297*\n\n**Speed at Sea**\n\nSpeed at sea is measured in knots. 1 knot = 1 nautical mile per hour.\nThe three formulae you need:\n\n  **To Find**   **Formula**                 **Example**\n\n  Distance (NM) Speed (kts) x Time (mins) ÷ 10 kts for 18 mins = 10 x 18 ÷\n                60                          60 = 3 NM\n\n  Speed (kts)   Distance (NM) x 60 ÷ Time   5 NM in 20 mins = 5 x 60 ÷ 20\n                (mins)                      = 15 kts\n\n  Time (mins)   Distance (NM) x 60 ÷ Speed  8 NM at 20 kts = 8 x 60 ÷ 20 =\n                (kts)                       24 mins\n\n**The 6-Minute Rule (for mental arithmetic)**\n\n6 minutes is one-tenth of an hour. So at any speed, the distance covered\nin 6 minutes is one-tenth of your speed in knots. At 10 kts you cover 1\nNM in 6 minutes. At 25 kts you cover 2.5 NM in 6 minutes. This allows\nquick calculations without a calculator.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, p.297*\n\n**Reading a Nautical Chart**\n\nA chart is a navigator's map, concentrating on the sea and coastal\nareas. The RNLI uses UK Admiralty charts. A relevant chart must always\nbe carried afloat as it is the primary method of navigation.\n\n**Chart colours and what they mean:**\n\n  **Colour**        **Meaning**\n\n  Yellow            Land\n\n  Green             Drying heights (areas exposed at low water)\n\n  Blue              Shallow water\n\n  White             Deep water (navigable)\n\n**Reading depths on a chart:**\n\nDepths are shown in metres and tenths at chart datum (the lowest\nastronomical tide). A large number with a small subscript shows depth:\ne.g. a large 4 with small 3 means 4.3 metres of water at chart datum. An\nunderlined number is a drying height: e.g. an underlined 1 with small 2\nmeans this feature stands 1.2 metres above chart datum at low water — \nit will be exposed.\n\n**The compass rose:**\n\nPrinted on every chart, the compass rose shows True North (outer ring)\nand Magnetic North (inner ring). The difference between them is\nvariation, which changes slowly each year. The rose states current\nvariation and annual change. For example: '2°20'W (2010) decreasing 8'\nannually' — subtract 8 minutes per year since 2010 to get current\nvariation.\n\n**Variation and deviation:**\n\n-   Variation — the difference between True North (on the chart) and\n    Magnetic North (where your compass points). Caused by Earth's\n    magnetic field. Found on the compass rose\n\n-   Deviation — additional compass error caused by metal objects on\n    the boat or the boat's own magnetism. Each SAR unit's fixed compass\n    has a deviation card showing the error for each heading\n\n-   Compass Bearing = True Bearing adjusted for both variation and\n    deviation\n\n**Chart corrections:**\n\nCharts go out of date as the seabed changes, buoyage is moved, and new\nhazards appear. The Admiralty publishes corrections weekly in Notices to\nMariners. Corrections should be recorded in magenta pen on the bottom\nleft margin of the chart. The COIR, LOM, and Coxswain/Helm are\nresponsible for chart updates. Using an uncorrected chart is dangerous\n — buoy positions, light characteristics, and depths may all have\nchanged.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.290 — 292 and 298; TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2a, pp.230 — 231*\n\n**IALA Buoyage System (Region A)**\n\nThe IALA Region A buoyage system is used around the UK and Europe. These\nmarks indicate safe channels, hazards, and special areas. You must be\nable to identify each by day (shape, colour, top mark) and by night\n(light colour and flashing pattern):\n\n  **Mark**    **Colour**            **Shape/Top      **Light**        **Meaning**\n                                    Mark**                            \n\n  Lateral:    Red                   Can (flat top) / Red, any rhythm  Port side of\n  Port                              red can                           channel entering\n                                                                      from seaward\n\n  Lateral:    Green                 Conical          Green, any       Starboard side\n  Starboard                         (pointed) /      rhythm           of channel\n                                    green cone up                     entering from\n                                                                      seaward\n\n  Cardinal:   Black over yellow     Pillar; 2 cones  White,           Pass NORTH of\n  North                             points UP        continuous       the mark\n                                                     quick/VQ         \n\n  Cardinal:   Black-yellow-black    Pillar; 2 cones  White, 3         Pass EAST of the\n  East                              base-to-base     quick/VQ flashes mark\n\n  Cardinal:   Yellow over black     Pillar; 2 cones  White, 6 Q/VQ +  Pass SOUTH of\n  South                             points DOWN      long flash       the mark\n\n  Cardinal:   Yellow-black-yellow   Pillar; 2 cones  White, 9         Pass WEST of the\n  West                              point-to-point   quick/VQ flashes mark\n\n  Isolated    Black + red horiz.    Pillar; 2 black  White, group     Danger with safe\n  danger      band                  spheres          flash (2)        water around it\n\n  Safe water  Red + white vert.     Spherical; red   White,           Safe water all\n              stripes               sphere           isophase/Morse A around\n                                                                      (mid-channel)\n\n  Special     Yellow                Any shape;       Yellow, any      Special area\n                                    yellow X         rhythm           (cables,\n                                                                      military)\n\n  Emergency   Blue + yellow vert.   Pillar; yellow   Blue/yellow      New, uncharted\n  wreck       stripes               cross            alternating      wreck\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.179 — 182; TP-OCF-02, Task 4.1.2b, p.136*\n\n\n:::diagram North Cardinal — pass to the NORTH\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 200 220\" style=\"max-width:200px\">\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"90\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"115\" width=\"50\" height=\"45\" rx=\"0 0 6 6\" fill=\"#FFD700\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">BLACK</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"145\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">YELLOW</text>\n<polygon points=\"85,65 100,50 115,65\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<polygon points=\"85,50 100,35 115,50\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">▲▲ Both point UP</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"197\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">Continuous quick flash</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">Pass NORTH of the mark</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::diagram East Cardinal — pass to the EAST\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 200 220\" style=\"max-width:200px\">\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"90\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"22\" rx=\"6 6 0 0\" fill=\"#FFD700\"/>\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"112\" width=\"50\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#FFD700\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"107\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">BLACK</text>\n<polygon points=\"85,65 100,50 115,65\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<polygon points=\"85,50 100,65 115,50\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">▲▼ Point APART</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"197\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">3 flashes (3 o'clock)</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">Pass EAST of the mark</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::diagram South Cardinal — pass to the SOUTH\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 200 220\" style=\"max-width:200px\">\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"90\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#FFD700\" stroke=\"#D4A800\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6 6 0 0\" fill=\"#002B5C\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">BLACK</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">YELLOW</text>\n<polygon points=\"85,65 100,80 115,65\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<polygon points=\"85,50 100,65 115,50\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">▼▼ Both point DOWN</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"197\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">6 flashes + long (6 o'clock)</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">Pass SOUTH of the mark</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::diagram West Cardinal — pass to the WEST\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 200 220\" style=\"max-width:200px\">\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"70\" width=\"50\" height=\"90\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#FFD700\" stroke=\"#D4A800\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"75\" y=\"100\" width=\"50\" height=\"28\" fill=\"#002B5C\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"89\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">YELLOW</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"white\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">BLACK</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"147\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">YELLOW</text>\n<polygon points=\"85,65 100,50 115,65\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<polygon points=\"85,65 100,80 115,65\" fill=\"#002B5C\" stroke=\"#001B3D\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#002B5C\" font-weight=\"800\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">▲▼ Point TOGETHER</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"197\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#6B7280\" font-family=\"Barlow\">9 flashes (9 o'clock)</text>\n<text x=\"100\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#E86826\" font-weight=\"700\" font-family=\"Barlow Condensed\">Pass WEST of the mark</text>\n</svg>\n:::\n\n:::memory\n**Cardinal flash counts match the clock:** North = continuous (12 o'clock), East = **3** flashes (3 o'clock), South = **6** + long (6 o'clock), West = **9** flashes (9 o'clock). **Top marks always point to the black** — that's how you tell them apart at distance.\n:::\n\n\n\n\n\n**Remembering cardinal marks:**\n\nThe top marks tell you the direction. North: both cones point UP (like a\ncompass needle pointing north). South: both cones point DOWN. East:\ncones point away from each other (like an egg shape — E for Egg).\nWest: cones point towards each other (like a wine glass — W for Wine\nglass). The number of flashes corresponds to a clock face: North = 12\n(continuous), East = 3, South = 6 (+ long flash), West = 9.\n\n#### Launch Authority Perspective\n\nNavigation fundamentals (latitude/longitude, charts, buoyage,\ndistance/speed/time) are taught in full in the Shore Crew Stage 2 guide.\nAs LA, you need this knowledge to understand position reports from the\nCoastguard, assess whether a casualty position is within your SAR unit's\nrange, and understand chart references during briefings.\n\n#### Tier 2 Crew Perspective\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 26. Apply navigation fundamentals from the boat rather than from a    |\n|     chart table                                                       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 27. Use the A85's SIMS and depth sounder for position fixing and      |\n|     pilotage                                                          |\n|                                                                       |\n| 28. Understand the practical application of chart reading, buoyage,   |\n|     and tidal information at sea                                      |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nNavigation Introduction is taught in comprehensive detail in the Shore\nCrew Stage 2 guide, covering latitude/longitude, distance measurement,\nspeed/distance/time formulae with worked examples, chart reading\n(colours, depth notation, compass rose, variation), and IALA buoyage\nwith the full 10-mark identification table. At Tier 2, you apply all of\nthis from the moving boat.\n\nThe key shift from shore-based navigation to afloat navigation is that\nthe chart is no longer flat on a table under good lighting — it is on\nthe SIMS screen or wedged into the console while the boat is bouncing.\nThe primary method of navigation on the A85 is still paper charts\n(electronic systems can fail), but the SIMS provides GPS position,\ncourse and speed over ground (COG/SOG), cross-track error (XTE),\nwaypoint proximity, depth, and radar overlay. The navigator must be able\nto cross-reference electronic and paper chart positions continuously.\n\n> **At Littlestone, specific navigation awareness includes: the shipping\n> lane 4 miles SE of Dungeness (IRPCS Rule 10 applies), the unlit wrecks\n> Veermann (050°55.3'N 000°49.13'E) and Coruna (050°55.49'N\n> 000°48.10'E), the Mulberry Harbour remains off Littlestone (unlit WWII\n> structure), and the sand bar at Rye Harbour entrance. These hazards\n> must be identified on both paper and electronic charts before\n> departure.**\n\n*Source: Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP V4.0; TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.1, pp.226 — 230*\n",
  "7.1.2": "### 7.1.2 NAVIGATION\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Select and interpret the correct chart for your area              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Fix the vessel's position using visual, electronic, and radar     |\n|     methods                                                           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Apply variation and deviation to convert between true, magnetic,  |\n|     and compass bearings                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 20. Determine tidal heights using tide tables and tidal curves        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 21. Determine tidal stream speed and direction using tidal diamonds   |\n|     and stream atlases                                                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 22. Plan a simple route between two locations including hazard        |\n|     assessment and STD calculations                                   |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Chart Selection and Interpretation**\n\nYou must select the most appropriate chart for your area of operation. A\nsmall-scale chart (covering a large area, e.g. the English Channel) is\nsuitable for passage planning but does not have the detail needed for\nclose-quarters pilotage. A large-scale chart (covering a small area in\ndetail, e.g. Dungeness to Folkestone) gives you the depths, hazards, and\nfeatures you need when operating close to shore.\n\nChart features you must be able to identify and interpret:\n\n  **Feature**      **What It Tells You**\n\n  Colours          Yellow = land. Green = drying heights (exposed at low\n                   water). Blue = shallow water. White = deep water\n\n  Depth soundings  Numbers show depth below chart datum in metres and\n                   tenths. Underlined numbers show drying heights (height\n                   above chart datum). Example: 4.3 = 4.3m depth; 1.2\n                   (underlined) = dries 1.2m above chart datum\n\n  Contour lines    Connect points of equal depth. Used for navigation by\n                   following a contour to maintain a safe depth\n\n  Compass rose     Shows true and magnetic bearings. The inner ring is\n                   magnetic. Variation is stated in the centre with the\n                   year of measurement and the annual rate of change\n\n  Tidal diamonds   Lettered diamonds on the chart (A, B, C etc.) with a\n                   corresponding table showing tidal stream direction and\n                   rate for each hour relative to high water at the\n                   standard port\n\n  Chart            Bottom-left corner shows the date of last correction.\n  corrections      Charts must be kept current — an uncorrected chart\n                   may show moved buoys, changed lights, missing hazards,\n                   or wrong depths\n\n  Magenta outlines Adjacent chart numbers. Used to find the next chart\n  / numbers        needed\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2a, p.230; TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.291 — 293*\n\n**Variation and Deviation**\n\nTrue North (on the chart) differs from Magnetic North (what your compass\npoints to). This difference is called variation. It is stated on the\ncompass rose with a date and annual rate of change — you must\ncalculate the current variation from the stated value.\n\nThe boat's own magnetic field further deflects the compass. This is\ncalled deviation and varies with heading. The A85's steering compass has\na deviation card showing the error for each heading.\n\nThe conversion mnemonic: True → Variation → Magnetic → Deviation →\nCompass. Remember: 'Cadbury's Dairy Milk Very Tasty' (Compass to True:\nadd West). When going from True to Compass: subtract westerly errors.\nWhen going from Compass to True: add westerly errors.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.298 — 299; TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2a, p.230*\n\n**Position Fixing**\n\nYou must be able to fix position using multiple methods and understand\nthe limitations of each:\n\n  **Method**     **How It Works**            **Limitations**\n\n  GPS fix        Latitude/longitude from the Depends on satellite\n                 SIMS or handheld GPS        reception. Can be affected\n                                             by poor aerial siting, power\n                                             failure, or shielding.\n                                             Subject to operator error in\n                                             reading\n\n  Three-point    Take compass bearings of    Requires identifiable\n  fix (visual)   three identifiable charted  charted objects. Accuracy\n                 objects (lighthouses,       depends on the angle between\n                 church spires, headlands).  the objects (wider angles =\n                 Plot the bearings on the    better fix). Affected by\n                 chart — where the three   compass error\n                 lines intersect is your     \n                 position. A 'cocked hat'    \n                 (triangle) indicates        \n                 bearing error               \n\n  Radar fix      Use VRM to measure range    Target identification can be\n                 and EBL to measure bearing  uncertain. Radar shadows,\n                 to a charted object. Plot   sea clutter, and rain\n                 on chart                    clutter degrade accuracy\n\n  Dead reckoning Plot your position from the Does not account for tidal\n  (DR)           last known position using   stream or leeway. Becomes\n                 course steered and distance increasingly inaccurate over\n                 run (from log or calculated time\n                 from speed and time)        \n\n  Estimated      Dead reckoning position     Better than DR but still an\n  position (EP)  with tidal stream and       estimate. Accuracy depends\n                 leeway applied              on the quality of tidal data\n                                             used\n\n  Fix by depth   Compare echo sounder        Useful as a confirmation but\n                 reading (corrected for tide rarely unique enough to fix\n                 height) with charted depths position alone. Best used in\n                 and contour lines           conjunction with other\n                                             methods\n\n  Transit        Two charted objects aligned Limited to areas with\n                 gives a position line. Two  suitable charted objects.\n                 transits crossing give a    Very accurate when available\n                 fix                         \n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2b, p.231; TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.300 — 302*\n\nYou must increase the frequency of position fixing when: on service, in\nreduced visibility, close to the coast or dangers, in pilotage waters,\nor when electronic equipment fails.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2b, p.231*\n\n**Tides**\n\nYou must be able to determine the height of tide at any time using tide\ntables and tidal curves. The standard port for your area provides the\nbase data; secondary ports use corrections. Key concepts:\n\n-   Spring tides: larger range (higher highs, lower lows), faster tidal\n    streams. Occur around full and new moon\n\n-   Neap tides: smaller range, slower streams. Occur around first and\n    last quarter moon\n\n-   Chart datum: the reference level for depths on the chart. It is\n    approximately the lowest astronomical tide (LAT). Actual water depth\n    = charted depth + height of tide\n\n-   Drying heights: shown as underlined figures. To find actual depth\n    over a drying feature: height of tide minus the drying height. If\n    the result is negative, the feature is exposed\n\n-   Rule of twelfths: an approximation of tidal rise and fall. In the 6\n    hours between low and high water, the tide rises: 1/12, 2/12, 3/12,\n    3/12, 2/12, 1/12 of the range. This means the tide rises fastest in\n    the middle two hours\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.304 — 311; TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2c, p.232*\n\n**Tidal Streams**\n\nTidal streams are the horizontal movement of water caused by the tide.\nYou must be able to determine the speed and direction of the tidal\nstream using:\n\n-   Tidal diamond tables on the chart — each lettered diamond has a\n    table showing direction (in degrees True) and rate (in knots) for\n    spring and neap tides at each hour relative to HW at the standard\n    port\n\n-   Tidal stream atlases — a series of charts showing the direction\n    and rate of tidal flow for each hour. More visual and often easier\n    to interpret than tidal diamonds\n\n-   Electronic sources — SIMS may display tidal data if available\n\nTidal streams affect your course made good and your ETA. A 2-knot tidal\nstream setting across your course at 090° when you are heading 000° at\n20 knots will push you significantly off track. You must apply the tidal\nstream vector to your dead reckoning position to get your estimated\nposition.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2c, p.232; TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.312 — 314*\n\n**Route Planning**\n\nTo plan a route between two locations, you must:\n\n-   1\\. Select the appropriate chart(s) for the passage\n\n-   2\\. Plot the start position and the destination\n\n-   3\\. Draw the intended track between them\n\n-   4\\. Check for hazards along the route: depths, rocks, wrecks, buoys,\n    TSS, military areas, no-go zones\n\n-   5\\. Measure the bearing (True) using the compass rose and parallel\n    ruler\n\n-   6\\. Apply variation (and deviation if required) to convert to a\n    Magnetic or Compass course\n\n-   7\\. Measure the distance using the latitude scale on the side of the\n    chart (1 minute of latitude = 1 nautical mile)\n\n-   8\\. Calculate the time using the Speed — Distance — Time formula: Time\n    (mins) = Distance (NM) × 60 ÷ Speed (kts)\n\n-   9\\. Apply tidal stream information to determine course to steer (the\n    course you actually need to point the boat to end up on your\n    intended track)\n\n-   10\\. Identify safe havens and contingency plans along the route\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2b, p.231; TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.297 — 298; TP-OCF-03, Session Plan: Navigation, pp.67 — 70*\n",
  "7.1.3": "### 7.1.3 NAVIGATION ADVANCED\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 23. Plan a passage with multiple waypoints accounting for all         |\n|     navigational factors                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 24. Convert between True, Magnetic, and Compass courses in both       |\n|     directions                                                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 25. Determine position using dead reckoning, estimated position, and  |\n|     visual fixing                                                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 26. Demonstrate safe pilotage and passage by day and night at         |\n|     operational speed                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 27. Manage crew effectively during navigational duties                |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Passage Planning**\n\nA passage plan consists of three or more waypoints with the following\nconsiderations at each:\n\n  **Factor**           **What to Check**\n\n  Low water / high     Will there be enough water at all points along the\n  water (standard      route for the entire duration of the passage?\n  port)                Check depths against tide height at the time you\n                       will be there\n\n  Range (spring /      Determines tidal stream strength and available\n  neap)                depth\n\n  Rate and direction   Tidal stream rate and direction from tidal\n                       diamonds or stream atlas for each hour of the\n                       passage\n\n  Clearance heights    Bridges, overhead cables, or structures you will\n                       pass under — check the clearance against tide\n                       height\n\n  Notices to mariners  Temporary hazards, changes, or restrictions not\n                       yet charted\n\n  Limiting danger      Mark the minimum safe depth contour on the chart.\n  lines                If you cross this line, you are in danger\n\n  Overfalls / shoal    Areas of disturbed water caused by tidal flow over\n  ground               shallow or uneven seabed\n\n  Wrecks / rocks       Charted hazards that must be given adequate\n                       clearance\n\n  Buoyed channel       Identify the buoyed channels and whether you need\n                       to follow them\n\n  Traffic separation   Rule 10 applies. Cross at right angles. Do not\n  scheme               enter unless crossing\n\n  Hazards to shipping  Commercial traffic, fishing vessels, military\n                       exercise areas\n\n  No-go areas          Military firing ranges (Hythe Ranges at\n                       Littlestone), exclusion zones, nature reserves\n\n  Weather / sea state  Current and forecast. A85 limits: daylight F7,\n                       darkness F6\n\n  Safe havens          Identify ports or shelter along the route in case\n                       of emergency or deteriorating conditions\n\n  Contingency plans    What to do if conditions change, equipment fails,\n                       or a crew member is injured en route\n\n  Waypoint convergence Avoid placing waypoints too close together — the\n                       boat may overshoot one and the SIMS will jump to\n                       the next, causing confusion\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.3a, pp.233 — 234*\n\n**Determining Position on Passage**\n\nYou must be able to determine your position using four methods and\nunderstand when each is appropriate:\n\n  **Method**       **When to Use**      **How to Plot**\n\n  Dead reckoning   When you have no fix From last known position, draw the\n  (DR)             available. Uses      course line for the distance run.\n                   course steered and   Mark with a single arrow and time.\n                   distance run only    Symbol: a cross with no circle\n\n  Estimated        When you can apply   From the DR position, draw the\n  position (EP)    tidal stream and/or  tidal stream vector (direction and\n                   leeway to your DR    distance for the period). The end\n                                        of this vector is the EP. Symbol:\n                                        triangle with a dot\n\n  Course to steer  When you know where  Plot the intended track. Apply the\n                   you want to go and   tidal stream vector to the\n                   need to account for  destination. The line from your\n                   tidal stream         position to the end of the stream\n                                        vector is your course to steer\n\n  Course made good To determine where   Plot your actual position fixes\n                   you actually went vs over time. The line connecting\n                   where you planned    them is your course made good.\n                                        Compare to intended track to\n                                        assess tidal stream effect\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.3a, p.234; TP-LB-01, Activity 7, pp.300 — 302*\n\n**Pilotage and Passage**\n\nPilotage is navigation in confined or hazardous waters using visual\nreferences, depth, and radar. Passage is navigation in open water using\ncharts and instruments. You must demonstrate both by day and night,\nacross the full range of A85 operating speeds. High-speed navigation\nrequires:\n\n-   Increased situational awareness — less time to notice or react to\n    hazards\n\n-   Planning further ahead — reduced thinking time at 35 knots vs 10\n    knots\n\n-   Clear communications and procedures between Helm, navigator, and\n    crew\n\n-   Increased monitoring with reduced fixing intervals\n\n-   Electronic navigation equipment set up to best aid high-speed\n    navigation (appropriate range scales, XTE alarm tight, waypoint\n    proximity alarm active)\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.2b, p.231; Task 7.1.3a, p.234*\n\n**Managing the Navigation Team**\n\nAs Navigator, you manage the navigational effort, not just perform it.\nThis means:\n\n-   Allocating crew roles against competence (experienced crew on\n    critical tasks)\n\n-   Effective briefing and communications — the Helm must know what is\n    coming next\n\n-   Positioning yourself on board to manage navigation (on the A85: Crew\n    2 or 3 position, with access to SIMS screens, paper charts, and VHF)\n\n-   Confirming and correcting information and data from crew — if a\n    lookout reports a bearing, check it makes sense against your chart\n    plot\n\n-   Utilising and validating crew input — ensure all crew understand\n    they have a role in safe passage. Acknowledge hazards identified by\n    other crew\n\n-   Adapting your management style to the conditions — in calm\n    daylight you can discuss and explain; in heavy weather at night you\n    give clear, concise orders\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.1.3b, p.235*\n",
  "7.2.1": "### 7.2.1 E NAVIGATION\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 28. Start up, set up, and operate the A85 SIMS and GPS                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 29. Create, edit, and delete waypoints and routes                     |\n|                                                                       |\n| 30. Follow a route using electronic navigation including XTE          |\n|     monitoring                                                        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 31. Understand and respond to all electronic navigation alarms        |\n|                                                                       |\n| 32. Know the limitations of electronic systems and what to do when    |\n|     they fail                                                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Equipment on the A85**\n\nThe electronic navigation equipment provides:\n\n  **System**       **What It Provides**\n\n  GPS              Bearing, distance, accurate position, time, ETA, COG,\n                   SOG. Feeds data to SIMS and other equipment\n\n  SIMS chart       Displays vessel position on electronic chart. Plot and\n  plotter          follow routes. Input search patterns. Two workstations\n                   (master/slave)\n\n  Depth sounder    Depth of water below the hull. Set the shallow water\n                   alarm to warn of reducing depth\n\n  Radar            Collision avoidance, vessel tracking, casualty\n                   location, general navigation, and pilotage\n\n  AIS              Automatic identification of vessels transmitting AIS.\n                   Shows name, MMSI, position, course, speed\n\n  DF (Direction    Locates VHF transmissions, EPIRB and PLB distress\n  Finder)          signals by bearing\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.2.1a, p.236; TP-LB-23, Activity 7, p.68*\n\n**Start-Up Procedure**\n\nPower up in order: GPS first (as it feeds other equipment), then\nSIMS/chart plotter and radar. The RNLI SIMS has three toggle switches:\nNav 1, Nav 2, and Radar. All three should be turned on. Verify\nfunctioning: check position against a known reference, check depth\nagainst chart, respond to any error messages or alarms.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 7, p.68; TP-OCF-02, Task 7.2.1a, p.236*\n\n**Creating and Following Routes**\n\nYou must demonstrate:\n\n-   Entering a waypoint by latitude/longitude, or by range and bearing\n    from a fixed point\n\n-   Editing and deleting waypoints\n\n-   Constructing a route from multiple waypoints and editing it\n    (including moving waypoints)\n\n-   Checking pre-made routes — confirming they are current and safe\n    before use\n\n-   Following a route or 'go to' waypoint, monitoring: lat/long, COG,\n    SOG, bearing and range to waypoint, XTE, VMG (velocity made good)\n\n-   Altering route direction: forward, reverse, and advance (skip to\n    next waypoint)\n\n-   Using the boundary function (if fitted) to highlight hazard areas\n    and no-go zones\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.2.1b, pp.238 — 239*\n\n**Alarms**\n\n  **Alarm**      **What It Means**          **Action**\n\n  XTE            You have deviated from the Check position. Assess cause\n  (cross-track   planned track beyond the   (tidal stream, wind, helm\n  error)         set tolerance              error). Correct course. If XTE\n                                            is 45°+ off course, the\n                                            plotter may cease displaying\n                                            critical information\n\n  Waypoint       You are approaching the    Prepare for course alteration.\n  proximity      next waypoint              Confirm next heading with the\n                                            Helm\n\n  Anchor watch   The vessel has moved       The anchor may be dragging.\n                 beyond the set radius from Check transits. Take action\n                 the anchor position        (more scope, redeploy, or\n                                            weigh)\n\n  Lost signal    GPS has lost satellite     Fix position by other means\n                 lock                       (radar, visual, DR). Reduce\n                                            speed. Inform the Helm. Do not\n                                            rely on the last displayed\n                                            position\n\n  MOB            Man overboard alarm        Follow EOP 1. The SIMS records\n                 activated                  the position automatically\n\n  Shallow water  Depth below the set alarm  Alert the Helm immediately.\n                 threshold                  Reduce speed. Check chart for\n                                            safe water\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.2.1a, pp.236 — 237*\n\n**Limitations and Failure**\n\nElectronic navigation equipment can fail. You must know the limitations\nand the actions:\n\n-   GPS/chart plotter limitations: operator error (most common), power\n    failure, poor aerial siting or shielding, poor satellite reception\n\n-   Echo sounder limitations: disturbed water gives false readings,\n    false echoes from marine life or sediment\n\n-   On failure: acknowledge and record alarms. Fix position by other\n    available means on paper chart. Reduce speed. Adapt the plan and\n    resources to account for the failure. Inform the Helm immediately\n\n-   If fitted, demonstrate use of secondary navigation system\n    (standalone GPS, handheld GPS)\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.2.1a, p.237*\n\n**Shutdown Procedure**\n\nBefore shutdown: cancel route, clear sail plan, delete unwanted\nwaypoints and tracks. Shutdown the SIMS in the correct order as per\nequipment manual.\n",
  "7.2.2": "### 7.2.2 E NAVIGATION ADVANCED\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 33. Input and execute search patterns on SIMS                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 34. Integrate electronic navigation with paper chart plotting         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 35. Manage electronic navigation in challenging conditions at command |\n|     standard                                                          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nE Navigation Advanced builds on the E Navigation module to cover the\ncommand-level application: inputting search patterns from Coastguard\ntasking data (Card 7 of the SAR Check Cards), integrating electronic and\npaper chart positions in real time, and managing electronic navigation\nduring complex multi-phase operations (transit to scene, execute search,\nrecover casualty, transit to safe haven). You must demonstrate the\nability to switch seamlessly between electronic and paper navigation\nwhen electronic systems fail or when paper charts provide better detail\nfor close-quarters work.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Tasks 7.2.2, pp.240 — 241*\n",
  "7.3.1": "### 7.3.1 RADAR\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 36. Set up, adjust, and check the radar for optimal performance       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 37. Interpret the radar picture: identify targets, clutter, and radar |\n|     shadows                                                           |\n|                                                                       |\n| 38. Determine if a risk of collision exists using radar               |\n|                                                                       |\n| 39. Fix position using radar (VRM and EBL)                            |\n|                                                                       |\n| 40. Use radar for pilotage including parallel index lines             |\n|                                                                       |\n| 41. Recognise a SART (Search and Rescue Transponder) on the display   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 42. Integrate radar and chart plotter information                     |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Setting Up the Radar**\n\nOn the A85, radar is accessed through SIMS and is displayed on either\ncrew screen. Setup:\n\n-   Turn on the Radar toggle switch (one of the three SIMS switches)\n\n-   Allow the radar to warm up and begin painting a picture\n\n-   Select the appropriate range scale for your situation (shorter range\n    for close-quarters, longer for open water)\n\n-   Adjust gain (sensitivity) until targets are clearly visible without\n    excessive clutter\n\n-   Adjust sea clutter (STC) to reduce returns from waves close to the\n    vessel\n\n-   Adjust rain clutter (FTC) if precipitation is causing interference\n\n-   Select orientation: head-up (vessel heading always at the top — \n    most intuitive for ILB) or north-up (true north at the top — \n    matches the chart)\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1a, p.243; TP-LB-23, Activity 7, p.68*\n\n**Interpreting the Radar Picture**\n\nThe radar display shows echoes (returns) from objects that reflect the\nradar beam. What you see on screen:\n\n  **Feature**    **What It Looks      **How to Interpret**\n                 Like**               \n\n  Land           Strong, solid        Compare with the chart. Known\n                 returns forming      headlands, harbour walls, and cliffs\n                 recognisable         give distinctive returns\n                 coastline shapes     \n\n  Vessels        Small bright dots or Compare successive sweeps to\n                 short arcs. Moving   determine direction and speed of\n                 targets change       movement. A target with constant\n                 position between     bearing and decreasing range is on\n                 scans                collision course\n\n  Buoys / small  Small, intermittent  Difficult to detect reliably. Use\n  objects        returns. May be lost long pulse and increase gain to\n                 in sea clutter at    enhance small target detection\n                 close range          \n\n  Sea clutter    Bright returns close Adjust STC to reduce. Do not\n                 to the centre caused over-adjust — you may suppress\n                 by wave reflections  real targets hidden in the clutter\n\n  Rain clutter   Diffuse, bright      Adjust FTC to reduce. Rain also\n                 areas on the display attenuates the radar beam — \n                 corresponding to     targets behind the rain may be\n                 rain showers         invisible (radar shadow)\n\n  Radar shadow   Areas behind large   No returns does not mean no targets.\n                 objects (land, large Be aware that vessels can be hidden\n                 vessels) where the   behind headlands or large ships\n                 radar beam cannot    \n                 reach                \n\n  SART (Search   A line of 12 blips   A distress signal and aid to\n  and Rescue     along the bearing of locating survivors. The first echo\n  Transponder)   the SART. As range   is the target position\n                 decreases, the blips \n                 become arcs, then    \n                 concentric circles   \n                 at about 1 NM        \n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1b — c, pp.244 — 246; Task 7.3.1f, p.249*\n\n**Collision Avoidance Using Radar**\n\nThe fundamental technique: plot a target's bearing and range over time.\nIf the bearing is constant and the range is decreasing, you are on a\ncollision course (same principle as visual CBDR, but radar gives you the\ndata in poor visibility when you cannot see the vessel).\n\nTo determine if a close-quarters situation is developing:\n\n-   Use EBL (Electronic Bearing Line) to measure the bearing of the\n    target\n\n-   Use VRM (Variable Range Marker) to measure the range\n\n-   Record bearing and range at regular intervals (e.g. every 3 minutes)\n\n-   If bearing is steady and range decreasing → collision risk exists →\n    take action per IRPCS\n\n-   If bearing is drawing ahead (moving forward relative to you) →\n    target will pass ahead\n\n-   If bearing is drawing aft → target will pass astern\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1c, p.246*\n\n**Position Fixing by Radar**\n\nFix position using radar by taking range and bearing to identifiable\ncharted targets (headlands, harbour walls, isolated rocks). Plot the\nrange arc and bearing line on the chart — where they intersect is your\nposition. Radar fixes are particularly valuable in restricted visibility\nwhen visual fixes are impossible.\n\nFor pilotage, use parallel index lines (if the SIMS supports them): set\nan index line parallel to your intended track at a set range from a\ncharted target. If the target stays on the index line, you are on track.\nIf it moves, you are drifting off track.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1e, pp.248 — 249*\n\n**Radar/Chart Plotter Integration**\n\nThe A85 SIMS can overlay radar returns on the electronic chart and vice\nversa. This integration allows you to see radar targets in the context\nof your charted position. MARPA (Mini Automatic Radar Plotting Aid)\ntargets, if available, can be automatically tracked with range, bearing,\nclosest point of approach (CPA), and time to CPA displayed. Waypoints\nand routes from the chart plotter can also be displayed on the radar\nscreen.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1f, p.249*\n\n**Command Responsibilities**\n\nAs Navigator, you are responsible for the correct interpretation of and\nresponse to radar information. In clear weather, you use radar as a\nsupplement to visual lookout. In restricted visibility, radar becomes\nyour primary collision avoidance tool and Rule 19 (IRPCS) applies. You\nmust demonstrate correct appreciation of the radar situation and correct\nactions taken for all situations presented.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.3.1d, p.247*\n",
  "7.4.1": "## Local Knowledge — Littlestone Operating Area\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Know the Littlestone operating area from Rye to Dover             |\n| 2.  Identify all local navigational aids, landmarks, hazards, and no-go areas |\n| 3.  Know the emergency extraction points and casualty landing sites   |\n| 4.  Understand local regulations including military ranges and bylaws |\n| 5.  Know the Littlestone-specific launch and recovery procedures      |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nLocal knowledge is built over time and continuously updated. This content is drawn directly from the Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP and the B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP.\n\n### Local Navigational Aids (Rye to Dover)\n\n**Cardinal marks:**\n- South Cardinal — Dungeness\n- North Cardinal — Bullock Bank\n- South Cardinal — Varne Bank\n\n**Other key buoyage:**\n- CS3 Special Mark Buoy\n- Rye Harbour Fairway Buoy\n- Hythe Sewer Outlet Buoy\n\n### Landmarks, Harbours and Headlands\n\nFrom west to east along the operating area:\n\n| **Location** | **Notes** |\n|---|---|\n| Rye Harbour | Tidal ±3hrs. VHF Harbour Master Ch14 |\n| Camber Sands | Beach landmark |\n| Jury's Gap / Galloway's | Coastal features |\n| Dengmarsh / Dungeness | Both working and non-working lighthouse |\n| Dungeness Lifeboat Station | Flank station (Shannon class) |\n| Lade Toilets | Landmark and emergency extraction point |\n| Littlestone Lifeboat Station | Home station |\n| Water Tower, Littlestone | Prominent landmark for sea approaches |\n| Pirate Springs | Emergency extraction point |\n| Dymchurch Main Slip / Redoubt | Coastal features |\n| Old Lifeboat Station, Fisherman's Beach | Historical landmark |\n| Hythe Imperial / Battery Point | Battery Point is the fuel station |\n| Mermaid Beach / Folkestone Harbour | Folkestone Harbour is tidal |\n| Sunny Sands / Copt Point | Shallow water, rocks visible |\n| The Warren / Concrete Apron | Coastal feature |\n| Samphire Hoe | Rock visible |\n| Dover Port (Western & Eastern Entrance) | Major commercial port |\n| Dover Lifeboat Station | Flank station — via Dover Port Western Entrance |\n\n### Emergency Extraction Points\n\n| **Location** | **Access** |\n|---|---|\n| Rye Harbour Lifeboat Station | Tidal ±3hrs. VHF Ch14 |\n| Dengmarsh, Lydd | Beach extraction |\n| Dungeness Lifeboat Station | Flank station |\n| Lade Toilets | Beach access |\n| Littlestone Lifeboat Station | Home station |\n| Pirate Springs | Beach access |\n| Dymchurch Slip | Slipway access |\n| Hythe Imperial | Beach access |\n| Mermaid Beach | Beach access |\n| Battery Point (Fuel Station) | Access point |\n| Folkestone Harbour (Tidal) | Harbour access |\n| Dover Lifeboat Station | Via Dover Port Western Entrance |\n\n### Local Regulations\n\n| **Regulation** | **Detail** |\n|---|---|\n| Hythe and Lydd Military Ranges | Active firing ranges — check times. Range Safety Vessels and Range Towers on VHF Ch73 |\n| Commercial shipping lane | 4 miles SE of Dungeness. IRPCS Rule 10 (TSS) applies |\n| Dungeness Lighthouse | Active lighthouse — relevant in fog |\n| Dymchurch Bylaw | No jet ski launching permitted |\n| Dymchurch Bylaw | Power-driven vessels: 6 knot speed limit inside the buoyed area |\n\n### Hazards and No-Go Areas\n\n:::warning\nMany of these hazards are **unlit** — particular caution is needed at night. This list is not exhaustive; local conditions change with weather, tide, and season.\n:::\n\n| **Hazard** | **Location / Detail** |\n|---|---|\n| Sand bar | Entrance to Rye Harbour — dangerous and shifting |\n| Wreck 'Veermann' | Camber Bay, UNLIT — 050°55.3'N 000°49.13'E |\n| Wreck 'Coruna' | Camber Bay, UNLIT — 050°55.49'N 000°48.10'E |\n| Lydd Firing Ranges | Active military range — check firing times before entering area |\n| Mulberry Harbour remains | Littlestone, UNLIT — submerged WWII structure |\n| Timber groynes | Littlestone to Hythe — wooden structures extending from the beach |\n| St Marys Bay Outfall | Sewage outfall pipe extending seaward |\n| Dymchurch buoys and groynes | UNLIT buoys at Dymchurch Slip; groynes along shore |\n| Rock armour | St Marys Bay to Folkestone — large rocks along coast defence |\n| Battery Point to Sandgate | Rock visible at low tide |\n| Copt Point | Shallow water — rocks visible |\n| Samphire Hoe | Rock visible |\n| Hythe Ranges | Active military range |\n\n### Littlestone Launch Procedure (Station-Specific LOP)\n\n**Mandatory PPE:**\n- **Head Launcher** — orange high-visibility vest, steel toe cap wellies, orange Gecko\n- **Tractor driver (LVD)** — steel toe cap wellies, tractor lifejacket (manual inflation), suitable PPE for conditions\n- **Shore crew** — yellow high-visibility vest, steel toe cap wellies, whistles\n\n:::steps\n1. LA appoints approved **Head Launcher** and **LVD** (Licensed Vehicle Driver)\n2. **Prepare boat and launch vehicle** — disconnect electric chargers, close all hatches and pouches, hand red tags to Head Launcher\n3. LVD carries out **vehicle checks**\n4. Open boathouse door and place **barriers either side** outside\n5. **Clear boathouse of ALL personnel** before the vehicle moves\n6. Head Launcher uses **hand signals** to signal tractor driver it is clear to move out\n7. Helm gives the **SMEAC briefing**\n8. Head Launcher instructs shore crew to **position marshals** in designated areas\n9. **Stop rig** to allow crew to put A-frame and aerials in position\n10. Head Launcher asks for **DoDo trailer to be made ready** — water pipes checked/removed from engine fishtails, tanks opened as required\n11. **Radio check** — Head Launcher to tractor on Ch31, then control passed to Helm for launch\n12. Helm **directs LVD** to ramp and down to launch site as per SOP\n13. All crew aware of **public, dogs, and waterborne craft** — at low water, a marshal is placed on the beach\n14. After launch, shore crew **escort rig back to boathouse** in same positions\n:::\n\n### Littlestone Recovery Procedure (Station-Specific LOP)\n\n:::steps\n1. **Washdown on the ramp** if necessary\n2. Stop in designated area to **make ready for recovery**\n3. **Spring ropes replaced** on DoDo carriage; water tanks switched off and refilled; water pipes stored\n4. Carriage prepared as instructed by Helm — **gates open/closed or net rigged**\n5. **Radio check** — Head Launcher to tractor on Ch31\n6. Head Launcher and driver **observe safest route** to shoreline\n7. Tractor driver **contacts Helm** for recovery information, performed as per SOP\n8. After recovery, LVD brings rig back to ramp; **shore crew marshal** under Head Launcher direction\n9. **Washdown** at top of ramp or outside boathouse\n10. Crew assigned tasks — **washdown, refuelling, make ready for service**, post-recovery checks per PM job cards\n11. **Rig put away** in boathouse under Head Launcher instruction\n12. **Full debrief** in boathouse with all crew involved\n:::\n\n:::info\nIn case of emergency, tractor failure, or ramp failure, **Dover Harbour or the local beach** are to be used as alternatives.\n:::\n\n### Flank Stations\n\nKnow your flanks — part of the launch authority decision may involve suggesting a flank station is better placed to respond:\n- **West** — Dungeness Lifeboat Station (Shannon class all-weather lifeboat)\n- **East** — Dover Lifeboat Station (Severn class all-weather lifeboat)\n",
  "7.4.2": "### 7.4.2 Local Knowledge (Afloat)\n\n\nAshore local knowledge is taught in the Shore Crew Stage 2 guide with\ncomplete Littlestone operating area detail. At Tier 1, the afloat\nperspective adds: casualty landing points in the area (all 12 emergency\nextraction points from the Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP), chart-based\nknowledge of depths, hazards from the water side (the wrecks Veermann\nand Coruna are visible on approach, not just as positions on paper),\ntidal streams and their effect on boat handling, and the shipping lane 4\nmiles SE of Dungeness where IRPCS Rule 10 (Traffic Separation Schemes)\napplies.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.4.2, p.251; Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP V4.0*\n\n**ILB DECISION SUPPORT CHECK CARDS (TP-LB-28)**\n\nThese cards are carried on the Atlantic 85 and must be accessible at all\ntimes. They provide structured decision aids and emergency procedures.\nAs Tier 1 crew, you must know every card exists, what it covers, and\nwhere it fits into an operation. The Helm leads the use of these cards,\nbut every crew member must understand them.\n\n**Card 2 — Briefing Structure (SMEAC)**\n\n  **Element**          **Prompt Question**\n\n  S — Situation      What are the facts? Give a big picture summary\n\n  M — Mission        What is the objective? What are we going to do?\n\n  E — Execution      How are we going to do this? Allocate roles and\n                       responsibilities\n\n  A — Administration What support do you need? Consider other SAR\n                       assets, additional resources, extra equipment, and\n                       crew welfare\n\n  C — Command,       Pause... Is there a reason this plan won't work?\n  Communication and    What have I missed?\n  Confirmation         \n\n*Source: TP-LB-28, Card 2*\n\n**Card 4 — Multiple Person in the Water: Triage**\n\nIf the Helm believes the situation and number of casualties is beyond\nthe capability of available assets, inform the Coastguard that this is a\n'multiple persons in the water incident'. The triage procedure is:\n\n-   1\\. Assess the scene and brief the crew\n\n-   2\\. Scan the area and deploy Lifesaving Apparatus (LSA)\n\nThen prioritise recovery in this order:\n\n  **Element**   **Prompt Questions**\n\n  S — Safety  What did we do well? What would we change to be safer\n                next time?\n\n  P — People  Is everyone OK? Consider physical health, mental health,\n                crew welfare, members of the public\n\n  E — Did everything perform as expected? Are there any defects\n  Equipment     to report?\n\n  P — Did we achieve what we intended? What could we do\n  Performance   differently next time? Were there any problems and does\n                anyone else need to be informed?\n\n*Source: TP-LB-28, Card 6*\n\n**EOP 1 — Man Overboard**\n\nImmediate actions (all happen simultaneously):\n\n-   Inform all crew: shout 'Man Overboard!'\n\n-   Push and hold the MOB alarm button\n\n-   Reduce speed, turn onto reciprocal course\n\n  **Card**   **Title**           **Content / Purpose**\n\n  Card 7     Search Instructions Records all search parameters from the\n             Form                Coastguard: incident details, search\n                                 object description, search pattern, CSP\n                                 (lat/long), direction of first leg, leg\n                                 length, track spacing, first turn\n                                 direction, number of legs or overall\n                                 search width, search area size, search\n                                 speed, other SAR units and channels,\n                                 A/B/C/D coordinates if provided. Note:\n                                 advise Coastguard when commencing\n                                 penultimate leg using the SITREP\n\n  Card 8     SAR Situation       Standardised form for reporting the\n             Report (SITREP)     current situation back to the Coastguard\n                                 during a search. Includes: position,\n                                 search progress, weather on scene, fuel\n                                 state, crew condition, any sightings\n\n  Card 9     Reporting of Search Used to report back to the Coastguard how\n             Effectiveness       effective the completed search was, so\n                                 the SMC can plan follow-up searches\n\n*Source: TP-LB-45, Cards 7 — 9*\n\n**Section 3 — Independent Search Planning**\n\n  **Card**   **Title**           **Content / Purpose**\n\n  Card 10    Corrected Sweep     Reference table providing sweep width\n             Widths              values based on target type, sea state,\n                                 and visibility. Used to calculate track\n                                 spacing for independent search planning\n                                 when the Coastguard has not specified it\n\n*Source: TP-LB-45, Card 10*\n\n**Section 4 — Search Patterns (Cards 11 — 16)**\n\nCards 11 — 16 provide visual examples and worked calculations for each\nsearch pattern. The key details from each card:\n\n  **Card**   **Pattern**      **Key Details from the Card**\n\n  Card 11    Sector Search    Datum search from a central point. Use\n             (water-based)    compass headings and LOG speed (not GPS).\n                              Deploy a physical datum marker\n\n  Card 12    Expanding Square Datum search with timed legs increasing after\n             (water-based)    every two legs. Card includes a worked\n                              example: CSP 050°20.0'N 002°05.0'W, ITS 0.4\n                              NM, speed calculated from sweep width. 20-leg\n                              table with times and cardinal headings.\n                              Notes: use compass headings not COG; use\n                              speed through water not SOG; time countdown\n                              prior to turning; tick off legs once complete\n\n  Card 13    Parallel Track / Area searches. Parallel track: longest leg\n             Creeping Line    parallel to longest edge of box. Creeping\n             (ground-based)   line: longest leg parallel to shortest edge.\n                              CSP is always half a track space in from the\n                              box edge. Search width = track spacing x\n                              number of legs\n\n  Card 14    Amended          Amended Shoreline: first leg at 0.5 track\n             Shoreline /      space from shore, each subsequent leg steps\n             Amended Creeping out one full track spacing. Use radar for\n             Line             accurate distance. Amended Creeping Line:\n                              follows coast contour at 0.5 track space,\n                              working outward\n\n  Card 15    Barrier / Track  Single line of search along a known track.\n             Line Search      Ground-based\n\n  Card 16    OSC / Search     For when the A85 is appointed On-Scene\n             Planning         Coordinator. Form for recording: search\n                              pattern, A/B/C/D coordinates, CSP, initial\n                              heading, first turn direction, track spacing,\n                              number of legs, search area dimensions, and\n                              up to 8 assets with their assignments\n\n*Source: TP-LB-45, Cards 11 — 16*\n\n**Card 17 — Helicopter Operations**\n\nReference card for ILB helicopter operations, covering communication\nprocedures, approach configurations, and winching procedures. Helicopter\noperations are covered in detail at Tier 2 level (Task 4.10.1) but\nawareness of this card and its location is required at Tier 1.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-45, Card 17*\n",
  "7.4.3": "### 7.4.3 LOCAL KNOWLEDGE (COMMAND)\n\n\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 24. Make launch decisions based on local conditions at Littlestone    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 25. Identify alternative launch and recovery sites and when to use    |\n|     them                                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 26. Manage operations across all areas of the Littlestone operating   |\n|     area                                                              |\n|                                                                       |\n| 27. Maintain and communicate updated local information to all         |\n|     personnel                                                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nAs Head Launcher, you need all the local knowledge from Stage 2 (Shore\nCrew) plus the command-level ability to make decisions based on that\nknowledge. This means not just knowing that the Mulberry Harbour remains\nare unlit off Littlestone, but deciding how that affects your launch\npoint at low water on a dark night. Not just knowing that Dover Harbour\nis the emergency alternative, but knowing when to make the call to use\nit.\n\n**Factors Affecting Your Launch Decisions at Littlestone**\n\n  **Factor**       **How It Affects Your Decision**\n\n  Ramp condition   Seaweed, algae growth, ice in winter — assess before\n                   every launch. May need additional marshals or\n                   alternative route\n\n  Beach profile    Changes with tide, season, and storms. Soft sand areas\n                   may shift. Assess in situ before committing vehicle\n\n  Tide state       At high water: reduced beach area, potential water on\n                   ramp. At low water: longer transit, soft ground risk,\n                   need to consider DoDo Release/Winch EOP\n\n  Summer crowds    Dymchurch to Littlestone beaches are busy. More\n                   marshals needed. Consider timing of exercises\n\n  Wind direction   Onshore wind increases surf — affects recovery\n                   method choice (stern vs net). Offshore wind may affect\n                   smoke/fume direction in fire\n\n  Darkness         Scene lighting required. Greater risk of unseen\n                   hazards. Fewer public but harder to manage those\n                   present\n\n  Military range   Check Hythe and Lydd firing times. Monitor VHF CH73\n  activity         for range safety vessel communications\n\n*Source: Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP V4.0; Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0*\n\n**Alternative Sites**\n\nYou must know when to use alternative launch or recovery sites. At\nLittlestone, the primary alternative in an emergency (tractor/ramp\nfailure) is Dover Harbour or the local beach. For recovery, if stern\nrecovery is not safe, the Helm must opt for net recovery or a safe\nhaven. You must be familiar with any LOP variations for alternative\nsites and brief all crew on changed procedures and additional hazards.\n\n*Source: Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0, p.3; A85 Launch & Recovery SOP V7.0, p.3*\n\n**Maintaining Local Knowledge**\n\nIt is your responsibility to ensure updated local information reaches\nall shore crew. The process is: information comes from Poole HQ,\nnational sources, and local observations; LOPs are updated in accordance\nwith the current template and guidelines; LOPs must be approved\ncentrally before adoption; and all station personnel must be kept\ninformed of new hazards, features, and regulations so they can maintain\neffective situational awareness.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.4.3, pp.252 — 253*\n\n**COMMAND SKILLS**\n\nCommanding people undertaking operational activity is a unique\nresponsibility. As Head Launcher, you need not only the knowledge and\nunderstanding of procedures but the ability to lead people, perhaps\nunder challenging conditions. You must demonstrate four command skills.\nThe table below (drawn directly from the Pass Out Handbook) shows\nexamples of the positive behaviours you should aim for, and the negative\nbehaviours you must avoid:\n\n  **Skill**       **Positive Behaviour**      **Negative Behaviour**\n\n  Communication   Communicates clearly in a   Communicates in an\n                  standardised, efficient     unstructured, inconsistent\n                  format                      manner\n\n  Communication   Shares information when     Withholds or gives\n                  relevant and at the right   incomplete information\n                  time                        \n\n  Communication   Proceeds with               Proceeds without informing\n                  safety-critical tasks only  crew or cross-checking\n                  when crew are informed and  \n                  can cross-check             \n\n  Communication   Raises opportunities for    Responds negatively to\n                  questions; questions are    questions; discourages crew\n                  open (e.g. 'have I missed f rom speaking up\n                  anything?')                 \n\n  Decision Making Is proactive and actively   Is reactive and passive;\n                  takes control of the        the situation develops\n                  situation                   around them\n\n  Decision Making Takes time to make a        Fails to take time; jumps\n                  decision; avoids jumping to to conclusions\n                  conclusions                 \n\n  Decision Making Recognises when a situation Fails to recognise or apply\n                  is covered by SOP/EOP/LOP   the correct procedure\n                  and applies it              \n\n  Decision Making Briefs regularly in an      Fails to brief effectively;\n                  open, collaborative way;    leaves the HOW uncovered\n                  covers the HOW as well as   \n                  the WHAT                    \n\n  Decision Making Reviews the plan to check   Sticks to the initial plan\n                  it is still appropriate;    even when clearly\n                  changes it if not           inappropriate\n\n  Teamwork        Demonstrates awareness of   Underuses or overburdens\n                  crew abilities;             crew members\n                  incorporates this into task \n                  guidance                    \n\n  Teamwork        Actively seeks opinions,    Has little interest in crew\n                  ideas, and cross-checking   input\n                  from crew                   \n\n  Teamwork        Actively seeks to avoid,    Uses sarcasm, is abrupt, or\n                  identify, and resolve       dismissive\n                  conflict                    \n\n  Teamwork        Supports crew members when  Demonstrates lack of\n                  difficult emotional or      support\n                  physical states are         \n                  identified                  \n\n  Situational     Uses information from       Shows tunnel vision on one\n  Awareness       multiple sources to form an element\n                  overall picture             \n\n  Situational     Recognises external cues in Does not recognise cues or\n  Awareness       good time and plans         recognises them late\n                  effectively                 \n\n  Situational     Notes the time to manage    Lacks awareness of time and\n  Awareness       time-related factors        time-related factors\n\n  Situational     Identifies possible escape  Fails to identify escape\n  Awareness       points                      points\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, pp.52 — 53*\n\n#### Helm Command Perspective\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 47. Apply complete Littlestone local knowledge to command-level       |\n|     decisions                                                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 48. Know all casualty landing points, emergency extraction points,    |\n|     and alternative launch sites                                      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 49. Know flank stations, their SAR units, and their limitations       |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nLocal Knowledge at ashore and afloat level is taught in the Shore Crew\nand Tier 1 guides with complete Littlestone detail. At command level,\nyou must be able to apply all of this knowledge to make operational\ndecisions: choosing recovery sites based on conditions, identifying\ncasualty landing points for ambulance handover, knowing when to use\nDungeness or Dover as a flank station (and their operational\nlimitations), and understanding how seasonal variations (summer crowds,\nwinter storms), tidal state, wind direction, and darkness affect every\naspect of the operation from launch to recovery.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 7.4.3; Littlestone Local Knowledge LOP V4.0*\n\n# Domain 8: First Aid & Casualty Care\n",
  "9.1.2": "### 9.1.2 OPERATE ILB MAIN MACHINERY\n\n*Source: Helm Command guide*\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 50. Respond to all engine alarms correctly                            |\n|                                                                       |\n| 51. Manage refuelling with correct PPE and safety precautions         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 52. Start and stop engines correctly including post-capsize restart   |\n|                                                                       |\n| 53. Conduct single-engine running and understand its limitations      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 54. Manage engine failure, overheating, and loss of propulsion        |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\n**Engine Alarms**\n\n  **Alarm**      **Cause**             **Action**\n\n  Oil pressure   Low oil pressure.     Shut down the affected engine\n  warning        Possible oil loss,    where safe. Run on single engine.\n                 pump failure, or      Inform Coastguard\n                 bearing wear          \n\n  Coolant        Blocked cooling water Check tell-tale from back of\n  temperature /  intake, failed water  engine for water flow. If no flow,\n  overheat       pump, obstructed      shut down the engine. Run on\n                 tell-tale             single engine. Consider clearing\n                                       the intake (weed, debris)\n\n  Fuel alarm     Low fuel, fuel supply Check fuel tank levels. Consider\n                 problem, blocked      fuel changeover blocks to run both\n                 filter                engines from one tank (range\n                                       halved). Plan for nearest safe\n                                       haven or request assistance\n\n  Alternator /   Battery not charging. Use couple batteries button to\n  charging       Failed alternator,    link both banks. Monitor battery\n                 broken belt, wiring   voltage. Reduce electrical load\n                 fault                 (turn off non-essential\n                                       equipment). If both banks are\n                                       depleted, you will lose\n                                       electronics and engine start\n                                       capability\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 9.1.2a, pp.269 — 270*\n\n**A85 Fuel System**\n\nThe A85 has two fuel tanks (105 litres each, port and starboard). Each\nnormally feeds its respective engine. Fuel changeover blocks under the\ncrew seat allow both engines to run from one tank. If you connect both\nhoses to the same block (port or starboard), that single tank feeds both\nengines. Your range is halved but you retain twin-engine capability. The\nfull-throttle endurance on both tanks is approximately 2 hours 30\nminutes. At reduced speed, range and duration increase significantly.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.26*\n\n**Starting, Stopping, and Post-Capsize Restart**\n\nStarting procedure: both isolator switches ON, prime both fuel bulbs\n(located in front of engines), check throttles in neutral, press each\ngreen start button individually until the engine starts. Check the\ntell-tale from the back of each engine to confirm coolant flow. To stop:\nreturn throttles to neutral/idle, press and hold the red button until\nthe engine completely stops, then release.\n\nPost-capsize engine restart (EOP 5): throttles to neutral, check engine\nhoods are secure, check fuel connections, on/off switches to RUN, prime\nboth fuel bulbs, start engines, recover and stow sea anchor, inform the\nCoastguard.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 4, p.40; TP-LB-28, EOP 5*\n\n**Single-Engine Running**\n\nIf one engine fails or must be shut down, you must be able to continue\non single engine. Limitations: reduced speed, reduced manoeuvrability\n(the boat will want to turn towards the dead engine), increased fuel\nconsumption per engine. Crew weight distribution helps compensate for\nthe turning tendency. Where both engines could be used and one must be\nshut down (e.g. during veering), prefer to keep the starboard engine\nrunning to protect the steering ram on the port engine.\n\n*Source: 85-SOP-Veering Down V6.0, p.4; TP-OCF-02, Task 9.1.2a, p.269*\n\n**COMMAND SKILLS**\n\nThe complete positive and negative behaviours table for all four command\nskills (Communication, Decision Making, Teamwork, Situational Awareness)\nis reproduced in the Head Launcher guide. As Helm, you are assessed\nagainst these behaviours during the practical pass out. The assessor\nobserves the entire simulated shout and evaluates not just what you do,\nbut how you lead.\n\nThe key distinction at Helm level: at every other stage in the pathway,\nyou demonstrate command skills in a supporting role or a limited domain\n(Head Launcher commands the shore, Launch Authority commands the\ndecision to launch). As Helm, you demonstrate command skills across the\nentire operation simultaneously — briefing, launching, transiting,\nsearching, rescuing, towing, recovering, debriefing — while managing\ncrew welfare, communicating with the Coastguard, and maintaining your\nown situational awareness. There is no one above you afloat. The\ndecisions are yours.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-04, pp.10 — 13, 52 — 53*\n",
  "1.6.1": "### 1.6.1 EMERGENCY AND SURVIVAL PROCEDURES\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Know the immediate actions after a capsize and the A85 righting procedure |\n| 2.  Deploy and recover the sea anchor                                 |\n| 3.  Prepare for and execute abandonment                               |\n| 4.  Survive in cold water using HELP position and group techniques    |\n| 5.  Respond correctly as crew to a man overboard                      |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### A85 Post-Capsize Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Remain in your seat** until the boat inverts — find the air pocket between the console, deck, and sponson\n2. **Remove intercom cable** from your helmet immediately\n3. **Deploy the sea anchor** using the release (if underneath) or the remote release on the sponson\n4. **Exit from underneath** — easiest from the bow area. Assist anyone trapped\n5. **Assemble at the stern** if outside the boat. Deploy a swim line to full length\n6. **Head count** — check all crew are accounted for. If anyone missing, complete a 360° check\n7. On command, **activate ONE righting ring** on the transom\n8. If defective, wait **1 minute**, then activate the second righting bottle\n9. Once upright, **reboard the lifeboat**\n10. Recover swim line(s) and ensure sea anchor is deployed\n11. **Restart engines** — throttles neutral, check hoods, check fuel, switches to RUN, prime fuel bulbs, start\n12. Rig the **emergency antenna** if required\n13. **Send DSC distress alert** and voice Mayday. Leave righting bag inflated until recovered at station\n:::\n\n:::info\n**Automatic systems on capsize**: engines stop, air intake seals, deck lights illuminate inside the inverted vessel, fuel tank breather pipes seal via ball valves.\n:::\n\n### Abandonment Procedure\n\n:::steps\n1. **Note your position** from GPS or chart\n2. **Brief** the abandonment procedure to all crew\n3. **Send DSC distress alert** and voice Mayday (MIRDPANIO)\n4. **Collect grab bag**: VHF radio, flares, first aid kit, water\n5. **Full PPE check** — all cuffs closed, zips done, visor down, lifejacket inflated. Buddy check\n6. **Muster** in a safe location, carry out head count\n7. **Enter the water one person at a time** — slowly, to minimise cold water shock\n8. **Move clear** of the vessel. Group together\n9. **Activate PLBs**. Use HELP position (alone) or huddle (group)\n:::\n\n:::acronym HELP Position (Heat Escape Lessening Posture)\nH — **Hold** your knees up to your chest\nE — **Enclose** your arms across your chest\nL — **Limit** movement — keep still to conserve heat\nP — **Preserve** energy — don't swim unless rescue is close\n:::\n\n---\n\nThis is the module that prepares you for the worst-case scenarios. Every\nprocedure taught here exists because these emergencies have happened to\nRNLI crews. The CEP course gives you the practical experience; this\nsection gives you the knowledge framework.\n\n**Preparing for Heavy Weather**\n\nBefore conditions deteriorate:\n\n-   All loose items of equipment must be securely stowed\n\n-   All hatches closed to preserve watertight integrity\n\n-   Additional protective equipment donned: extra thermal layers, helmet\n\n-   Crew seated, holding on correctly, restrained by foot straps\n\n-   Shorten Coastguard reporting intervals (ILB: every 15 minutes)\n\n-   Grab bag prepared if available: portable VHF, GPS, first aid kit,\n    pyrotechnics, torch, food, water\n\n-   If crew must move around the vessel, inform the helm first so course\n    and speed can be altered\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, p.108*\n\n**Capsize on the Atlantic 85**\n\nThe A85 has been designed with re-righting capability. When the boat\ncapsizes, automatic systems activate: engines stop, air intake seals,\ndeck lights illuminate the inside of the inverted vessel, fuel tank\nbreather pipes seal via ball valves. The electrical systems are designed\nto withstand inversion.\n\n**During capsize:**\n\n-   Remain in your seat until the boat inverts — you will find an air\n    pocket between the console, deck, and sponson\n\n-   You may be thrown clear — if so, make contact with the boat as\n    soon as you safely can\n\n**Immediately after capsize:**\n\n-   Account for all personnel — head count\n\n-   Remove intercom cable from helmet\n\n-   Assist anyone trapped underneath to a safe exit (easiest from the\n    bow area)\n\n-   Assemble at the bow (if underneath) or group at the stern (if\n    outside)\n\n-   Deploy the sea anchor using the release attached to the sea anchor\n    bucket (if underneath) or the remote release on the starboard\n    sponson (which is now on the LEFT as the boat is inverted)\n\n-   Release one of the two orange swim lines and swim it out to full\n    length directly astern, positioning all crew at the far end away\n    from the boat\n\n-   Operate ONE of the two righting rings located on the transom\n\n-   The righting bag inflates, re-righting the boat. The bag has a\n    pressure relief valve preventing over-inflation, even if both\n    cylinders fire\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, pp.17 — 18*\n\n**Post-capsize checks:**\n\n-   Head count — is everyone accounted for?\n\n-   Injury assessment — immediate first aid for life-threatening\n    conditions\n\n-   Damage assessment — check for damage that might cause sinking\n\n-   Consider activating PLBs and using pyrotechnics\n\n-   Stay with the vessel — it is easier to locate a boat than\n    individuals in the water\n\n-   Raise the alarm — DSC distress alert. Aerials are prone to damage\n    in capsize; connect the emergency aerial before transmitting\n\n-   Check engines — ILB outboards stop automatically as a safety\n    precaution. Before restarting, ensure all ropes and debris are clear\n    of propellers\n\n-   Deploy sea anchor if not already done\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, pp.109 — 110; TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.18*\n\n**MOB Recovery on the A85**\n\nPreferred recovery location is the PORT side (because the throttles on\nthe starboard side impede movement). Crew should gain contact with the\nMOB level with the helm's seat, then guide them aft to the 4th seat\nwhere there is more space and the sponsons are lower. If recovery proves\ndifficult, the rear sponsons can be deflated to reduce freeboard.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.17*\n\n**Your actions as crew on a MOB:**\n\n-   Raise alarm: shout 'Man overboard!', activate MOB alarm\n\n-   Activate MOB function on SIMS (records time and position)\n\n-   Point continuously at the MOB if visual — do not lose sight\n\n-   Maintain communication to helm: direction, distance, condition of\n    person\n\n-   If visual contact lost at night or in poor weather: send DSC\n    distress and Mayday immediately, start datum search from the\n    SIMS-recorded position\n\n-   Prepare recovery equipment as directed by helm\n\n-   You must demonstrate the ability to recover a 35kg MOB dummy from\n    the water\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.1e, pp.85 — 86; TP-LB-23, Activity 2, p.17*\n\n**Sea Anchor**\n\nThe sea anchor is a parachute device streamed from the bow that\nstabilises the boat head-to-sea and slows drift. On the A85, the warp is\npermanently secured to the boat — it does not need to be independently\nsecured to another point. If sufficient sea room exists, deploy at full\nlength for maximum effectiveness.\n\n**When to deploy:**\n\n-   Post-capsize recovery\n\n-   Engine failure (single or both)\n\n-   Fouled propeller\n\n-   Swamping\n\n-   During helicopter transfer\n\n-   Propeller change\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, pp.109 — 110; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.1f, p.86*\n\n> **The sea anchor warp is permanently secured to the lifeboat. Be aware\n> of the hazards of snagging and coiled line going under load during\n> deployment. Communicate with the helm throughout. When restowing,\n> place weight on top if fitted.**\n\n**Abandonment**\n\nAbandonment is your last resort at sea. The factors that may trigger it:\ncritical damage to the vessel, uncontainable fire, risk to life if you\nremain. Your options are: to a liferaft, to another vessel, to a\nhelicopter, into the sea, or ashore.\n\n**Muster procedure:**\n\n-   Muster in a safe location, brief\n\n-   Full PPE: all cuffs closed, zips done, visor down, lifejacket\n    inflated\n\n-   Head count\n\n-   Prepare liferaft: remove from stowage, ensure painter is secure, do\n    NOT deploy until instructed\n\n-   Send distress: DSC alert, voice Mayday, activate PLB\n\n-   Muster equipment: portable VHF, pyrotechnics, casualty care kit,\n    torch, GPS\n\n**Entering the liferaft:**\n\n-   Pull the painter to activate\n\n-   Right the raft if it inflates inverted\n\n-   Enter feet first — aim to stay dry (climb down from vessel if\n    possible)\n\n-   Stabilise the raft by distributing crew weight evenly\n\n-   Confirm all crew accounted for\n\n-   If the vessel is in immediate danger of sinking or is on fire, cut\n    the painter\n\n-   Stream the drogue, close the entrance, maintain the raft\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, pp.111 — 112; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.1c, pp.83 — 84*\n\n**Surviving in Cold Water**\n\nIf you enter the water (intentionally through abandonment or\nunintentionally through MOB), follow these rules:\n\n-   Close all wrist and ankle cuffs, zips, collar, and hood. Helmet\n    visor DOWN\n\n-   Inflate your lifejacket fully\n\n-   Enter the water slowly to minimise the effects of cold-water shock\n — do NOT swim until your breathing has stabilised\n\n-   If alone, adopt the HELP position (Heat Escape Lessening Position)\n — draw your knees up to your chest, cross your arms across your\n    chest, keep still\n\n-   If there is more than one of you, form a tight huddle ring — \n    conserves heat, maintains morale, creates a larger target for\n    searchers\n\n-   Only use pyrotechnics if you think you are close enough to land or\n    shipping to be seen — fire in pairs in close succession\n\n-   Activate PLB\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 2, p.112; TP-OCF-02, Task 1.6.1d, pp.84 — 85*\n\n**1.7.1 PYROTECHNICS**\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 12. Identify all flare types carried on the A85, their purpose,       |\n|     location, and how to fire them                                    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 13. Know what PPE to wear and what to do if a flare misfires          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nPyrotechnics are taught in full in the Shore Crew Stage 2 guide. As\nafloat crew, you now need to be able to use them from the boat in\noperational conditions. The key difference is that you may be firing\nflares from a moving, unstable platform in the dark, potentially while\ninjured or in the water.\n\n  **Flare Type**    **Purpose**       **Key Details**\n\n  Personal          Distress          Stowed on lifejacket. Dual purpose:\n  day/night flare   signalling from   red flare one end, orange smoke the\n                    lifejacket        other. Burns approx. 20 seconds per\n                                      end\n\n  Red hand-held     Short-range       Self-oxygenating (burns in water).\n  flare             distress and      Fire from downwind at full arm's\n                    location          length. Burns approx. 60 seconds\n\n  White rocket      Illumination and  Reaches 300m\n\n*Source: Safe to Go on a Service Teaching Guide*",
  "3.1.1": "### 3.1.1 LAUNCH PROCEDURES (AFLOAT CREW)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 14. Embark the SAR unit safely and unaided                            |\n|                                                                       |\n| 15. Know the correct signals for launch procedures (hand, VHF,        |\n|     whistle, horn)                                                    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 16. Understand the hazards of launch from the boat crew's perspective |\n|                                                                       |\n| 17. Know what to do if launch equipment fails                         |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nAs afloat crew, your launch experience is fundamentally different from\nshore crew. You are ON the boat during launch — on the DoDo carriage\nbeing towed across the beach by a tractor. You must be correctly seated\nbefore the vehicle moves, and you must not attempt to disembark while\nthe rig is in transit.\n\n**Embarkation**\n\n-   Board the boat safely and unaided — maintain three points of\n    contact at all times\n\n-   Use designated embarkation points as per the SOP and LOP\n\n-   Hazards: falls, slips, entanglement, height — ensure ladder is\n    footed and secured\n\n-   Once aboard, position yourself away from hazards, visible to those\n    overseeing operations, ideally seated with good handholds\n\n-   Remain seated while the rig is in transit. Do not attempt to\n    disembark unless a halt has been called\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.1.1a, pp.100 — 101; TP-LB-01, Activity 3, p.133*\n\n**Pre-Launch Checks (from the boat)**\n\nBefore launch, you should have completed: briefing received (SMEAC),\nrole and hazards understood, equipment prepared, hatches closed, charger\ndisconnected, battery isolators ON, navigation aids powered up (SIMS,\nradar, charts available). At Littlestone: A-frame raised, DoDo water\npipes connected, VHF comms on CH31 with tractor.\n\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 3, p.32; Littlestone B-Class Launch & Recovery LOP V1.0, p.2*\n\n**If Equipment Fails During Launch**\n\n-   Notify the Head Launcher or Helm immediately\n\n-   Carry out any tasks as directed by the person in charge\n\n-   Failure may require alternative launch methods, or the coordinating\n    authority must be informed and a flank station asset activated\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.1.1a, p.101*\n\n*Source: Safe to Go on a Service Teaching Guide*",
  "3.1.2": "### 3.1.2 RECOVERY PROCEDURES (AFLOAT CREW)\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 18. Prepare the boat and equipment for recovery                       |\n|                                                                       |\n| 19. Assist with stern, net, and beach recovery from the boat          |\n|                                                                       |\n| 20. Disembark safely and unaided                                      |\n|                                                                       |\n| 21. Conduct post-recovery checks and make the boat ready for service  |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nRecovery is the most hazardous part of the operation from the boat\ncrew's perspective. You are approaching a moving carriage in surf\nconditions, or driving into a net at speed. Your role is to follow the\nhelm's instructions precisely, prepare recovery equipment as directed,\nand be ready for the boat to come to a sudden stop.\n\n**Post-Recovery Duties**\n\nAfter recovery at Littlestone, you will be directed by the Head\nLauncher:\n\n-   Flush engines with fresh water (salt water corrodes aluminium\n    cooling passages)\n\n-   Washdown the boat\n\n-   Refuel — PPE for refuelling: eye protection, coveralls, disposable\n    gloves. Precautions: fire, naked lights, spillage, restricted\n    access, vapour, suitable fire extinguishers to hand\n\n-   Report any defective equipment to the person in charge\n\n-   Clean and re-stow all used equipment\n\n-   Report refuelled and ready for service to the LA and Coastguard\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 3.1.2b, pp.105 — 106; TP-LB-23, Activity 3, p.36*\n\n*Source: Safe to Go on a Service Teaching Guide*",
  "4.1.1": "### 4.1.1 LOOKOUT\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 22. Maintain an effective lookout using the SCAN — FOCUS — SCAN         |\n|     technique                                                         |\n|                                                                       |\n| 23. Use binoculars, searchlights, and image intensifiers correctly    |\n|                                                                       |\n| 24. Understand night vision: how to develop it, how to preserve it,   |\n|     and how to lose it                                                |\n|                                                                       |\n| 25. Recognise visual distress signals                                 |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n:::info\nThis module covers essential knowledge for your OCF training pathway. Study the content thoroughly and test yourself with the assessment questions.\n:::\n\n\nLookout is the most fundamental duty of every crew member afloat. IRPCS\nRule 5 requires that every vessel maintains a proper lookout by all\navailable means appropriate to the conditions. On the A85, with a crew\nof 3 or 4, everyone who is not helming or navigating is a lookout.\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.1.1a, p.134*\n\n**The SCAN — FOCUS — SCAN Technique**\n\nVisual scanning is a systematic step-by-step method. It ensures\ncasualties are detected as quickly and from the greatest distance as\npossible, while reducing eye fatigue:\n\n-   Scan in segments of 10 — 15 degrees — this allows your eyes to\n    register objects within an 8-degree radius around the focused\n    position\n\n-   At each segment: SCAN the area, FOCUS on it briefly, then SCAN on to\n    the next segment\n\n-   Each crew member should be given a specific sector to scan (e.g.\n    port bow to port midships)\n\n-   Link your scanning speed to the speed of the boat — faster boat\n    speed means you must scan faster\n\n-   Spray and wind affect lookout vision — RNLI-issued sunglasses are\n    recommended in bright daylight or high-glare conditions\n\n-   For daylight searches, look AWAY from the sun where possible — \n    less glare, better contrast on coloured objects\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 5, pp.241 — 242; TP-LB-23, Activity 5, pp.52 — 53*\n\n**Combating Fatigue and Boredom**\n\nProlonged scanning causes fatigue and boredom which degrade your\neffectiveness. After extended scanning in low-contrast conditions, your\neyes tend to focus short of where you think you are looking. To counter\nthis:\n\n-   Periodically focus on an object closer to you to reset your eye\n    focus\n\n-   Rotate lookout positions and roles at regular intervals (recommended\n    every 30 minutes)\n\n-   Do NOT scan with binoculars — use your eyes first, then binoculars\n    only to focus on a spotted object\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 5, p.242; TP-OCF-03, Session Plan: SAR, p.65*\n\n**Night Vision**\n\nYour eyes take up to 40 minutes to fully adapt to darkness, but only\nseconds to lose that adaptation. At night, your peripheral vision works\nbetter than your central vision — objects may actually seem to\ndisappear when you look directly at them. Instead, look slightly above\nor to the side.\n\n-   Reduce background lighting on the boat to the minimum needed for\n    safety\n\n-   Use the red chart light under the crew console (not white light) for\n    reading charts\n\n-   If searchlights, spotlights, or illumination flares are used, close\n    one eye — when the light passes, the eye that remained\n    dark-adapted will still allow you to see\n\n-   In night searches, weak lights are detectable at the edge of your\n    vision, not at your point of focus — scan slightly higher than the\n    horizon and be alert for distant flares\n\n*Source: TP-LB-01, Activity 5, p.242; TP-LB-23, Activity 5, p.53*\n\n**Search Equipment on the A85**\n\n  **Equipment**   **Location on    **Use**           **Limitations**\n                  A85**                              \n\n  Binoculars      Under crew seats Focus on and      Narrow field of\n                  (if carried)     identify an       vision. Must be\n                                   object already    adjusted per operator.\n                                   spotted unaided   Not for primary\n                                                     scanning\n\n  Image           Under crew seats Night/low-light   Limited field of\n  intensifier     (if carried)     search.           vision. Battery life.\n  (NVD)                            Intensifies       Dangerous if directed\n                                   ambient light     at bright lights. Use\n                                                     searchlight from\n                                                     behind/above the\n                                                     operator's field of\n                                                     view\n\n  Searchlights    Under crew seats Illumination at   Glare in fog/mist.\n  (x2 portable)   2 and 3. Four    night             Reduced effectiveness\n                  sockets: two on                    against shore\n                  helm console                       backlighting. NEVER\n                  front, two at                      direct at crew or helm\n                  crew seats — destroys night\n                                                     vision\n\n  White parachute 3 under each     Illumination (NOT Disrupts night vision.\n  flares (x6)     side of crew     distress).        Limited numbers. Short\n                  seats            Collision         burn time (\\~30 sec).\n                                   avoidance         Do not use if\n                                                     helicopter operating\n                                                     in area\n*Source: TP-LB-23, Activity 5, pp.52 — 54; TP-OCF-02, Task 5.1.1a, p.194*\n\n**Visual Distress Signals to Watch For**\n\n-   Red parachute or hand-held flares\n\n-   Orange smoke\n\n-   Raising and lowering of arms repeatedly\n\n-   Any light or sound signal that appears distressed or abnormal\n\n*Source: TP-OCF-02, Task 4.1.1a, p.134*\n\n*Source: Safe to Go on a Service Teaching Guide*",
  "CC.1": "## Casualty Care\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| **WHAT YOU'LL LEARN**                                                 |\n|                                                                       |\n| 1.  Assess a casualty using the DR ABC primary survey                 |\n| 2.  Perform CPR correctly and use an AED                              |\n| 3.  Manage bleeding, shock, hypothermia, and drowning                 |\n| 4.  Operate the A85's casualty care equipment including oxygen and Entonox |\n| 5.  Understand hydrostatic squeeze and post-rescue collapse           |\n| 6.  Know the qualification pathway and currency requirements          |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\n### The Primary Survey\n\nThe primary survey is the first thing you do with any casualty. It follows a strict sequence — each step must be completed before moving to the next.\n\n:::acronym DR ABC\nD — **Danger** — Check for danger to yourself, bystanders, and the casualty. Do not become a casualty yourself\nR — **Response** — Is the casualty responsive? Tap their shoulders and ask loudly 'Are you alright?'\nA — **Airway** — Open the airway: tilt the head back and lift the chin. Check for obstructions and clear them\nB — **Breathing** — Look, listen, and feel for **normal** breathing for **up to 10 seconds**\nC — **Circulation** — Check for signs of severe bleeding. Control any life-threatening bleeding immediately\n:::\n\n:::warning\nIf the casualty is **not breathing normally** after opening the airway, call for help immediately and begin CPR. Do not delay — every second counts.\n:::\n\n### CPR (Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation)\n\n:::fact CPR RATIO\n**30 chest compressions** followed by **2 rescue breaths**, repeated continuously until help arrives, the casualty starts breathing, or you become physically unable to continue.\n:::\n\n- Compressions should be at least **5cm deep** at a rate of **100–120 per minute**\n- Allow the chest to fully recoil between compressions\n- Minimise interruptions — hands-off time should be kept to an absolute minimum\n- Where available, use a **pocket mask** or **bag valve mask** for rescue breaths\n- If an **AED** is available, switch it on and follow its voice instructions as soon as possible — do not wait\n\n:::memory\n**CPR rhythm**: Push hard, push fast — think of the beat of *Stayin' Alive* by the Bee Gees (approximately 104 BPM). 30 compressions, 2 breaths, repeat.\n:::\n\n### Managing Bleeding\n\n:::steps\n1. Apply **direct pressure** to the wound using a dressing or clean cloth\n2. If blood soaks through, **apply another dressing on top** — do NOT remove the first one, as this disturbs clotting\n3. **Elevate** the injured limb above the level of the heart where possible\n4. If bleeding cannot be controlled with direct pressure, consider a **tourniquet** as a last resort\n5. Call for medical assistance — monitor the casualty for signs of shock\n:::\n\n### Recognising and Treating Shock\n\nShock occurs when the circulatory system fails to deliver enough blood to the body's tissues. It is a life-threatening condition.\n\n:::fact SIGNS OF SHOCK\n**Pale, cold, clammy skin** · **Rapid, weak pulse** · **Rapid, shallow breathing** · **Nausea and dizziness** · **Confusion or altered consciousness** · **Thirst** · **Grey-blue skin colouration (cyanosis)**\n:::\n\n**Treatment:**\n- Lay the casualty down on their back\n- Elevate their legs above the level of their heart (if no leg injury)\n- Keep them warm with blankets or the **orange survival bag**\n- Loosen any tight clothing\n- Monitor their condition continuously\n- **Do not give food or drink**\n- Reassure the casualty — anxiety worsens shock\n\n### Hypothermia and Cold Water Casualties\n\n:::info\nA casualty recovered from cold water may appear stable but is at extreme risk of **post-rescue collapse**. Handle all hypothermic casualties with exceptional care.\n:::\n\n#### Hydrostatic Squeeze\n\nWhen a person is immersed in water up to their neck, water pressure compresses blood vessels in the limbs and abdomen, pushing blood towards the heart and core. This maintains blood pressure to the brain and vital organs while in the water.\n\n#### Post-Rescue Collapse (Circum-Rescue Collapse)\n\nWhen the casualty is removed from the water, the hydrostatic squeeze is suddenly released. Blood rushes back into the limbs, and blood pressure to the heart and brain drops catastrophically.\n\n:::warning\nA person who was **conscious and talking in the water** can lose consciousness, suffer cardiac arrest, and die within minutes of being pulled out. This is why **horizontal recovery** is essential for hypothermic casualties.\n:::\n\n**Why horizontal recovery matters:**\n- Vertical lifting allows gravity to compound the loss of hydrostatic squeeze\n- Blood pools in the legs, starving the heart and brain\n- The **double strop method** (one under arms, one under knees) recovers the casualty more horizontally\n- The **Jason's Cradle** provides full horizontal recovery from the water\n\n### The Recovery Position\n\nIf a casualty is **breathing normally** but **unconscious**, place them in the recovery position:\n\n:::steps\n1. Kneel beside the casualty\n2. Place the arm nearest to you at a right angle to their body, elbow bent, palm facing up\n3. Bring the far arm across the chest and hold the back of their hand against the cheek nearest to you\n4. Grab the far knee and pull it up, keeping the foot flat on the ground\n5. Pull the knee towards you to roll the casualty onto their side\n6. Tilt the head back to maintain an **open airway**\n7. Adjust the upper leg so the hip and knee are both at right angles\n8. Monitor breathing continuously — be prepared to start CPR if breathing stops\n:::\n\n:::warning\n**Do NOT place a casualty with a suspected spinal injury in the recovery position** unless their airway is at immediate risk and you cannot maintain it by other means. Use a **jaw thrust** instead of head tilt to open the airway.\n:::\n\n### Equipment on the Atlantic 85\n\n| **Item** | **Location** | **Purpose** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Oxygen delivery system | Casualty Care Bag | Supplemental oxygen for breathing casualties |\n| Entonox (pain relief gas) | Casualty Care Bag | Self-administered pain relief — casualty holds mask and breathes normally |\n| AED | Casualty Care Bag | Automated external defibrillator for cardiac arrest |\n| Wound dressings and bandages | Casualty Care Bag | Wound management and bleeding control |\n| Cervical collars | Under crew seat 4 | Spinal immobilisation |\n| PS1 stretcher | Port side of A-frame | Orange basket stretcher for casualty transport |\n| Survivor lifejackets | Under crew seat 4 | Fit to any casualty recovered from the water |\n| Orange survival bag + balaclava | Under crew seat 4 | Hypothermia prevention — protect from exposure |\n| Nitrile gloves | Casualty Care Bag | Infection control — always wear when handling casualties |\n| Clinical waste bags (YELLOW) | Casualty Care Bag | Disposal of contaminated materials |\n\n:::warning\nThe **PS1 stretcher will NOT be lifted by any SAR helicopter**. Only the helicopter's own basket stretcher is used for winching. Plan accordingly if helicopter evacuation is needed.\n:::\n\n### Fitting a Casualty Lifejacket\n\nFit a **survivor lifejacket** to every casualty recovered from the water or at risk of entering it. The lifejacket protects the casualty's airway and prevents drowning if they are lost overboard. Ensure all straps are correctly adjusted and the crutch strap is fastened to prevent the lifejacket riding up.\n\n### The Orange Survival Bag\n\nThe orange survival bag and balaclava are used to **protect the casualty from exposure and further heat loss**. Wrap the casualty as soon as practical after recovery and initial assessment. Even in summer, wet casualties lose heat rapidly, especially on a moving boat with wind chill.\n\n### Qualification Pathway\n\n| **Qualification** | **Validity** | **Notes** |\n|---|---|---|\n| First Aid 1 (eLearning) | 3 years | Foundation level — required for all crew |\n| First Aid 2 (course or STCW equivalent) | 5 years | Supersedes First Aid 1 when in date |\n| Casualty Care (course) | 3 years | Supersedes both First Aid 1 and First Aid 2 when in date |\n\n### Decontamination After Casualty Care\n\nAfter handling any casualty, you must follow the decontamination procedure:\n- **Minor external contamination**: clean PPE with 1000ppm Chemgene solution, then rinse thoroughly\n- **Moderate contamination**: soak in 10,000ppm Chemgene for 5 minutes, then rinse thoroughly\n- **Heavy contamination** (soaked with bodily fluids): do NOT attempt to clean — contact Regional Business Support Team for clinical waste disposal within 48 hours\n- Clinical waste goes in **yellow bags** found in the casualty care kits\n\n:::fact KEY NUMBERS TO REMEMBER\n**30:2** — CPR ratio (compressions to breaths)\n**10 seconds** — maximum time to check for breathing\n**3 years** — First Aid 1 validity\n**5 years** — First Aid 2 validity\n**Yellow** — colour of clinical waste bags\n:::\n"
};
